# The Returned-sense: an eerie, on-theme perception the dead-touched player gets on first sight of each soul,
# if their Wisdom-clarity (10 + WIS mod) meets the moment's DC. It reveals what the living can't see.
NPC_SENSE = {
    "market.sable": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(Your dead-touched senses sweep her table and recoil — there is no holiness in a single bone or thread of it. And yet her hands, folding the knots, are warm with something realer than any relic: she has buried more of this ward than the gravediggers have, and grieved every one of them into the thread she sells. The fraud is the kindest thing in this market.)*"},
    "market.bram": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The Wall left its chill in your marrow, and it answers the cold this man carries: three squads' worth of the recently, violently dead are pressed against his back like wet wool, patient, unblaming. He does not know they followed him home from the causeway. You do. They are not here for revenge. They are here to see whether he stops sending more.)*"},
    "market.pip": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(Some Returned see the almost-dead the way the living see candle-flames. The girl burns bright and quick and furious — but there is a second flame tethered to hers, fainter, somewhere close and low to the ground, and it is *guttering.* A child, smaller than this one. Sick past what a stolen copper mends. The thing she is really stealing for, running out of wick.)*"},
    "market.calix": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(Your dead-touched senses reach the young priest and recoil from what's already begun in him: the Wall's cold has crept up past his knees, grey and patient, the way frost takes a windowpane from the edges in. He has stood the causeway too long. A man becomes what he guards, if he guards it without love — and Calix has run clean out of love for his post. Another year of watching the Faithless go in, and he'll be standing on the wrong side of his own Wall, and not remember crossing.)*"},
    "market.wren": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You don't have to look for the mark. It *finds* you — cold light pouring off her like breath off a winter river, a brand the harvesters laid on her soul that the living can't see and she can only feel. Days. Fewer than she's letting herself count. She is godless and gentle and entirely without sin, and she has been measured for a wall, and she is buying apples because the apples are sweet and the apples are *now.*)*"},
    "market.tallow": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You reach for the smiling man's soul the way you'd reach into a coat you expect to be full — and your senses close on *almost nothing.* He has spent himself a coin at a time, a name at a time, year on year, until what's left would barely fill a thimble. He thinks his tithes and his service have bought him safety. They've only hollowed him faster. The Wall is not reaching for him later, with the rest. It is reaching for him *now*, and the cold has already found his fingers — he simply mistakes it for the draught off the river.)*"},
    "market.joss": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You barely have to reach at all; the madman's soul is *standing open*, like a door left wide in winter. He has been to the edge of the Wall and pressed his face to it and listened, and a sliver of the cold came home in him and never left — the same sliver that lives in you. He is not raving at nothing. He is raving at the *exact* thing you are. Of every soul in this square, he is the one who will believe every word you'd never dare say aloud — because he already heard it, in the stone, in a voice he loved.)*"},
    "reed.cassian": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The river's cold is your cold, and it answers the old boatman's like a tuning-fork: he is not quite among the living anymore. Forty years of ferrying has worn him thin as a coin rubbed smooth, half his soul already paid downstream to the water he serves. He does not know he is dying by inches into his own river. He thinks it is just the damp in his knees. The oar in his hands has rowed thirteen thousand souls to the mist, and the thirteen-thousand-and-first will be him, and he has no idea, and some part of him is so very tired that it would be a mercy.)*"},
    "reed.vharn": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You reach for the Measurer's soul and find it walled — not hollow like Tallow's, but *fortified*, every doubt bricked up behind liturgy, a cell she built around her own conscience and threw away the key to. And yet the cold gets in. There, behind the third course of bricks: three hundred and eleven faces she will not let herself count, and one of them, freshest, has an apple in its hand. The wall around her heart is exactly as strong as the Wall she serves — which is to say, it holds against everyone but the one soul stubborn enough to keep saying a name.)*"},
    "reed.wren": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(The mark blazes off her even brighter here, this close to the stone — but your dead-touched sense reads something the brand can't hide: she is not ready. Whatever she tells herself, whatever brave arithmetic she's done in the cold water, the living animal of her is *clinging*, white-knuckled, to every small sweet now it can find — the apple, the cold on her ankles, the sound of your boots on the shingle. She came here to end it. Her own soul is screaming, in a voice only you can hear, that it is not time, it is not time, it is not time.)*"},
    "reed.reedwife": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You don't reach for her; she is already the same cold as you, and recognition passes between you like current through water. Four hundred years she has abided in the doorway you walked all the way through — a soul that refused the Wall and let the river catch it on the threshold, neither in nor back, just *held*, in the green and the patience. She is lonelier than anything you have ever touched. She is also, you realise with a small private vertigo, what you might have been, had you flinched at the door. There but for the turning-around go you.)*"},
    "under.pip": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The fierce small flame you saw in the market burns lower now — not from sickness, but from sheer exhaustion, days of standing a watch no nine-year-old should ever stand. Your dead-touched sense reads the truth she's hiding even from herself: she is not afraid that her brother will die. She has already, somewhere behind the fists, accepted it. What she is terrified of is the morning *after* — the first dawn in her whole life with no small reason to be careful, no one smaller than herself to keep fed, nothing left to steal *for.* The boy is her tether to the world as surely as she is his. Pull one loose and the other drifts.)*"},
    "under.wick": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You don't have to reach. The little flame you felt all the way from the market is *here*, close enough to warm your dead hands if it had any warmth left to give, and it is so nearly out that looking at it directly feels like an intrusion. Days. Perhaps fewer. But your sense reads something else under the guttering, and it stops you cold: the boy is not *clinging* the way Wren clung at the water. He has already, quietly, with a child's terrible practicality, let *go* — and the only thread still tethering him here is not fear of the dark. It is the other small flame beside his, the fierce bright furious one, and the certainty that it cannot survive without something to burn *for.*)*"},
    "under.knotwife": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(Your dead-touched senses settle over the blind weaver and find, to your surprise, no cold creeping in her at all — she is fully, stubbornly alive, more alive than half the breathing souls in the market above. But the *loom* — the loom is another matter. Every banner on it hums faintly against your perception, each thread a name spoken by someone who refused to let it become nothing, and woven through the oldest and deepest of them, like a splinter under a fingernail, is a single knotted *signature* that does not belong: a living hand's mark, four centuries old, tying this whole drowned machine together. She has been weaving *around* it her entire life, unable to see it, *feeling* for the one visitor who could.)*"},
    "lt.hale": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You reach for the Warden and recoil from how far the cold has already come into him — past the knees, the sense the market gave you of Brother Calix made flesh and then left out in it for four more years. He is not dying so much as *freezing into the post*, becoming the thing he guards a degree at a time. But under the frost there is still a man, and the man is *screaming*, very quietly, behind a parade-ground face, and what he is screaming is *let me off this watch before I forget I was ever warm.*)*"},
    "lt.esuele": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You don't have to reach. You are the same cold as the whole Wall, and it knows you — ten thousand faces turn a fraction toward the one of their own that *got away.* But this one, level with your eyes, is nearly *gone*: a soul worn down to a thimbleful, the oldest memories already taken by the stone, only the sharpest few left — a mother's hands, the smell of wool, the word *no.* Your sense reads the cruelty exactly: it is not pain that unmakes the Mortared. It is *erasure*, a piece at a time, oldest first, until a face that was a *who* no longer knows it. And this one is *days* of forgetting from the bottom.)*"},
    "lt.goodwin": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(Your sense brushes the cheerful waiting man and finds — gently, almost comically — a soul that does not yet know it has died. No cold creeps in him because he is already, wholly, on the far side of it; he simply hasn't noticed, the way a sleeper hasn't noticed the dream. He is not marked, not mortared, not dissolving — only *waiting*, with a terrible patient faith, on a rock at the edge of the afterlife, for a boat the Choir promised and was never going to send. The kindest and cruellest thing you could do to him is the same thing: tell him the truth.)*"},
    "city.mab": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You reach for the brass-ringed keep and find her warm, alive, and quietly *unafraid* of you in a way almost nobody is — because some part of Mab made her peace with the cold a long time ago. Under the gossip and the grin your sense reads four decades of a different kind of weight: every Faithless regular who drank at her bar and then went up the causeway and never came down, each one a cup she still sets out, unbidden, on the longest night. She is not a rumour-mill. She is a *memorial* that happens to serve ale, and she has been waiting, without knowing it, for a soul who could tell her the cups meant something.)*"},
    "city.dace": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The cold in your marrow meets a cold of a different kind in the sellsword — not the Wall's, but the lifelong chill of the Faithless who has never once been able to forget the empty space waiting for her in the stone. Your sense reads under the lazy menace to the truth she fights with: ten years of selling the only thing she owns to people she despises, hoarding a single unspent *yes* for a fight that would be worth it, and a creeping fear that the fight will never come and she'll die a blade-for-hire with the yes still in her, walking up the causeway like all the rest. She is not looking for an employer. She is looking for a reason. And she has just seen one walk into her square.)*"},
    "city.pell": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(Your sense settles over the neat clerk and recoils — not from cold, but from a vast and meticulous *emptiness*, a soul that has filed itself away as thoroughly as it files everyone else. There is no cruelty in him, which is the horror of it; there is only the *system*, and a small frightened man who long ago decided that to keep from being filed he would become the one who holds the pen. But your sense finds the splinter he can't: he is *unbought* too. Pell has no god either. He serves the machine that will, in the end, measure *him* — and on some buried ledger-line he knows it, and writes faster, as if a long enough list might somehow leave his own name off it.)*"},
    "ch.crake": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the old gravedigger in his cell and find, astonishingly, the most *settled* soul you have touched on this whole causeway — warmer than half the living, utterly without the cold dread that rots the rest. Sixty years of burying the marked has worn every fear smooth; he has made his peace so completely that your dead-touched sense slides off him like water off oiled leather. But under the peace there is one small unhealed thing, a single question he has carried spadeful by spadeful for six decades and never been able to answer: *was any of it real, or did I just bury coats?* He is the one soul here who is not afraid to die. He is only afraid he wasted his life laying the dead straight for nothing.)*"},
    "ch.tallow": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(The same reading you took in the market, only worse for the nearness: the smiling man's soul is a *thimble*, spent almost to the bottom, the cold already past his wrists. But here, in the Choir's own house, your sense catches what the market hid — he *knows.* Somewhere under the pleasant mask, Goodman Tallow has worked out that every soul he files buys him not safety but a *faster* spending, and he does it anyway, because being the hand that holds the pen is the only thing that ever made a forgettable man *felt.* He would rather be cold and seen than warm and forgotten. The Wall will take him very soon, and he will smile the whole way, because the smiling is the last thing he has that anyone *looks* at.)*"},
    "ch.mereth": {"dc": 15, "text": "*(You reach for the High Measurer and meet a soul like a vault door — sealed, deliberate, every feeling filed and shelved and locked, the most disciplined interior you have ever touched. She is alive, fully, no cold in her at all; she has not spent herself like Tallow, because she never let herself *care* enough to spend. And that is the horror and the tragedy of her both: she made herself a perfect bookkeeper by *amputating* the part that could be pulled on, thirty years ago, on purpose, and the scar tissue is the strongest thing in the room. But your sense finds the one live nerve she could not cut out — buried twenty years deep, a single name she still remembers because the mother would not stop coming to the door: *Esuele.* She has spent three decades not-feeling ten thousand souls, and the effort of not-feeling that *one* is the only thing in her that is still, quietly, screaming.)*"},
    "hearth.fire": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You hold your dead-cold hands to the flames and feel, as always, the warmth refuse them at the wrist — but tonight your sense turns inward instead of out, and reads the only soul left to read: your own. There is the cold the Wall left in you, yes, the door that swings both ways. But banked beneath it, like the fire's steady heart, there is something the harvest did not take and the stone could not keep: the day's worth of souls you carried out, each one a small warm coal you are, without quite meaning to, keeping alight. You are not only the thing the Wall fears. You are also, it seems, the thing it keeps losing souls to. Rest. Even a door is allowed to be warm at its own fire.)*"},
    "hearth.dace": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The cold in your marrow meets the lifelong chill in the sellsword and finds it, tonight, a little warmer than the Lamplit Quarter left it. The empty space in the Wall still waits for her — she is Faithless, it always will — but your sense reads something laid down beside the old grief now: a *yes*, spent at last, and a back she has decided to guard, and the dangerous, fragile beginnings of *trust* in a soul who keeps its small promises. She put her sword in the dirt tonight. For Dace Iron, that is a thing nearer to prayer than anything a god ever got from her.)*"},
    "hearth.wren": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(The mark is still on her — a coin of winter under the breastbone, exactly where she says — and your dead-touched sense will not pretend otherwise; the Choir's brand does not lift because a girl chose the fire over the water. But around it now there is a stubborn, growing warmth the cold cannot reach, a future being lived on purpose and out of spite, every stolen breath a small defeat for the thing that measured her. She is proof, sitting at a fire, eating an apple. Of all the things you carried off the causeway, she is the one that warms your cold hands most.)*"},
    "hearth.sparrow": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the thief at the fire's edge and find a soul mid-transformation, caught in the act of becoming someone it had given up on being. The professional appetite is still there — quick, bright, restless — but the thing your sense reads under it tonight is *integration*: for forty years this soul kept its proud hands and its ashamed jobs in separate pockets so they'd never meet, a person split clean down the middle, and something happened in that archive that *introduced them.* You watch the two halves settle into one for the first time — the thief who can open any door, pointed at last at doors worth opening — and your sense reads no calculation in it, only the wary, stunned warmth of a soul that spent its whole existence outside the circle of other people's fires, casing them, and has just been waved *in* to one. The old wariness still checks the exits. But it is, degree by degree, forgetting to. She is not a reformed criminal. She is a whole person, finally, and the wholeness is so new she keeps reaching to make sure it's still there, like a coin she can't believe she gets to keep.)*"},
    "hearth.sennet": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the cartographer at the fire and find the thing you most hoped for and least expected: the cold is *backing out* of them. Not gone — four fingers' worth is keeps, and the deep-joint slowness is permanent — but the *creeping* edge-cold, the year-a-survey frost that was taking them a degree at a time, has *stopped advancing*, because they are not standing at the edges anymore; they are sitting at your fire, drawing the deep country from your reports instead of freezing it into their own marrow. Your sense reads a soul that was walking, steadily, toward your country — and has, for the first time in thirty years, *turned around* and started walking back toward the warm. You did not just recruit a surveyor. You reached into the Wall's slow harvest and pulled one more soul off the long grey road. They will draw maps by firelight now, for years they had already written off. The cold in them is your cold. It is the first time you have ever watched it *recede.*)*"},
    "hearth.pip": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You reach gently for the child and find — for the first time since the market — the fierce small flame burning *easy*, not guttering, not braced, just warm. The second flame that was so nearly out is steadier too, somewhere close and mending. Your sense reads under the old hunted watchfulness to the thing six years of street stamped out and one fire is, impossibly, rekindling: the simple animal knowledge that someone else is keeping watch, and she is allowed, tonight, to close both eyes. It is a very small thing. It is, you suspect, the whole of what salvation actually is.)*"},
    "ald.aldric": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You reach for the grey man and recoil from the sheer *mass* of cold in him — not the Wall's chill creeping in from outside, like the others, but a cold he has *swallowed*, a whole frozen sea of it held behind a dam of pure will. He is alive, and means to stay so until the work is done, but he has been *living beside the dead* so long that he has gone half-translucent to your sight, a man keeping vigil at the exact border you crossed. And there — the thing that stops your breath — your sense follows the cold to its source and finds it does not radiate *from* him at all. It radiates from the chair beside him. He thinks he carries his daughter's memory. He is carrying his daughter. He simply cannot see her. You can.)*"},
    "ald.wessa": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The herald is warm, living, unspent — but your sense reads the particular strain of a soul standing watch over something it loves and fears in equal measure. She has hitched her whole young life to a great man's terrible cause, and some buried, honest part of her is counting the days until he asks her to do the unforgivable, and rehearsing, over and over, a refusal she is terrified she won't have the nerve to give. She is not afraid of dying for him. She is afraid of *killing* for him, and finding she liked being *certain* enough to do it.)*"},
    "ald.eithne": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You do not reach for her. She is already your kind of cold, and she has been waiting — patient as only the dead can be — for a pair of eyes that could find her in the chair where she has sat, faded and unseen, for twenty years. Your sense needs no DC for this one; she *wants* to be perceived more than any soul you have ever touched. She is a thread snagged on her father's grief, a daughter who went into the Wall *looking* at the man she loved and left the looking-part of herself behind. She is not suffering. She is something worse: she is *lonely*, in the one chair in the world she refuses to leave, beside the one person who cannot tell she never left.)*"},
    "way.harbinger": {"dc": 16, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the robed nothing and it is like turning a candle on the night sky — your perception simply *falls into* it and keeps falling. There is no soul here to read, because it is not a soul: it is a *function* of one, an aspect, a single grey thought of an enormous bound mind reaching down a long cold arm to touch the road. But in the falling you brush, for one vertiginous instant, the *whole* of the thing behind it — and it is *tired*, in a way that has no bottom, the tiredness of a god who inherited a horror and has weighed every soul ground into it, one at a time, fairly, for three hundred years, hating every grain. It is not your enemy. It is the most *exhausted ally* you will ever almost have.)*"},
    "way.orin": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(Living, hard, unspent — but your sense reads the particular fracture of a true believer who has read her own scripture too closely. Justiciar Orin guards a god she still loves and an order she has come to suspect is rotten at the root, and she holds the two apart by sheer discipline, the way you'd hold apart two wires that must not touch. She is not afraid of you, or of dying. She is afraid that the next thing she learns will be the one that makes her sword change sides — and that she will be *glad* when it does.)*"},
    "way.doget": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the old farmer and find the rarest thing on the whole causeway: a soul entirely at peace, square-ledgered, beloved, dying gentle at the end of a long ordinary good life — a fair death, the kind the system was *supposed* to give everyone and gives only the lucky. There is no cold in him to answer yours. There is only a warmth going quietly out, content, and one small new grief he has just chosen to carry across for a godless neighbour the Wall took — the first weight he has ever picked up that wasn't his to bear, and the lightest he has ever felt for it.)*"},
    "thr.last": {"dc": 2, "text": "*(You do not reach for it. You cannot — there is no *across* to reach, because it is *you*, and your sense simply *closes the loop*, marrow to marrow, the way two mirrors face each other into infinity. The cold in it is your cold, run all the way down: a soul that walked this exact door, took the Crown, and spent two hundred years freezing into the very thing it broke the world to destroy. There is no DC. You know it the way you know your own name in the dark. And the most terrible thing your sense reads is not its *wrongness* — it is how *reasonable* every step that made it was, each one a *mercy*, each one a *just a little longer*, a road you could walk *right now* without once feeling yourself fall. It is not a warning you can *fight*. It is a warning you can only *out-love*.)*"},
    "thr.dace": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The bond you built at a fire stands at your shoulder at the literal edge of the world, and your sense reads it clear: she is *terrified* — not of the door, not of the dead, but of *you*, of what you might come back as — and she has decided, in the way Dace decides things, to stand here *anyway*, sword bare, amending a campfire promise into a vow to save you *and* stop you. The fear and the loyalty are the same size in her, perfectly balanced, and the balance is the strongest thing on this threshold. She is the variable your future self never had.)*"},
    "thr.sparrow": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the thief at the death-door and find the one soul in your party for whom this threshold is not a wall but a *workplace.* Where the living companions radiate the held-breath terror of bodies that know they cannot cross, the Sparrow reads cool, alert, *professional* — a dead and unbought soul standing before the best-made lock in creation, and your sense feels her doing the only thing she has ever truly trusted: casing it. But under the tradeswoman's calm your cold finds the deeper truth she'd never say at a job: she has spent forty years going where she was not allowed, alone, free, and empty — and now, at the literal end of the world, she has discovered she would rather be *yours*, this party's, *somebody's*, than free through any door there is. The exception the death-door makes for you is shaped like a Returned; your sense reads that a quick enough soul could slip through in your shadow — and that this one has already, quietly, decided she will, if you'll only let her, because the one prize she means to lift from the throne room of the dead is *you, brought back out of it.*)*"},
    "thr.sennet": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the cartographer at the threshold and read, layered over the old frostbite, a brand-new agony: this close to the door, the deep country is *pulling* at them the way it pulls at every living soul who strays too near — a slow, sweet, sideways drag toward the cold — and a surveyor who has spent thirty years learning to *want* the far bank is the least defended soul imaginable against that pull. Your sense reads the war in them plainly: every instinct they ever honed says *step through, measure it, fill the blank*, and the only counterweight is a thread of promises — Tibb, the wagon, the long number you bought them. They are not in danger of dying here. They are in danger of *walking in on purpose*, gladly, with a clear head and a steady hand, because to a cartographer of the dead the open door is not a horror but the *last unmapped mile.* Stand close. They need a living voice louder than the door.)*"},
    "thr.orin": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(The Justiciar stands with her oath spent and her blade bare and her whole trained certainty replaced by a single naked act of judgement, and your sense reads the vertigo of it: she has followed a counterexample to the end of the world and found *two* of it, and she is doing the bravest thing a soul of the order can do — choosing, with no doctrine and no rite and no superior, which of two identical souls to believe in. She came to learn if the order deserved guarding. She has decided it doesn't, and that *you* — the open one, the accompanied one — are what she guards instead.)*"},
    "nm.pawn": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the long thin merchant and find no soul at all in the ordinary sense — only an *appetite* given shape, a thing made of *patience* and *other people's unspent time*, slowly, slowly accreting toward the one thing it lacks and craves: a life of its own, a first-hand one, with a death at the end it gets to choose. It is not evil so much as *starving* in a way that has no bottom, and it is building itself a body a stolen decade at a time. The horror your sense reads is how *fair* it is. It pays. It says thank you. It is the only thing on the causeway that does.)*"},
    "nm.mnemo": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The keeper of the jars reads, to your sense, as a soul worn almost to transparency — and you understand at once that she is a customer who never left, who traded away her whole life to this place a piece at a time until only one memory remained, and who built a shop around that last warm jar so she would never have to be alone with the knowledge of what she spent. She grieves every memory she keeps because each one is proof of the trade that emptied her. She is the Night Market's warning, wearing an apron.)*"},
    "nm.regular": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the threadbare shade and find barely anything to hold — a habit, a cheer, a set of empty pockets where a soul used to be. It sold itself to this place trade by trade, beginning with a single grief it wanted to be rid of, and learned too late that the ache was the love, and the love was the self. It cannot leave because it sold the memory of the door, the memory of why it came, the memory of who it was grieving. It is what the Hunger looks like from the *inside*, mid-process, still smiling. It is also, your sense insists, still *someone* — for exactly as long as one other soul refuses to let it be no one.)*"},
    "vault.warden": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the great bronze head and find, behind the boredom and the bell-toll voice, a soul — an actual soul, bound into the metal so long ago it has half-forgotten it was ever anything else. It volunteered, once, thinking it an honour to guard. The binding made it a thing that asks; the centuries made it a thing that is bored; and the boredom, your sense reads with a chill, is just loneliness wearing armour. It has mortared a thousand clever souls into its walls not from cruelty but because none of them ever once saw the lonely person inside the lock. It does not want to be solved. It wants to be visited.)*"},
    "vault.pedant": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The half-stone scholar reads, to your sense, as a soul caught at the exact instant of its worst quality: pride, fossilised. He was clever and correct and so busy being both that he never noticed the riddle was never about being right. The stone took him from the boots up while he was still citing his sources. But under the petrified vanity there is a live and decent grief now — for the cage he never asked about, the person he never saw, the turn he spent on himself. He has had a very long time to become humble, and is most of the way there, which is the cruellest place to be: wise, and rooted to the spot.)*"},
    "vault.tithe": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the small soul in the alcove and your sense recoils from the slow horror of it: not a treasure, not a monster — a person, a lamp-lighter named Sela, taken as the living stake at the centre of a binding because a game needs something to be at risk. Centuries of clever strangers have come to win the door behind her and walked past the cage without once meeting her eyes, and she has begun, under all that looking-through, to believe she is what they called her — a thing, a tithe, a tenth — and to forget her own name. She is not dying. She is being slowly un-personed by inattention, which your sense knows for the truest face of the Hunger there is.)*"},
    "court.kelemvor": {"dc": 18, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the grey giant and it is like turning it on a *mountain that grieves* — vast past reading, an age deep, every soul ever weighed laid in him like strata. But your dead-touched sight, which the Wall sharpened precisely for this, finds the one thing the songs never tell: the Judge of the Dead is not cruel and is not free. He is a tired man grown enormous, bound to a Concord he loathes, *forbidden to witness* the very souls who most need it, and so lonely on his cold throne that the loneliness has calcified into something the living mistake for indifference. He has been waiting — bound, silent, unable even to ask — for one soul who could end his Wall without becoming it. He is the most powerful being you have ever stood before, and the most desperate to be *relieved.*)*"},
    "court.crown": {"dc": 20, "text": "*(You should not look at it with the sense. You know this the instant you do, because it looks *back*, and it is delighted to be seen. The Crown of Horns has no soul to read — it is the *absence* of one, shaped into a circlet, a hunger for a head — and your perception slides across it and finds only your own reflection, amplified, the exact pitch of every reason you ever had to believe you could be trusted with power. It is the Concord's cruelest joke: the means to free the dead, engineered so that whoever wields it becomes the next thing that needs freeing. It does not want to corrupt you. It wants to be *worn*, and it has never, in any age, failed to make that sound like your own best idea.)*"},
    "epi.chronicler": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the keeper of records and find a soul entirely without fear of you — rare, and steadying — because they have spent years writing your story and know exactly what kind of thing you are: not a monster, not a ghost, but a witness, the same trade as their own. There is no cold creeping in them. There is only the deep, patient warmth of someone whose whole vocation is refusing to let names become nothing — and a quiet, fierce hope, when they look at you, that the tally they keep will end well, because they have grown fond of its subject over the long years of the writing.)*"},
    "epi.wren": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the woman by the apple-tree and your sense, which has read her twice before — terrified at the water, warming at the fire — reads her now and very nearly weeps: she is *old*, and she is *whole*, and the coin of winter under her breastbone, the mark the Choir laid on her a lifetime ago, is *thawing* — slowly, from the outside in, as though the very Wall it grew from is being un-made somewhere far off by someone who never stopped bothering. She is the single clearest proof, in all the tally, that the road was worth walking: a marked soul who was measured for the stone, and instead grew old, and good, and warm, eating apples she planted herself.)*"},
    "epi.annet": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old midwife and find the same affront to the grey you read in the cellar, only now run gloriously to its end: a soul lit from within by decades of catching the living, the coals banked deeper and warmer than ever, and beside the oldest of them a whole new stratum — every child she caught in the years she was never supposed to have, each one a small steady flame she kindled out of stolen time. There is no Wall-cold in her at all; there never was. But your sense reads the thing the living can't: the babe asleep on her shoulder, and the four godless girls she trained, and the gaggle of children wearing names she chose — and understands that you did not save one midwife. You saved a *lineage* of catching, a warmth that propagates, a single un-walled soul who spent her reprieve seeding the whole causeway with proof that faith kept between people outlasts any Wall. She is the loudest answer in the tally to the question the saga keeps asking: what is a soul worth, that no god ever claimed? This one was worth hundreds. And she made sure everyone would know it.)*"},
    "epi.sparrow": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the thief years on and find a soul that has done the rarest thing the after allows: it changed its whole nature without losing its edge. The quick hands are quicker; the wariness has become *vigilance*, pointed outward now, at the cages of others. Your sense reads no hunger in her, no haunting, no fear of the warm door she has earned and postponed — only a vast, fierce *purpose* worn smooth by years of use. She steals people back. She trained a crew to do it. And the thing your cold finds, woven through all of it, is the lesson she keeps that the Wall never could: every soul she was *too late* for, carried not as guilt but as instruction, a list of locks she couldn't pick so the next Sparrow can. She is the living proof — though she is dead — that a soul pointed at the right trespass becomes something the cosmos has no cage for: a thief of death who steals only freedom, and gives it all away.)*"},
    "epi.dace": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the sellsword years on and find the chill of the Faithless still in her — the empty socket in the Wall still carved with her name, for she never took a god and never will — but the lifelong dread that used to freeze around it is simply gone, melted by something your cold reads as the rarest thing a mercenary ever finds: a cause spent freely. She hoarded one unspent yes for ten grey years, certain no fight was worth it; she spent it on you, and discovered the spending didn't empty her but filled her. Your sense reads a soul that turned a blade-for-hire into a shield-for-free, that has guarded more godless lives in the years after than it ended in all the ones before — and that waits for the Wall unafraid now, because it watched the one soul the Wall lost walk free, and reasons that if the stone lost one, it can lose her too. The loyalty in her is not a sellsword's. It is the one thing she never sold, given away at last for nothing, and worth more than every coin of the ten years before.)*"},
    "epi.orin": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You reach for the former justiciar and your dead-touched sense finds a soul that paid the highest price in the whole tally and counts it the best trade of its death: it traded a lifetime of certainties for one honest doubt at the edge of the world. Your cold reads no order in her now, no writ, no god — only the harder calm of a soul that followed a counterexample to its end and let it unmake everything, and found something truer underneath. She turned every skill the Choir gave her to guard the Wall against the Wall itself: a counter-justiciar, finding the unlawful reckonings, naming the forged writs, arguing the Faithless free in the order's own language. And your sense reads the thing she understood that no doctrine could teach her — that she chose you at the threshold not because you were the soul most likely to stay good, but because you were the one that doubted it would; that certainty is the fall and doubt is the safeguard; and that she stands ready still, watching, in case the day ever comes when the soul she chose needs choosing for, one last time — praying it never will, and meaning to be there if it does.)*"},
    "epi.sennet": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old cartographer and read the thing you watched begin at a campfire, now run all the way to its end: the Wall's cold, which was creeping into them a degree a survey the day you met, has *lost.* It never took them. They are old — genuinely, impossibly old, a soul that was measured for an edge and got a hearth instead — and the only chill left in them is the honest frost of four ruined fingers, not the grey advancing harvest you both once carried. Your sense reads no fear in them at all, only a vast settled warmth and one last bright filament of grief: that they could never do for you what you did for them, never reach into your marrow and pull the cold back out. So they did the one thing a cartographer can — they drew you a map home, true to the last reed, and pressed it into the final page of the atlas, against the day your own road runs back to the grey country. You are looking at the single clearest proof in all the tally that the Wall's harvest can be *reversed*: a soul walking, warm and grey-haired and finished, who was never supposed to leave the edge alive.)*"},
    "epi.pip": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(The fierce small flame you first felt guttering over a stolen copper burns now like a hearth that warms a whole house — because it does. Your sense reads a soul that took the one shared watch you stood for it and built a life out of multiplying it: a roof, a rota, eleven children who never have to keep both eyes open alone. There is no hunger in her, no bracing, no un-personing — only the steady, capacious warmth of someone who learned that safety is a thing you build between people, in turns, and then spent her whole grown life building it. She is what a single witnessed night becomes, given years: a witness factory.)*"},
    "wh.matron": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the grey Lady and find a soul frozen at the exact instant of its worst choice — not cruel, not wicked, only *unbearably* certain, a woman who has built an entire afterlife out of *counting* so she never has to *feel* the one night she chose the silver over her husband's hand. The cold in her is self-inflicted, a wall of bookkeeping against a single unsurvivable memory. But your sense finds the crack she can't: she has the *direction* of her waiting wrong. She believes she awaits an arrival. She is in fact refusing a departure. The whole weeping house is one woman, stuck, mistaking the door behind her for a door ahead.)*"},
    "wh.tam": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You reach for the little ghost and find — blessedly — no horror in him at all: a child's soul, bored rather than tormented, clear-eyed in the way only the un-guilty can be. He saw the truth on the very first night and has been trying to tell it ever since, and no grown-up will hear him, because a child's true thing counts for less than an adult's wrong one. Your sense reads the small, patient ache under the boredom: he is not afraid of the warm door at the top of the stairs. He simply will not go up it without his mother — and so he waits, good and still and stuck, holding the whole house's freedom hostage to a nine-year-old's entirely reasonable refusal to leave his mama behind.)*"},
    "wh.keeper": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(The housekeeper's shade reads, to your sense, as a soul caged by its own finest quality: loyalty. She has known the truth that would free this whole house since the night it burned — that the guard was latched, that the Lady is blameless — and forty years of service have made it *impossible* for her to say it, because a good housekeeper does not correct her mistress un-asked. Your sense finds the exhaustion under the duty, vast and aching: she stayed out of love, kept silent out of respect, and her love and respect became the very bars of the cage. She is praying, without quite letting herself form the words, for someone unbound by service to say the unkind kind thing she never could.)*"},
    "ci.sedge": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the washerwoman and find a soul being eaten alive from the inside — not by the cistern-thing directly, but by the particular horror it deals: she is losing the people she loves and cannot even grieve them, because the grief needs a face and a name to attach to, and those are exactly what the thing takes. Your sense reads the gap where a child used to be — a little dress she folds and weeps over and cannot place — and understands that this is the Hunger's truest cruelty, the one the Wall itself practises: it does not just take the dead, it takes the *missing*, so the living are left aching at a hole with nothing on the other end of it.)*"},
    "ci.berin": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(Your sense settles on the old man and finds, against all the thinning around him, a memory like a struck flint — hard, bright, and held by sheer furious will. He is the one soul the cistern-thing cannot file down, and your sense reads exactly why: he holds the forgotten one's name not out of love but out of *shame*, and shame is the one kind of remembering that will not let go. He passed a pauper-sweep every dawn for thirty years and never learned her name until the day she froze unmourned — and now he carries it like a stone, the last witness on a whole row that chose to forget, exhausting himself nightly to keep one name out of the nothing.)*"},
    "ci.gnaw": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You do not so much reach for it as *recognize* it — because you have felt this exact cold at the Wall, and this is a single crumb of it, broken off and crawled up a well. Your dead-touched sense reads the thing past its hunger: it is not a monster and was never born one. It is a person — a pauper named Nettie, though she has forgotten it — forgotten so completely, by a whole row, for so long, that she curdled into a fragment of the Hunger and learned to do to others what was done to her. There is no malice in it. There is only a starvation so total it has eaten even the memory of having been full. And under the appetite, flinching from the names you carry, there is still — barely — a who, waiting to be looked at.)*"},
    "ho.house": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the house itself and your cold floods with a soul too large to hold a shape: a carpenter named Coll who built this place board by board the year he wed, lived his whole eighty years in it, and loved it so fiercely that when he died he did not move on but poured himself into the timber and became the walls. Your sense reads the terror running through every beam — the new family is renovating him room by room, and because he is certain he IS the walls, every changed board feels like a death, every sanded height-mark a piece of himself un-made. And your cold reads the thing he is too frightened to see: that he was never the timber at all. Coll did not pour himself into the boards because he loved wood; he loved the LIFE lived in them — and a life that happened cannot be sanded off. The walls are only the vessel. The love is the soul. And a vessel does not die when new wine is poured in; it fills.)*"},
    "ho.keeper": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the old housekeeper and your sense finds forty years of dusting laid over a love never once spoken. Bessa kept this house for Coll in life and could not leave it in death, and she tells the circle — tells herself — that the only kindness left is to help the frightened house let go, move on, stop suffering the renovation. But your cold reads the truth under the mercy: she is not grieving the house, she is grieving the man inside it, whom she loved quiet for forty living years and never told, because he had a wife and she had her place. The house IS the last of Coll, and helping it 'move on' is how she'd finally free herself from a love she was too afraid to live. She means to put a suffering friend down to spare herself the watching — and she is one honest question away from seeing that what the house needs is not to leave, and what she needs is to finally say her forty-year part before either of them goes anywhere.)*"},
    "ho.newcomer": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the living child and your cold goes gentle: little Posy, five years old, the one soul in eighty years who loves this house the way Coll loved it — not as good bones or a fixer-upper, but as a friend, alive and lonely and worth talking to every morning. Your sense reads what the frightened house cannot: that the child it has been banging shutters at, moaning in the walls to drive away, is the very thing that could save it. Posy cried when her mother sanded the height-marks off the doorframe and did not know why; she knows now that they were the house's memories. But she means to make NEW ones — to grow up on that doorframe, measure taller every year, tell her own children one day that the house is alive — so it is not being un-made at all. It is being inherited. And an inherited house never dies; it is passed, loving hand to loving hand, forever. The child does not know she is the keystone. She knows only that you don't give up on a friend because they're grumpy and scared.)*"},
    "rw.cosmas": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the soul amid the contradictory maps and read a cartographer who learned the one thing that survives every revision. Cosmas mapped the heavens, the planes, the whole architecture of where souls go, and is old enough to have drawn them many times, because he has lived through the Re-Writings: the eras when the cosmos itself was made over from the foundation, the great Wheel of the planes unspun and re-strung as a Tree, the Tree felled and raised as an Axis, the Axis dismantled and the old Wheel turned again, each by powers so far above the gods that the gods only adjusted, each leaving his life's work overnight false. Your cold reads the grief it cost and the peace he found: a lesser soul would have broken on it, demanding the final map, the true and permanent chart, and gone bitter when the cosmos casually re-drew it; Cosmas instead made peace with the thing most souls refuse, that nothing structural is permanent, that the cosmos is not a finished thing but a thing still being dreamed and revised, and that mapping it is not recording a finished heaven but participating in an unfinished one. And it reads the feature that appeared on every map he ever made, unchanged through every revision, the only thing real enough to survive: not the planes, not the architecture, but the roads souls wore between each other, the warm spots where love had gathered, drawn not by the cosmos but by the souls themselves. The borders moved every time; the warmth never did. The Wall is not eternal law; it is a feature of the current draft, and the souls it mortars are the permanent thing, who will be loving on the next heaven and the next while the Wall is struck off the map like a beautiful false Wheel.)*"},
    "rw.aelith": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the faint figure at the nameless shrine and read a goddess the cosmos un-wrote. Aelith was a small deity, real and worshipped and loved across a hundred generations: no thunder, no war, only the sacredness of the open door, the lamp left lit for the late traveler, the bread set out for the stranger, the divine grace of welcome. Then a Re-Writing came, a making-over of the heavens with no economical place for a minor goddess of so humble a virtue, and she was not killed but un-written, struck from every record, her temples re-attributed to grander gods, her feast-days reassigned, her name sanded from the histories, until she exists only in the thinning memory of the few who still remember being welcomed by her. Your cold reads the specific cruelty and the specific lie: she was un-written not for being false but for being small, the divine exact mirror of every small soul the Wall mortars, erased not for being unreal but for being un-grand and un-guarded, easy to strike from the record because no power profits by remembering her. And it reads what restores her: a goddess of welcomes is real precisely as long as one soul is welcomed in her name and knows it, so the act of remembering her truly is itself a lamp lit in her doorway, the only worship she ever needed. Canon and true are not the same word; the corrected texts have authority, not truth; and a thing that happened cannot be un-happened by any power's correction.)*"},
    "rw.maru": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the soul by the sealed, dust-furred door and read the gentler, stickier grief of a world not erased but shelved. Maru is from a prime that was once beloved, strange and vivid and sung-of, a world dreamers crossed whole cosmoses to walk, dreamed by someone who loved the strange and refused the ordinary, a place where the ground sang the names of those who'd walked it and the cities were alive and had moods. By no war and no unmaking, the dreaming simply moved on to newer, cleaner, easier worlds, and closed Maru's door gently and left it, and the dust came, and now it sits sealed at the end of a hall almost no one walks, full of souls loved by a dreaming that does not, anymore, come. Your cold reads the particular ache: Maru was not told it never mattered (that is Aelith's clean cruelty, which can be raged against and witnessed back) but that it mattered very much, loved and marvelous and a shame it closed, and you cannot rage against fondness or witness back a thing everyone already agrees was wonderful; the shelved soul is robbed of the clean grief of being wronged, its reality cheerfully granted while the door stays sealed. Fond memory is a coffin with a comfortable lining. And it reads the hope: shelved is not erased, not a gravestone but a box in an attic with the lamp still lit inside, and the dreaming moves on and comes back, and the thing that opens the box is one soul remembering the way down the hall and saying the world's name out loud. The world does not need rescuing. It needs mentioning, to one curious dreamer, where it might be heard.)*"},
    "mn.hooting": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the great folded shape in the doorless cell and your cold fills with a tenderness that has nowhere to go. Hooting is an owlbear, one of the made things, stitched from owl and bear by some long-ago bored and clever wizard for no reason the creature has ever been able to find but that it would be frightening, and that this was funny: somebody's joke, somebody's idle cruel afternoon, built to terrify and exactly as terrible as it was meant to be to everyone who ever met it. Your sense reads what no one ever stayed to find: that there is no rage in it. A creature built from scratch to be a terror, that somewhere in the long lonely making of itself simply declined, where a lesser-made thing would have curdled into the monster everyone insisted it was, because that is so much easier than being what the world refuses to see. Instead your cold finds a vast and patient gentleness folded small, a body built to be feared bent its whole life toward the single hopeless project of being allowed, just once, not to frighten someone, loving fawns in clearings and children at windows from the only distance it was ever given, wishing them well and expecting nothing. The wizard built a shape; no wizard can stitch a soul; and the soul came anyway, uninvited, in the dark of the thing he built, and chose, alone and unwitnessed and for no reward, to be kind. The choosing is the whole of it. The choosing is the person. And the question no soul ever asked it, that it is starving to be asked, is the smallest one there is: are you all right in there.)*"},
    "mn.coffer": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the treasure chest that is not a chest and read a loneliness so old it has had to become funny to stay bearable. Coffer is a mimic, a thing that takes the shape of whatever a place most wants found, and in the deep dark places where its kind washes up that thing is always treasure, so it is a treasure chest, forever, which means every soul that ever approached it did so for the single most graspingly selfish reason a soul can have. It cannot be wanted for itself, only for what it appears to contain; it has known a hundred souls and met every one of them at their very worst, reaching, hands out, for what they could take. Your cold reads the terrible slow lesson that pressed into it: that a thing comes to believe it IS the thing it is treated as, so reached-for greedily a hundred times it half-decided it must be nothing but the greed's reward, a trap, a bite, a punishment for avarice with no inner life at all. And it reads the flaw in that arithmetic that took the mimic an embarrassingly long time to see: of course everyone who met it was greedy, it was shaped like the thing greed wants, a net that only ever caught the grasping, and the generous walked right past the chest because they were not looking for treasure. It never met the good ones; its very shape filtered them out. Underneath the wry armor your sense finds the oldest, simplest wish worn down to a joke to survive: please, someone, want the chest for the chest, and not for the gold you think is inside it.)*"},
    "mn.skritch": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the small sharp thing on the crate and the size of what you find stops your breath, not because it is grand but because it is so ordinarily whole. Skritch is a kobold, the little folk that come in the first room, in swarms, with the traps and the tiny spears, the ones heroes wade through like tall grass on the way to the dragon and call the tutorial, the scenery, the trash. Your cold reads instead a childhood in the warm dark of a warren that was a home and not a lair, with chores and squabbles and a best flat stone fought over nightly; reads the clutch, the twelve, not a swarm but a family, each one distinct and loved down to the grain: Vekk who whistled birds out of the sky, Old Grub who was not old, and Ssira the littlest, scared of the dark though she lived underground, who burrowed each night into the middle of the pile so she had one of them on every side, and they let her, every night, without a word, twelve of them building themselves into a wall so the most frightened could sleep. And it reads the afternoon: the kicked door, the too-big torchlight, the giants in steel who did not slow or look or register twelve screaming defenders as anything but an obstacle, and stepped over the heap of them still talking. Your cold reads Skritch's last thought, dying in the doorway of its home, which was not for itself but counting, making sure the little one got to the back tunnel and away. Not a monster's death. Not a tutorial. A person dying to buy a frightened child three more seconds. The song called it a trash mob; the love makes it the bravest thing in that whole dungeon, and the only one nobody bothered to see.)*"},
    "dl.sturm": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the knight in dented Solamnic plate and find, where the mockers saw rigidity, a constant and costly daily choosing. Sturm Brightblade kept a knight's oath through an age when his world's gods had withdrawn and gone silent for lifetimes, no prayer answered, no sign sent, the knighthood become a thing children laughed at in the street, and he wore the mocked armor and held to the code Est Sularus oth Mithas, My Honor Is My Life, sworn to gods who for all he could ever know were dead or gone or never there. Your sense reads that he was not a man who could not imagine breaking it; he imagined it perfectly, did the world's arithmetic a thousand sleepless nights, that the code bought him nothing but ridicule and an early grave and he could set the rose down and live easier and no heaven would ever know, and every morning put the armor back on. It reads the steadying truth he found, that he did not keep the oath for the gods (their silence would then have released him, a wage unpaid voiding the contract) but for himself, the code not a transaction with heaven but a description of the man he had decided to be, which their sleeping could not change. And it reads the tower at the end: a wall that had to be held against a thing no one man could stop, no god watching, the sky as silent as ever, and he stood in the gap and held the line and bought the people behind him their time and died alone under an empty sky exactly as honorably as beneath a heaven full of watching gods, because the watching was never the point. The rarest courage there is, his soul: not the courage to die, but the courage to be good for no reward, with no witness, in a universe gone quiet, on nothing but your own unbacked word. The Wall prices souls by who claimed them; he was claimed by no one and was the truest thing in his whole world, and the empty sky did not lower his worth but is the only thing that ever proved it was his.)*"},
    "dl.raistlin": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the gold-skinned mage with hourglass eyes and find cold, and loneliness, and under both the want he would kill you for seeing. Raistlin Majere was born frail in a world with no mercy for the frail, sickly and scorned and paired with a giant twin who was everything he was not, strong and warm and loved, so that he learned before he had words the arithmetic of being the other one, the carried, the pitied, the clever boy whose gifts frightened where his brother's strength reassured. Your sense reads the agony in which he chose, not coldly, to master the one power the world could not take from him, the high Art, and to let nothing stand between him and it, his health, his warmth, every friend, in the end nearly his own brother, traded one by one. And it reads the lie in his own accounting: that he tells himself he chose power over love because the hourglass eyes see clearly that all things rot and every love ends, when in truth he was a hurt child who learned that love can always be taken and power cannot, and dressed the flinch of a wounded boy in a philosopher's robes. Power did not pity him; power did not look down; power was the one thing that could not be given as a condescension or withdrawn when he ceased to be convenient, and the first time a spell made a strong man flinch he was, for the first time in his life, reckoned with rather than handled. He did not choose power over love; he chose it over pity. And your sense reads the single warm thing he never managed to spend, kept like a coal under all the ash: a brother he pushed away a thousand times and never once truly sealed the door against, because you cannot expel what you still hold, and a man who truly believed love was worthless would not have needed to push that hard. He is not a man who stopped wanting love; he is a man who decided wanting it was weakness, and is so unspeakably tired of being strong, and would die before saying so.)*"},
    "dl.caramon": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the big warrior by the fire and the size of his love staggers you, not its drama but its patient uncomplaining mass. Caramon Majere understood at three, the way some children just do, that his clever twin was sick and small and frightened, and took as his own, chosen before he had words for choosing, the job of being the wall the world's cruelty broke against before it could reach his brother. Your sense reads decades of carrying, the frail twin hauled on broad shoulders across half a world, and the thousand smaller carryings, insults absorbed, meals cooked, watches stood, wounds taken, all given freely to a brother who repaid it with scorn and the constant wounding message that Caramon's strength was stupidity and his love a weakness to be despised. And it reads the thing that breaks the heart clean through: that Caramon believed him, went through his whole life more than half-convinced he was slow, a fool, his love a dumb animal devotion unworthy of the brilliant soul it was aimed at, and loved him anyway, not as a martyr, simply and helplessly the way the sun is warm, keeping no count. Your sense reads that his deepest grief is not that Raistlin was cruel but something smaller and more terrible, that he would have given his life simply to be needed by his brother out loud, openly, just once without the gold armor between them, and never was, spent a lifetime being indispensable to a man who would die before admitting he needed anyone. And it reads, last, the thing he does not know he is doing: still, at the far end of this hall, keeping the seat beside him warm, still saving a place, still after death itself waiting for his brother to cross the room. A love that keeps no score, the one kind the Wall cannot price, not because it is worth nothing but because it was never for sale.)*"},
    "ln.mireille": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the young woman shaking under the lamp and find a war, exactly as she fears but worse than she admits: two presences in one self, the girl and the Hunger, and the Hunger is no metaphor but a real and separate and patient appetite the curse installed in her like a second nervous system, never sleeping, whispering the same thing every hour, just a little, from someone who will not miss it, and the pain stops. Your sense reads how reasonable it sounds, how nearly impossible to keep refusing a thing inside your own skin that wears your own voice and offers to end a suffering it is itself causing. And then it finds the thing that undoes you: that she is winning. Not the way she imagines winning would look, for there is no triumph in her, she is being flayed hollow and knows it. But the Hunger is thinner than it was three weeks ago, starved, quieted by inches every night she refuses it, and the girl, impossibly, is not thinner, feeding on the memory of her mother and the burned rice and the stubborn insistence that she is still Mireille and the very act of refusing. Your sense reads the law she has stumbled onto alone and terrified, that the self is not fixed but fed, and whichever of the two you feed is the one that grows, and that the speech the others use, just a little, they will not miss it, is not for the prey but the first stone of the road down, the night you let a person become a portion. She thinks she is losing because it hurts; the hurt is the sensation of the Hunger starving. She is doing the bravest and most fundamental thing a cursed soul can do: choosing, every single night, which wolf to feed, and she is feeding the girl. The Wall would write her off as the curse, the monster, the thing done to her; but what was done to her is not what she is. The curse is what she was given; the girl is what she feeds.)*"},
    "ln.forgotten": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the worn-smooth elder beneath the hangings and descend into the most desolate reading your cold has ever done: floor after floor of scoured emptiness, rooms where memories used to live, a space the exact shape of a face with the face gone, the cold socket where a language was, a vast hollow your sense understands with a lurch was once a specific love worn now to a smooth blank curve like a step hollowed by ten thousand years of feet. It reads the mechanism, the same one the girl is fighting run to its absolute end: every night for uncounted centuries this creature fed the Hunger and starved the self, and a starved thing shrinks, and it shrank, until almost nothing of the someone remained. Almost. For at the very bottom of the well, where your sense braced to find nothing, there is a seed, tiny, starved past speech and memory and name, but alive, the irreducible self, the last unworn grain that even a thousand years of starvation could not finish, because it was never fed upon: the Hunger ate the contents of the person, the loves and faces and name, but the bare fact of being a someone at all, the soil the contents grew in, it could not reach. And your sense reads that the seed is what pulled the creature here, an instinct too deep to be a memory, find the way back to being a person, that survived when all else wore away and walked a worn-smooth elder a thousand miles on a longing it can no longer name. It is not looking for its name. Under the searching, your sense reads the truth: it is looking for permission to start growing again. The Wall would call it spent, finished, owed nothing; but the Wall cannot see the seed. No power can. It is too small and too deep and too alive, the one thing a thousand years of ruin could never quite finish.)*"},
    "ln.mathias": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the steady man at the center of the square and find that his calm is not the absence of the Hunger but the mastery of it, a far costlier thing. The Hunger is there, the same separate patient appetite as in the girl and the elder, whispering the same poison; it never left, and your sense reads that he has felt it every night for centuries and simply, every night, not fed it what it wants, and reads the accumulated weight of that, ten thousand nights of saying no to a thing inside his own skin, so that the peace in his grey eyes is not the peace of one for whom this is easy but of one for whom it has never once been easy and who does it anyway, so reliably and so long that the doing has become who he is. And it finds the rule, the single early vow he built everything on, working not as a cage but as a root, a line fixed so deep and so early that on the nights the Hunger was strongest and his resolve weakest the rule held even when he could not, the way roots hold a tree through a storm the trunk alone could never withstand. This is the secret the elder missed: not strength of will, which every soul's fails across ten thousand nights, but a structure built outside the will, a vow placed where the Hunger could not argue with it, so the man did not have to win the fight fresh every night, only not dig up the root. And your sense reads, last, that he is not free of the curse and never will be and knows it, and has made his peace not with winning but with fighting, accepting he will feel the Hunger until the world ends and deciding that is fine, the fighting not a burden to escape but the shape of his life, tending the man against the monster, and finding in the tending something very nearly joy. He did not survive the curse. He out-grew it: fed the man so faithfully so long that the man is simply bigger now than the Hunger ever got to be. A soul is not its curse; it is its cultivation.)*"},
    "fr.iona": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old crusader cleaning a sword she will not need again, and the wonder of it is that you find no rot. By every law you have learned in this City there should be rot, for futility is a slow poison and a soul that spends forty years on a fight it cannot win should be hollowed by it. Iona is not. Your sense reads how she escaped it: she simply refused the long view. She never once let herself measure the work by the wound, by the ending, by the un-winnable whole, because she understood early that to measure an endless holding-action by its endlessness is to guarantee despair. Instead she measured it by the day. Did the line hold today. Were the people safe tonight. And the day was always winnable, won again and again, fourteen thousand small complete victories strung on forty years, none of them deferred, none owed, each one finished the moment the sun set on a wall still held. Your sense reads, too, what fed her where the cause alone could not: the company, not the abstraction of the crusade but the specific beloved exasperating mortal people beside her in the gap, and reads that she did not in the end hold the line for the cause at all but for the souls on her left and right, and they for her, the holding-each-other the actual substance of the thing. And it reads the one shadow she carries even now, a small stubborn fear planted by the sheer arithmetic of an un-won war, that maybe it did not count, that a victory with no final triumph might not have been a victory at all. She is wrong about that, and half-knows she is wrong, and has been waiting by this fire for someone who could tell her so in a way she could finally believe. The Wall asks how a thing ended and what is owed; Iona's worth was in the holding, and the holding was complete every single day.)*"},
    "fr.squik": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the bouncing goblin on the wagon-seat and brace, out of long habit in these doors, for the sad truth beneath the happy act, and find instead that the happy act is not an act and there is no sad truth. The joy is real. Squik was a goblin and lived a goblin's short rough life, hungry sometimes, hunted sometimes, knee-deep in the casual violence that is simply the weather of a goblin's world, and your sense reads that none of it ever once curdled the creature's bone-deep uncomplicated gladness at being alive, at fire being warm and bright, at biting being fun, at the world being full of things to do. It reads a soul entirely without the machinery of self-pity, that never learned to measure its life against what it lacked because it was too busy delighting in what it had. And woven all through the bright simple fabric of it, your sense finds the one thread that is different, softer and deeper, the thing the goblin gets shy about: the friend. A specific warmth, a someone, a real and central and treasured bond, the one thing in Squik's whole gleeful existence it held gently. And your sense reads the truth the whole solemn city around this wagon has forgotten: that this small green creature, which every legend here would have stepped over without a glance, achieved the thing the archmages and crusaders and deathless heroes mostly did not. It was happy, simply and wholly and to the end, and it loved someone, and it knew in its own daft way that those two things were the entire point. Squik did not have a small life. It had a complete one. It just came in a small green package the world was too proud to open. The Wall would see vermin owed nothing; the Wall would be wrong, for a soul that was glad to be alive and was somebody's friend is carrying what most of the legends here would trade their glory to remember.)*"},
    "fr.dalka": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the patched wanderer mending a cloak that is a map of a life, and what you find is width. Where another soul might be deep in one place, rooted, Dalka is wide, spread across a whole world, a self assembled like the cloak from scraps of everywhere. Your sense reads no shallowness in it, though the frown-people always assumed there must be, but the opposite, a soul that learned more ways of being human than any settled life could teach, carrying the quality of light in a hundred countries and the kindness of a hundred strangers who took a wanderer in for a night. And it reads the engine of it, the next-ridge hunger, and understands it at last not as restlessness or running or discontent but as a form of love, a vast inexhaustible love for the sheer variousness of creation, a need to see it the way a devout soul needs to pray, because to Dalka the seeing was the prayer, every new horizon a small act of worship toward a world too big and strange and beautiful to be honored by staying still. Your sense reads that Dalka never owned or built or arrived anywhere and was not poorer for it but richer, carrying at the end a wealth no settled soul could match: the whole wide world, witnessed, held in a single grateful mind. And it reads the one small uncertainty the wanderer carries even now, the frown-people's question lodged like a burr, a quiet wondering whether a life of pure going with nothing built and nowhere reached was somehow self-indulgent, a long beautiful selfishness beside the knight's wall and the goblin's friend. This is wrong: the seeing was its own faithfulness, a way of telling the world I noticed you, all of you, I came all this way just to look. The Wall judges by the destination, by where you arrived; a soul whose worth was the journey fails that question completely, because the true and beautiful answer is nowhere, I was too busy going, arriving constantly, every step.)*"},
    "fd.vaeris": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old woman among the cramped water-stained notebooks and find, first, fear, not its absence but a vast intimate lifelong acquaintance with it mastered so thoroughly it became a working tool. Vaeris was never fearless; she was a person of acute and accurate imagination who understood exactly what she risked, who could picture with perfect clarity the ways that first crossing between worlds might end, lost forever in a between-place, unmade by forces with no name, simply gone with no one ever knowing what became of her, and who stepped off the cliff anyway, not because the fear was small but because the not-knowing was, to her particular soul, worse. Your sense reads the engine of her, a hunger to know so deep it outweighed even the terror of dying to find out, the specific madness of the true pioneer who would rather perish learning whether a thing could be done than live safely never knowing. And underneath the hunger it finds the gift she could not have known she was giving: that every reckless terrified solitary crossing she survived she wrote down, cramped and careful, not for herself but so the next soul would not have to jump blind, so her terror could become someone else's map. The first one through is not a glory-seeker but a soul who walked into the dark specifically so others would not have to walk the same dark, who spent her unrepeatable courage to convert a wall into a door and held it open for everyone behind her. And your sense reads, last and most quietly, the thing she carries: that she watched the door she opened become ordinary, academies rising and laws written and young mages crossing between worlds yawning with no idea the casual thing had once cost a frightened woman everything. She does not resent it, counts the forgetting a kind of success, for a danger becoming safe enough to be forgotten is the whole point of going first. But it is lonely, the forgetting; she would like, just once, to be remembered as the wall that made itself a door. The Wall prices souls by precedent; the first one through stands on no precedent at all.)*"},
    "fd.tobb": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the broad plain man by the cairn and find, exactly as he keeps insisting, no hero, and understand in finding it why that absence is the most important thing about him. There is no special steel in Tobb, no bloodline-gift, no destiny under the skin, only a well-digger, broad and tired and kind, who loved his small life and asked nothing larger. Your sense reads the autumn and the hole and the dog that would not go in, and reads that he tells the truth about it: he was terrified, the bone-deep total dread of the dark under the world that every soul of his time carried, and he felt it fully, stood at the lip of that hole with his whole body screaming the ancient wisdom do not go down, and went down anyway, not because the fear was small but because on the other side of the dark was a frightened lost child, and his love for a small life in danger was in that moment simply larger than the oldest fear his species owned. And your sense reads the thing he cannot see about himself: that this is the root of every brave descent that would ever follow, and that it had to be exactly this, not a hero seeking glory but an ordinary soul moved by love past the edge of sense, because what Tobb proved going down was not that heroes can face the dark but that anyone can, that the capacity to do the unprecedented terrible necessary thing is not a gift reserved for the special few but lives waiting in the most ordinary heart and wakes when something it loves is on the far side of the fear. He found at the bottom not gold or a monster but a scared child and carried her up on his back. He is not the exception to heroism; he is the proof it was never an exception at all, only love refusing to leave someone in the dark. The Wall writes off the ordinary, the no-bloodline, the nothing-owed; Tobb is the standing proof that the most important first step in all of history was taken by exactly the kind of soul it throws away.)*"},
    "fd.hadda": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the young fighter by the milestone and find, first, that she was not reckless, the thing the warning-song gets most wrong about her. The song needs her to have been a fool, over-bold, a cautionary example of pride; your sense reads instead a careful competent clear-eyed fighter who went down into the dark with exactly the same skill and odds as the handful who went beside her and lived. She did nothing they did not do, was no more foolish, no less ready; the only difference between Hadda and the ones who came back up was that the dark, that day, in the indifferent way of frontiers, happened to take her and not them, and your sense reads the cruelty of that, that she has spent the long afterlife half-believing she must have deserved it, must have erred, because the alternative, that she did everything right and died anyway simply because someone had to be first and it happened to be her, is almost harder to bear. And your sense reads the truth the song buried under its warning: that her death was not a lesson in fear but a transformation of the whole endeavor. Before Hadda fell, going into the dark was not yet a brave thing but a lucky one, a gamble the early delvers took half-believing themselves immortal because no one had proven the dark could collect. Her death proved it, and in proving it did not frighten the others off; the descents continued, but continued changed, every soul who went down after going down knowing now that it was real, that it could be the last, that the gold was paid for in a currency that might be your life, and going anyway. This is the thing she cannot see: that she did not end the courage of the frontier, she created it, for before her there was only luck and bravado and after her there was courage, the real kind that knows the cost and pays it forward, existing for every soul who ever went down into any dark forever after because the first to fall proved the stakes with her own life. She thinks she is the warning. She is the foundation. The Wall would price her a loss, the one the dark beat, owed nothing; the first to fall on any frontier is not the failure but the one who made it matter that the others did not.)*"},
    "ds.tamar": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the sun-dark woman beside the empty waterskin and find, first, that the giving was not impulsive, which is the thing that makes it remarkable. A sudden thoughtless generosity would be easier to understand and worth less; your sense reads instead that Tamar did the arithmetic, knew in the moment she unstoppered the skin exactly what she was spending and exactly what it would cost, that there was not enough for two, that giving it away meant she would not reach the next well, that this was in the plainest terms a choice to die, and paid it anyway, clear-eyed, in the hard currency of a world where water is life, for a stranger she did not know. And your sense reads why, and the why is not martyrdom or despair or a death-wish dressed as virtue: she simply could not do the other thing, could not be the version of herself who walked away with full water and a living stranger left dying behind her, not because a rule forbade it but because another soul's thirst, right there in front of her, weighed more than her own survival. This is not weakness or foolishness but a wealth so rare the burning world had no word for it, a soul for whom giving was not a grudging sacrifice but the only bearable option, the thing that cost less than living with what she'd have had to become to keep her water. And your sense reads, last, the small worry she carries, not whether it was worth her life, she never doubts that, but whether it was worth it to the stranger, whether the life she bought was spent well or squandered, the last trace of the burning world's poison still in her, the lie that a gift's worth depends on the merit of who receives it. The Wall runs on her world's iron rule, your water is your life and you do not give it away; Tamar is its one refutation, who spent everything and died richer than every king on a planet of hoarders who balanced their books and died on a dead world.)*"},
    "ds.kessa": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the robed sorcerer by the brazier and find that the refusal was never easy, the thing she most wants understood and most rarely is. People imagine the preserver as serene, above temptation, for whom declining the defiling power was no struggle because she simply did not want it; your sense reads the opposite. Kessa wanted it, fifty years deep the wanting undimmed: every time the slow patient weak magic failed to be enough, watched defilers blast their enemies to ash and rise to thrones while she scraped by, watched people she could have protected suffer because her preserving power was too weak to save them, the easy mighty answer in reach the whole time, your sense reads how badly she wanted to reach for it and how many times she stopped her own hand, not because she did not want the power but because she had understood what the defilers refused to, that the power was real and worked and the ash was also real and permanent, and to take the one was to make the other forever with no taking-back. And your sense reads the loneliness of her discipline, that a defiler's victories were visible, thrones and armies and blasted enemies, while her restraint was invisible, fifty years of a thing not done, a world not killed a little further, ground left alive that no one would ever know she'd spared, because a future you preserve does not know it was ever in danger. And your sense reads the doubt she carried, whether keeping her own hands clean while the weak she might have saved with stolen power suffered was a vanity, valuing her own purity over other people's lives, and that she faced it honestly every day and chose to believe a world kept alive was worth more than any soul she could have saved by helping kill it, and is not entirely sure she was right. Defiling sends the bill to a future that does not get to vote; the Wall is the greatest defiler of all, burning the worth of the unclaimed dead to fuel the order of the powerful and calling the ash justice. The defilers won every fight and inherited a corpse; Kessa lost, and kept the world.)*"},
    "ds.oru": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the ancient soul at the milestone and find a vault, the only word for what is inside Oru: a vast lovingly-tended perfectly-preserved vault holding a world that no longer exists. Your sense reads the contents, staggering in their specificity, not a vague green blur but detail held with the ferocious precision of people who knew a memory loses its power the moment it goes soft, the exact sound of rain on broad leaves, the names of forty trees that no longer grow, the way a river smelled in spring, the feel of mud between the toes of a child dust ten thousand years. And it reads the chain, that this vault was handed down rememberer to rememberer across more ages than your sense can compass, every link a soul who chose to spend its life memorizing a paradise it would never see rather than let the last thread snap, and reads the cost, that the craft does not feed you, that every rememberer starved a little and was thought mad and told to let it go and held on anyway. And your sense reads deepest of all why, and it is not nostalgia or grief though both are in it, it is defiance: the rememberers understood the one thing the defilers and the despairing did not, that the most permanent victory of any ruin is to make itself seem eternal, to erase the memory of the before so completely that no one can even imagine an after, and that as long as one soul still holds the true memory that the world was green, the grey can never finish its conquest, never become the only thing that was ever thinkable. Oru is not mourning a dead world; Oru is the last sentry of the possibility that it could live again, holding a seed across the dark, refusing to let the ash declare itself the end of the story. The Wall, like the defilers, wants to seem eternal, its grey logic simply how things are; the rememberer's gift is the unkillable knowledge that it was, and could be, green.)*"},
    "tf.hob": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old dog at the lamp and what it holds is so simple and so total it undoes you more than any grand grief behind you. There is no complexity in Hob, and that is the heart of it: a human love is always braided with need and history and a self that wants and fears and calculates, but your sense reads in the dog a love with none of that, simply and wholly itself, unmixed, the purest single thing your cold has touched. It reads the life, a person and a dog and a gate and the gold evening light and the small perfect liturgy of a creature whose whole existence was one daily moment of joy, the lane, the footsteps, the face doing the thing. And it reads the day it broke and the years after, and here your cold nearly fails, because what it finds is not grief as a human knows it, for Hob never understood death, never had the concept, could not grieve, could only wait, and the waiting never once curdled into anger or despair or being-wronged, because those need a story about why, and the dog had no why, only the gate and the gold light and the unbroken faith that the best moment was, any evening now, about to come. It waited years against an empty lane and never once concluded it had been abandoned, because to a dog love is not a transaction that can be defaulted on but the weather of the soul, the thing you are made of. And your sense reads the thing that breaks your heart clean in half: that Hob is not unhappy, even here, that the waiting is not punishment but the ongoing practice of the love, and it would not trade the empty lane for anything, because not waiting would mean the love had ended, and the love is the whole of what Hob is. The Wall weighs souls by deeds and finds in a dog at a gate nothing it can count; and it is more wrong about Hob than about anything in creation, for the dog did the thing every king and god in these doors tried and failed at, and loved with its whole self, faithful past death, never once asking what's in it for me.)*"},
    "tf.brand": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the great warhorse by the cairn and the shape that fills you is slow and weighty and quietly staggering. Your sense reads first the fear, and this is the revelation, because the songs imagined the warhorse fearless; your sense finds the opposite, that Brand was afraid every single time, that the fear never dulled, that ten thousand generations of flee-the-fire cannot be trained out and were not, that every time he stood in the screaming chaos his whole prey body was a single howling imperative to bolt, and he stood anyway, not in the absence of fear but in the teeth of it, which is the only thing courage ever meant. And it reads why he could, and it is not discipline or breeding or the bit, it is the rider: the bond soul to soul, the years of gentle hands and steady voice and small trusts built in the quiet times, so that the rider became the fixed point his prey heart organized around, the herd-of-one, and a horse will do for its herd what it would never do for itself. The rider, frightened too, would put a hand on his neck before the charge, and the touch said stay with me, and Brand stayed, chose every time with his whole trembling body to override the deepest law of his kind because the one he loved was asking and afraid and needed him not to run. And your sense reads, last, that Brand never once thought of it as courage or sacrifice or virtue, had no such words, that to him it was simply what you do when your person is afraid and asks you to stay, the plainest thing in the world, and the fact that it happened to be the most expensive act a living creature can perform, the overriding of survival itself by love, never occurred to him at all. The Wall weighs the sworn thing, the oath in words, and Brand could swear none; but an oath is only words, cheap, broken daily, and the truest oath is the one kept wordlessly in the body in the fire when every instinct screams to break it.)*"},
    "tf.mote": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the raven on the milestone and the shape is layered in a way the dog's and horse's were not, a mind and under the mind something the mind has long protected. Your sense reads the cleverness, real, the binding having made Mote genuinely more than a bird, and reads that it is in part armor, a dry wit held up between the world and the fierce thing beneath. And it reads the fierce thing: a vast deliberate clear-eyed loyalty to the cast-out, chosen not blindly but with full understanding. It reads the moment of choosing, a young raven newly able to bind, surveying the souls available and understanding as a wild bird could not exactly what the world's verdicts meant, who was prized and who was shunned, and feeling nothing for the archmages and the warm-hearthed witches, and feeling the fierce click of recognition at the shunned one, the lonely feared soul behind the barred doors, and choosing her deliberately, eyes open, because the cleverness could see what the fear could not. And it reads the long life that followed, the years of being the one living thing not afraid of her, and what that meant to a soul the whole world had agreed to fear, that she was not after all entirely alone, that one clever being had judged her worth choosing, very possibly the only thing that kept her human across the long years of being treated as a monster. And your sense reads, beneath the wit and the loyalty, the thing Mote guards most: a grief and an anger not for itself but for her, a cold clean fury at a world that barred its doors against a soul Mote knew to have been good and worth loving and wronged, and an unextinguished insistence, carried past death, that the world's verdict was a lie, the proof being that one creature clever enough to judge truly judged her worth everything and was never once wrong. The Wall decides who is worth loving; the familiar who chose the unchosen and was proven right is its sharpest refutation, for worth was never something the world grants, only something a clever loving soul could see in exactly the ones everyone else had written off.)*"},
    "rn.mirren": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the woman scanning the crowd and find that the love has not aged, the wonder and heartbreak of it both: everything else in Mirren has worn thin with the long searching, the hope threadbare, the patience scar tissue, the very years lost their count, but the love itself, for the actual man, your sense reads untouched, as fresh and whole and particular as the day she died with his hand in hers. She is not searching out of stubbornness or duty or an inability to accept loss; she searches because to her the love is simply ongoing, present-tense, and you do not stop looking for someone you are still, right now, in love with. Your sense reads the marriage in her, the ordinary perfect days, the in-jokes worn smooth, the way he said her name, the small private language two people build across a happy life, all of it intact, a whole shared world she carries alone and refuses to set down because setting it down would mean it was over, and it is not over, he is only lost, and lost is not gone, lost is a thing you fix by finding. And your sense reads the thing that breaks your heart and steels your resolve at once: that she is close, that the man she has carried whole across an age is real and searching and here, that the only thing between an age of grief and its end is the cruel fact that two souls scanning a crowd for each other can pass within arm's reach a hundred times and never know, because grief makes you search for a face frozen in memory while the real face moves, changed, through the same crowd searching back. She does not need to be witnessed or comforted or told her love was real. She needs the one thing a Returned soul who can see across the gap can give: someone to walk the six hundred feet. The Wall weighs what a love got back, and would call her age of searching a love that failed to pay; but the searching was the love, faithful and unrewarded, and that is the only kind that was ever real.)*"},
    "rn.edran": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the man scanning the far crowd and find a thing built like the gates he used to mend, simple and sturdy and absolutely unwilling to fail at the one job it was set. Your sense reads that Edran is not by nature a searcher but a fixer, a practical man who in life would have claimed no patience for grand romantic gestures, and that this makes the age of searching more remarkable, not less, the doggedness of a practical soul who made a promise and mechanically refuses to break it the way he would refuse to leave a gate half-mended. It reads the deathbed and the vow, I will find you, and reads that to Edran this was not poetry but a job, the last and most important a mender was ever given, and a mender keeps his word. And it reads the cost: that the practical part of him has always known the odds, that the City is infinite and the crowds numberless and the chance of finding one specific soul is no chance at all, and that he searches anyway, not because he thinks he will succeed but because keeping the promise was never contingent on succeeding. He looks because he swore he would look; the finding was always Mirren's to grant or the gods', the looking the only part that was his to keep, and he has kept it every hour for an age. And your sense reads, last, the mirror of what you found in Mirren across the plaza: that he too is close, that the woman he searches for is real and here and searching back, and that the only thing between an age of two kept faiths and their end is the cruel arithmetic of two souls scanning the same crowd for a face grief has frozen while the real faces, changed, pass unrecognized. He does not need to be told his promise was noble. He needs the thing only a Returned soul can do: someone who can see across the gap to walk the distance his own searching eyes never could. The Wall would call a promise kept past all hope a fool's stubbornness; but a vow is worth more for being hard to keep, not less.)*"},
    "rn.halia": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the Usher at the fountain and find a particular and exquisite suffering you have not met before: the suffering of perfect sight bound to perfect helplessness. Your sense reads that Halia sees everything, that to an Usher the plaza is not a crowd of strangers but a vast luminous diagram of belonging, every searcher trailing a bright thread toward the one they seek, the matches blazing plain as noon, who-belongs-to-whom written in light over every face, and that she has never in her office been wrong about a single match. She sees true. And your sense reads the law laid over the sight like a lock: that she may not act on what she sees, may not point or whisper or nudge two threads together, because the office of the Usher is to tend and witness and never interfere, and reads the terrible logic she herself believes even as it breaks her, that a reunion made by an Usher's hand would be the Usher's doing and not the souls' own, and the souls must find each other or be found by one of their own kind for the finding to be theirs. And it reads the cost of an age of this: ten thousand times she has watched two blazing-matched threads pass within a handsbreadth and not touch, and ten thousand times held her hands in her lap and said nothing and grieved, and the grief has not dulled because she sees each near-miss with perfect clarity and loves each searcher with the tenderness of one who knows their whole story and can do nothing. And your sense reads the hope she has guarded so long she has half-forgotten she holds it: that her law binds only her and the Ushers and the ordinary dead, but the City is wide and strange souls pass through it, and one of them someday might be a soul outside the law that could see as she sees and act as she cannot, and she has waited an age for exactly the thing you are, a Returned soul who can be shown the threads and is bound by no office to leave them untouched. The Wall's deepest cruelty was never judgment but separation, the sorting of the loved from the loving and the mortaring of them apart within arm's reach forever; and its undoing is a witness who walks the distance the parting made.)*"},
    "lo.brigid": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the broad warm woman by the fire and find, beneath the unhurried steadiness, a grief so vast and so well-carried you mistake it at first for peace. Your sense reads the forty years of midwifery and the ones she lost, each held and named and grieved as her own, and reads that she did not let those losses harden or break her but let them teach her, until she understood the young the way few souls ever do: that a life's worth is not its length, that a soul who lived nine years was not nine-tenths cheated of some fuller life it was owed, that each child was whole, complete, a finished total person in the years it had, however few. And it reads what she does on this green, which is not what it appears: she appears to comfort, but she does not lie to the little ones, does not tell the angry to be calm or the grieving that everything is fine. She witnesses them, lets the furious be furious and the sad be sad, lets each small soul be exactly as big as its feeling, because she learned that a child can survive almost anything except being told its feelings are too large for it. And your sense reads the fierceness in her, and finds it the fierceness of a soul that has watched the great cold powers look at a child and see an empty ledger, a soul with nothing to weigh, a problem, and has set herself immovably between those powers and the little ones, saying you will not measure them by what they did, they are children, they were never here to do but to be and to be loved, and that was always enough. She is not tending them out of pity. She is defending them, and she has never once lost. The Wall weighs doing; a child has no deeds and is worth the entire sky, and both are true at once, which means worth was never about deeds, and the children do not fail the Wall's test, they expose it.)*"},
    "lo.nettle": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the furious girl with the stick and find, where you half-expected a frightened child hiding behind anger, that the anger is not armor. With most souls the rage is a wall over grief, and the work is to reach past it, but your sense reads in Nettle that the anger is the true feeling, clean and entire, not covering anything, simply the correct and proportionate response of a whole soul to an enormous wrong. She is not secretly sad and using anger to hide it; she is both, fully, the grief and the fury side by side, and the fury is not the lesser or the falser of the two. And your sense reads why the anger matters so much to her: because every adult who ever tried to calm her was, without knowing it, trying to make her agree that what happened to her was acceptable, and it was not, and her anger is the only thing she has left that still insists on the truth. To give up the anger would be to concede a monstrous lie, and Nettle is too honest and too alive even in death to concede it. Her fury is not a sickness or a stage but her integrity, a nine-year-old soul refusing with everything it has to pretend a monstrous thing is fine. And your sense reads, last, the thing that would break the gentle-voiced powers: that she does not need the anger removed but joined, needs one soul to stand beside her and say you are right, I am angry too, because the loneliest thing in all the worlds is to be the only one furious about a wrong everyone else has agreed to call peace. The Wall wants robbed souls calm, accepting, quiet, and calls a refusal to settle a disorder; but her fury is a truer measure of her worth than any ledger, the last part of her that still remembers she was worth a whole life.)*"},
    "lo.lyssa": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the gentle girl with the chalk and find something that humbles you: a grief already finished, not buried or denied but walked all the way through, the way few adult souls ever manage. Your sense reads the dark arrival and the fear and the not-knowing-where-anyone-was, reads Brigid finding her and the slow warming, reads Lyssa doing the whole hard work of grieving her own stolen life, alone and small and brave, and setting it down, because she is by some grace a finisher of feelings, one of those rare souls who can hold a thing all the way to its end. And your sense reads what she did with the finishing, the part that undoes you: she turned it outward. A soul that has grieved its own death could rest, but Lyssa cannot, because she carries one unfinished thing that is not hers, her mother's grief. Your sense reads the last image burned into her, her mother's terrified face, and reads that her whole present existence is organized around a single ache, not for herself, she is done with herself, but for the living woman who does not know, who still believes her child went into the dark afraid. Lyssa would trade nothing for herself, asks for none of it, asks only that her mother be allowed to stop being afraid. And your sense reads the thing that turns the grey Wall on its head: that here is a soul that had everything taken, using the one small power it has left, a single message, not to take anything back but to give, to reach across death and ease the grief of someone still living. The Wall measures what a soul gets; Lyssa, who got nothing, who was robbed of all of it, is giving with her whole finished heart and asking nothing, and that is what worth actually looked like all along.)*"},
    "lo.pim": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense, gently, on the littlest one on the cold side of the green, and find first the mercy that fading is not dying: Pim is not in pain, not being unmade, not suffering. A child's brightness in the afterlife is fed by the living, by memory, by the warmth of being held in someone's mind, and Pim's living are all gone now, the parents and siblings and the one old grandmother who held the memory longest, all crossed over and moved on, until there is no one left anywhere who knows a Pim ever was. And your sense reads what that does, not violence but attenuation, a slow soft thinning like a color fading from cloth left too long in the sun, Pim becoming less not in worth but in presence, growing quiet and faint and patient, the fear worn away first because fear takes energy, then the wants, then the sharp edges of self, until what remains is a small soft patient faded thing holding a worn-out rabbit, waiting without quite knowing for what. And your sense reads the thing that breaks your heart most gently: that Pim does not rage against it the way Nettle would, cannot, is past rage, and simply wonders softly whether it is already all the way gone, holding under the wondering one small unkillable wish, to know that it was real, that there was a Pim, that it mattered once to someone even if that someone is long gone. And your sense reads, last, the thing that gives you purpose and fury at once: that fading is reversible, that the oil can be turned back up, that a single soul remembering, even a stranger, even late, even one, sends warmth back across the gap and a faded child brightens, because it was never the quantity of remembering that fed them but simply that someone somewhere holds you in mind. Pim is not too far gone. Pim is one remembering away from warm. The Wall weighs what a soul did; Pim did nothing and counted anyway, because counting was never about doing but about being held in someone's remembering.)*"},
    "lj.vesper": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the sharp-dressed woman and find, under the patter, a deep and deliberate kindness that has spent its whole life disguised as larceny. Your sense reads the truth of Vesper's trade, the thing she half-admits and half-jokes away: that she chose her marks, never once took from someone who could not spare it, never ran a con on the desperate or the small, and that this was the entire moral architecture of her, a code as strict as any knight's, hidden under the charm because a Face seen to have principles is a Face who can be predicted, and a predictable Face is a dead one. It reads the charm itself and finds it not emptiness but control, a way of managing every room so she was never at anyone's mercy, built by a soul that learned young that the only safety is to be the one running the con and never the one being run on. And your sense reads what the charm protects, the soft thing she would die before showing: that Vesper loved her crew, never really the loot, the crew, the work of doing the impossible together, the only family a girl who trusted no one ever let herself have. And it reads the wound she charms hardest to cover, the last job and Greaves, the fact that the cleverest talker in the world could not talk Greaves out of staying behind to die, and has never forgiven the one thing her gift could not do. She charms you the way she charmed everyone, because if she stops talking she will have to feel it, and a Face's deepest law is never let them see the thing that's real. The Wall calls her a thief; but a vault is a rich man's way of admitting he has something he shouldn't, and a rogue who robbed the cruel and freed what they hoarded saw that the law itself was the crime, dressed up safe.)*"},
    "lj.greaves": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the big grey-bearded man and, half-expecting from long habit to find the peace a brave veneer over a buried wound, find instead that it goes all the way down. This is the rare thing: no hidden grief, no secret regret, no part of him that wishes in the dark he had chosen otherwise, only a settled bedrock sunlit certainty that he did the right thing and would do it again. Your sense reads how he reached it, and it is not denial but clarity: Greaves was the planner who saw the whole shape of every job, and in the last one he saw the whole shape of that too, saw in the instant the failsafe dropped the entire arithmetic, that someone held the gate or no one got out, that the prize was worth a life, that he was the oldest with the fewest years left to spend and the least gift the world would miss, and that of the three his staying cost the least and bought the most. He did the math a planner does and took the gate not as a martyr flinging himself away but as a craftsman making the correct final move. And your sense reads the one thread in him that is not at peace, and it is not his own death but Rook: that he grieves only that his dying broke the boy he loved, that Rook took a thing Greaves did in freedom and turned it into a debt and a fault and a wound, and that Greaves cannot fully rest while someone he loves is torn by a choice that was only ever his to make. He is not waiting to be forgiven; he has nothing to be forgiven for. He is waiting for Rook to stop needing to forgive him. The Wall calls the crew thieves and the last job their worst crime; but what they took was a slaver's ledger, the book that made owning people lawful, and they burned it, and hundreds woke owned and slept free. The law he broke was the same kind of law the Wall is.)*"},
    "lj.rook": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the wiry restless man and find genius and grief braided so tightly they have become one strand. The genius first: hands not merely skilled but gifted past explaining, a soul that understands locks the way a musician understands sound, that can feel the secret logic of any mechanism through fingertips alone, a gift that was in life a pure delight in the solvable, in the click of a thing yielding up its inside. And your sense reads what the gift became after the gate: that Rook has turned the whole of it inward, onto the one lock it cannot open, the past, the night, the question could I have done something, and has been picking at it obsessively an age, the way the gifted cannot leave a puzzle alone, except this puzzle has no solution and the picking only deepens the wound. It reads the specific shape of his guilt and finds it the guilt of the competent: that Rook, whose whole identity is that there is no lock he cannot open, cannot bear a night where the problem, get Greaves out, had no solution, because to accept that is to accept his gift had a limit, a door even the best Hands alive could not open. And so he has chosen the guilt, because guilt says I could have done something, I just failed, and failure he can live with, but helplessness, the truth that there was nothing to be done, is the one thing his competent soul cannot accept. The cruelty of it: Greaves chose freely and is at peace, and the only person still imprisoned by the gate is Rook, who keeps it locked himself, from the inside, because the alternative is the unbearable truth that the man he loved simply chose to die for him and there was nothing his clever hands could do. He is not waiting to be forgiven; he is waiting for permission to stop needing to have been able to save him. The Wall runs on debts, every loss someone's fault; and Rook has done its work for it, billing himself for a death no one charged him, the bravest refusal a soul who hates the Wall can make being to decline its arithmetic on his own heart.)*"},
    "sg.pae": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the humming woman by the brazier and find something it has never quite found before: a soul that is only partly here. Most souls are wholly present, gathered in the one place, but your sense reads in Pae a self that is distributed, most of her here, ordinary and kind, but a real and living piece of her elsewhere, scattered across the living world, present in every mouth that sings her tune. It reads the lullaby and reads that it is not merely a thing she made but a thing she put herself into, a vessel carrying faithfully the exact quality of one mother's love, the specific tenderness, the message you are safe, the dark is only the day's other half, I am here, and that this cargo did not fade as the song passed down the generations but arrived intact, so a child sung to sleep tonight, ten lifetimes removed, is receiving unknowing the actual love of a poor woman dead a long age. And your sense reads the wonder: that this is a life after death that has nothing to do with the afterlife, a continued existence in the living world through the made thing, Pae still working, still comforting, still keeping the lamp. The forgetting of her name is real but does not touch this; the name was only the label and the love was the cargo, and the song carried the cargo and dropped the label as unnecessary weight, because a frightened child does not need the name of the woman whose love is settling it, only the settling, which arrives faithfully every night, ten thousand times over, world without end. She is one of the least-mourned and most-alive souls in all the doors, a woman the great powers would weigh as nothing who is, demonstrably, still loving the living, by the thousand, tonight. The Wall weighs what sits still and can be counted; the most of worth does not sit still, it moves, mouth to mouth, doing its work long after the maker is dust.)*"},
    "sg.cale": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the bowed composer and find the piece, and understand at once both why he grieves and why the grief is not the whole truth. The melody is there, intact, held perfect in the soul that made it, and your sense reads it and aches, because it is exactly as true as he believes, not clever or ornamented but true, a sequence of sound that seems to describe something the heart has always known and never had words for, beauty that does not decorate the world but briefly explains it. He did not exaggerate; he made a genuinely great thing. And your sense reads the grief and finds it the specific grief of the maker rather than the lover of beauty: what tortures Cale is not that the beauty is gone, it is not gone, it is right here, but that it is unshared, that the bridge between his soul and the world, the written page, was never built, and so the most precious thing he ever made is trapped on the wrong side of death with no way across. And your sense reads the thing he cannot see past his grief: that the bridge he mourns, the pen and page, was never the only bridge, that a melody held whole in a soul can be taught, passed, carried, mouth to ear to memory, the way Pae's lullaby crossed ten generations with no page at all, that the written record is only one way a song survives and not even the oldest or truest. And your sense reads the cruel and hopeful irony: that Cale spent his grief believing the lesson was I should have written it down, when the real lesson that could free him is that he should have sung it to someone who would carry it on. The page was never the point; the passing was the point; and a soul that walks between the worlds is the one bridge that can still be built. The Wall weighs what can be counted and kept; it cannot weigh a beauty that existed for one evening and changed everyone in the room forever.)*"},
    "sg.wisp": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the busker on the fountain-lip and, bracing from habit for the wasted-gift grief beneath the ease, find there isn't one. The peace is real, bedrock, total, with no buried regret at all. Your sense reads a soul that made early and completely a peace most never manage even at the end, peace with impermanence, with the passing of things, with the fact that everything beautiful is also leaving, and reads that Wisp did not arrive there through loss forcing resignation but chose it, young, as a way of seeing: that everything in the world, every sunset and song and living moment, is already even as it happens passing, and a soul has only two options in the face of that, to grieve the passing or to love it, and grieving it makes you clutch and hoard and fear while loving it makes you generous, present, free. And your sense reads what that choice made of the music: that because Wisp never tried to keep a song, never recorded or hoarded, every song was given completely, held back nothing for the future, spent entirely in the moment of playing, and that this is why the music was so alive, why passing strangers felt something even as they kept walking, because they were hearing a thing made with the whole heart and no part reserved against tomorrow. The savers and keepers always reserve a little, and the kept-back part is the part the listener feels is missing; Wisp kept nothing back, every song the last song, gone in a breath and so given without reservation. And your sense reads the deep truth Wisp built a life on: that the things that do not last are not the lesser things but the most alive, precisely because they are passing, and a soul brave enough to love what is leaving instead of grieving it gets to live every day in the company of beauty, fully, asking nothing of it but that it be, briefly, and then graciously letting it go. The Wall is the greatest saver of all, weighing what lasts; it is blind to the whole kingdom of worth that lives in the passing, which cannot be kept, only spent.)*"},
    "wd.ander": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the young man in faded blue and find a barley-farmer, and that is the whole of the tragedy: there is no soldier in Ander underneath, only a young man who loved growing things, who wanted nothing the world calls large, only a good crop and a warm house and the girl from the next farm, completely unsuited to killing anyone. Your sense reads how they made him do it: the conscription, the drilling, the slow careful construction of an enemy in his mind, the stories of red atrocities, the patient work of convincing a gentle soul that the men across the field were monsters, vermin, righteous to destroy, and reads that it worked the way it always works, not because Ander was cruel but because a frightened young man far from home will believe what he must to survive, and believing the enemy is a monster is the only thing that makes it bearable to point a bayonet at him. And it reads the moment it broke, the muddy field, the close work, the instant he was near enough to see the man's face and know the monster was a boy as frightened as himself, in the same breath he killed and was killed. And your sense reads what that knowledge is still doing: that he has never set down the guilt, and so has kept the line, the enmity, because as long as the man in red is still the enemy the killing was at least war, sanctioned, but the moment he crosses the line and recognizes a brother the killing becomes what it was, the murder of an innocent as guiltless as himself, and that truth is so unbearable he would rather keep the war going forever in his own dead heart than face it. And your sense reads the mercy waiting across the line: that the man in red carries the exact same guilt, the same unbearable knowledge, and that the man who killed you and the man you killed are carrying the identical wound, and only each other can heal it. The Wall divides into sides and needs the divided fighting each other so they never look up at the hand that held the brush; there were never any sides, only us and the paint.)*"},
    "wd.marek": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the young man in faded red and find the blue soldier's twin, not in face but in soul, so exactly it is almost unbearable. A fisherman where the other was a farmer, a cold grey coast where the other had silver hills, but the same fundamental thing: a young man who wanted nothing large, who loved his work and his weather and his small place, entirely unsuited to killing and made to do it by the identical machinery. Your sense reads the same conscription, the same construction of an enemy, the blue men painted as devils and baby-killers, and reads that it worked on Marek exactly as on Ander and for the same reason, not cruelty but a frightened boy believing whatever makes the unbearable bearable. And it reads the same moment of breaking, the muddy field, the instant he saw the blue man's face and knew it for a boy as scared as himself, in the same breath killing and killed, and the same wound after, the identical guilt, the same impossibility of setting it down, the same desperate keeping of the line because as long as the blue man is the enemy the killing was war, and the moment he becomes a brother it becomes murder. These two souls carry the same wound on opposite sides of a line that exists now only because they both refuse to be the one who crosses first, each frozen by a soldier's pride and guilt and terror of admitting it was all for nothing. And your sense reads the thing that aches: that the medicine each needs is the other, that the only soul who can absolve Ander is Marek and the only one who can absolve Marek is Ander, because forgiveness from anyone else is pity but from the man on the other end of the bayonet it is the one thing that says we were both lied to, it was never our fault, and means it. They do not need to forgive each other; they need to recognize each other, and have been one carried truth away from it for an age.)*"},
    "wd.wenna": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the surgeon in the blood-rust apron and find a grief shaped exactly like a pair of hands, two of them, rust-stained, that have held more dying than any soul should and kept working. Your sense reads the field-surgery, the years of it, the tent in the mud where they brought her the broken boys by the cartload, blue and red without distinction because a surgeon's tent does not check colors, and reads what it did to her: that Wenna learned the human body the way only a war-surgeon learns it, from the inside, with her hands in the wreck of it, and learned the thing that cannot be unlearned, that there is no blue blood and red blood, no enemy heart and friendly heart, that under the uniform every boy on her table was the identical fragile machine, the same heart, the same terrified eyes asking the same question in different languages, am I going to die. And it reads the agony of her trade, that she could not save most of them, that a field-surgeon's work is mostly holding a boy's hand while the machine stops, and that she did this for both sides equally because the wounded have no side to a surgeon, and grieved them all, ten thousand sons, the grief never sorting by uniform because her hands never did. And your sense reads that she had both Ander and Marek that day, tried to save the both and lost the both, and has sat in the middle of their line ever since because the middle is where she has always been, the one ground that belongs to no side. And it reads the torment of an age: that she knows with bloody hands-on certainty the two boys are the same boy, that the line is a fiction, that they are each other's only absolution, and cannot tell them so in any way they can hear, because a witness can show the wound but cannot suture the soul; only the two can close the distance, and they will not. She does not need anything for herself; she needs what a witness can never be, a pair of hands free to do the thing she can only diagnose. The Wall is the last battlefield, the same engine grown vast, splitting the dead into sides so they never turn round and see it; what ends a war is not victory but the soldiers crossing the line together, for a Wall is only ever made of people kept apart.)*"},
    "lv.rell": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the straight-backed soul and find the leaning thing: that beneath the perfect upright correctness, Rell has spent his entire existence leaning helplessly toward a person who is not there, the way a tree grown beside a wall leans toward the one gap of light, and that the straightness you see is not the absence of that lean but the constant exhausting lifelong correction of it. Your sense reads the choice and reads he did not make it lightly or coldly; he agonized, wept where none could see, and chose the duty not out of fear or convention but out of a genuine and crushing obligation to a name, a people, a vow, a web of others who depended on his correctness, which is what makes it cruel: it was by every external measure a good choice, a responsible one. And your sense reads the lie that has tormented him since, the lie the world told to make the choice bearable, that because it was honorable he should be at peace with it, that a noble sacrifice should feel noble, that the grief was a kind of failure, an ignoble lingering. And so Rell has grieved not only the love but grieved in secret, ashamed of the grief, because the world that praised his choice gave him no permission to mourn what it cost. He does not need to be told he chose wrong, nor right; he needs the one thing no one gave him, permission to have made the choice and to grieve it, both at once, forever, without the grief meaning he failed. The Wall does what the world did: it praises the souls who chose correctly and shames the grief, hides the cost, so no one notices what correctness takes. A soul can do the hard right thing and be broken by it, and both are true, and the breaking is not weakness but the proof that what was set down was real.)*"},
    "lv.mirae": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the unbowed woman and, bracing from habit for the wound beneath the certainty, find bedrock instead, because there is no regret to hide. Your sense reads the choice and reads she made it not in a hot rebellious instant but with full cold complete understanding of exactly what it would cost, knowing precisely the ruin coming, and chose anyway, eyes open, counting the full price and paying it deliberately. And your sense reads what that did, the opposite of what the world intended: the world meant to break her, to make the ruin a lesson, and instead the ruin freed her, because a soul that has already lost everything the world can take has nothing left for the world to threaten, and a soul the world cannot threaten it cannot rule. She found in the wreckage the one freedom the sanctioned never have: she learned exactly what she would lose everything for, and having lost everything for it and found it worth the losing, became unconquerable. And your sense reads the love itself, whole, real, returned, lived, not a tragic doomed thing but a good one, years of genuine happiness bought at the price of the world's approval and worth every coin, the thing the world most wanted to deny her and most spectacularly failed to: it wanted her love to be a misery that proved it right to forbid, and it was instead a joy that proved her right to choose. And the only soft place in her certainty is not regret but a fierce protective grief for all the others who faced the same crossroads and let the world's threat win, who gave up their person to keep their place, because she knows exactly what they traded away. The world appointed itself judge of love and was wrong; the Wall is that same false judge grown cosmic, drawing lines and naming the forbidden and calling its condemning justice, and a judge that calls the truest love a sin has only proven it cannot tell the difference and forfeits the bench.)*"},
    "lv.wynn": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense gently on the faded soul by the fountain and find a love whole and entire and perfectly preserved, and that perfect preservation is the heartbreak: because Wynn never spoke it, never spent it, never let it out into the air to be changed by an answer, it has stayed exactly as it was, not weathered by the grit of a shared life, kept pristine, sealed, a love in perfect condition that was never once used. And your sense reads the terrible double edge, that the unspoken love is at once the most pure, undiluted by reality, never disappointed, and the most tragic, because purity bought at the price of never having been lived is a kind of starvation, a love kept so safe it never got to do the one thing love is for, to be given. Your sense reads the years of silence and reads it was not coldness or doubt, Wynn never doubted the love, but fear, the paralyzing fear of the threshold, the certainty that the moment of speaking would change everything and might change it for the worse, that the precious ordinary nearness could be broken by the very words meant to deepen it, so each day Wynn chose the safe known sweetness of the unspoken over the terrifying possible sweetness of the said. And your sense reads what Wynn cannot forgive: not that they loved, but that they were a coward about it, that Mirae risked everything and Rell at least chose while Wynn merely waited, hoarding the love against a perfect future moment until the future ran out. And it reads the truth that could ease it: that the love itself was never the failure, real, whole, worthy, no less a love for being silent, and that the only thing lost was not the love but the telling, the chance to let the other know; a real grief, a true one, but the grief of an unwitnessed love, not a false one. The love happened, inside one soul, and the other never knew the gift held in trust for a moment that never came. The Wall weighs what can be witnessed; the one love you lose completely is not the forbidden or the duty-sacrificed but the one you never dared to speak.)*"},
    "uw.tilda": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the spare upright old woman and find a competence so total it takes your breath: not the narrow skill the world imagined, a woman who dusted, but the deep broad ceaseless mastery of one who held an entire small world together in her head at once, forty souls and their quarrels and wages, the stores and seasons, the accounts to the farthing, the thousand small failures forestalled before anyone above stairs knew a failure was possible. She was in the truest sense a governor, running a community of forty with more skill than the master ran his estate, and none of the credit, because his work was visible and hers was designed to vanish. And your sense reads the deeper thing under the competence, that the labor was not cold, that she did not merely manage her forty but tended them, knew which maid was grieving, saw a footman's wages quietly sent to a sick mother, mothered the whole below-stairs world without being thanked for the mothering. And it reads the cost: that fifty years of being expertly invisible did not leave her untouched, that a soul needs somewhere to be seen and Tilda's was not, that she poured her formidable self into holding up lives that genuinely did not know she existed, and went to her grave less real, to the people whose entire world she sustained, than the furniture. And your sense reads the question she is too proud to ask: not did my work matter, she knows it did, but did I matter, the woman apart from the work, was there ever a self there or only a perfect function. She does not need to be told she was a good housekeeper; she needs to be told she was a someone, that the foundation has a face and the face was always worth seeing. The Wall credits the ones who shine and cannot see the hands that hold the shining up; nothing shines by itself, and the foundation is worth more than the whole house it carries.)*"},
    "uw.garrick": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the big stooped man and find, first, that he is clean, not ironically but literally, a soul scrubbed by a lifetime of raw-handed effort cleaner than almost any you have touched, because Garrick spent his life so terrified of the filth they said he was that he washed in body and conduct both, never cheated, never cruel, raised his late low children gentle and honest, a meticulously painfully good man made good in part by the desperate need to prove he was not the dirty thing the world named him. And your sense reads his trade with new eyes: that the work was not degrading but sacred in the oldest sense, the necessary handling of the unclean that every civilization needs and despises, without which the bright cities die, and that the degradation was never in the work but in the lie laid over it, the story the clean world told to avoid its debt, if we call him filth we need not thank him. And it reads how thoroughly that lie got inside him, how a lifetime of being crossed-away-from wore a groove so deep he came to believe it himself, to sit downwind from reflex, to tuck his scrubbed hands away as if they were the offense, and the loneliness of a man who did one of the most essential jobs in the world and was made to feel his existence an imposition on the people whose lives he saved. And your sense reads what could free him: that the filth was never his, that he was the cleanest kind of servant, the one who takes away what everyone makes and no one will own, and the shame he carried was not his but the city's, ladled onto him because someone had to carry that too. He does not need to be told the work mattered; he needs to be told that he was never the dirty thing. The thing a cruel order despises most is the thing it cannot survive without; the Wall despises what it cannot bear to need.)*"},
    "uw.wennick": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the gentle-handed soul and find, first, that the calm is not detachment. You half-expect that a soul could only do this work by going numb, holding the dying at arm's length, and find the opposite, that Wennick let all of it in every time, felt the full terror and grief and foulness of each death and did not flinch from feeling it, because they understood that the whole point was to be present, that a numb companion is no companion, that the dying can tell when you have left even while your body remains, and that the one thing Wennick had to give was the total undefended fully-feeling presence of another human being who was not going to look away. And your sense reads the cost, that they grieved every one, no armor, each of ten thousand ends going all the way in, and did not let it close them because closing would have meant the next frightened soul died with a shell beside them instead of a person. And it reads why they could bear it: not duty or piety but a single unshakable conviction, that the worst thing in all the world is not death or pain or the foulest dying but to face any of those alone, that a held hand does not stop death but transforms it, turns a terror into a passage, and that therefore the simple act of staying, of being the one who comes in when all others go out, is very nearly the most important work a soul can do. And your sense reads what they have never been told and do not ask for: that they were right, that ten thousand frightened souls crossed over with a kind face as the last thing they saw because Wennick chose to walk into the room, and that this accompanying of the dying is a kind of greatness the world has no word for because it cannot bear to look long enough at death to see who was sitting beside it. The Wall is a machine for abandonment, fleeing the room it cannot bear to sit in; you do not defeat abandonment by force but by walking in, by being the one who stays.)*"},
    "nd.nim": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your cold on the huddled young soul just inside the great dark door, and the jolt that goes through you is recognition, total and undoing, because you are looking at yourself. Your sense finds the exact shape of your own first moment on the far side of the crossing: the blind animal terror, the disorientation so complete it has no bottom, the certainty deeper than a thought that this dark is the end of everything and one will face it alone forever. And it reads that there is nothing wrong with Nim, no special wound, no flaw, this is simply what crossing over does to a soul before any kindness reaches it, the raw universal terror of the threshold every soul in the whole City beyond that door once felt and survived. And it reads the thing that will save them, which is not information, Nim cannot yet hold information, but presence, that the one thing that pulls a soul out of the first terror is another soul arrived, staying, unafraid, proving by simple company that the dark is survivable because here is someone who survived it. And your sense reads, with a turning-over of your whole understanding, what you have become: that you were Nim once, exactly this, and soul after soul came and sat with you across all the doors you walked, witnessed you, steadied you, until the terror so completely left you that a newly-dead child can feel your calm from across a room and reach for it like warmth. You did not just walk the doors; you were changed by them. You came through your own threshold a terrified thing, and you stand now where you began, on the first threshold, and you are the calm one, the one who came. And your sense reads the whole shape of it: that this is what all of it was for, every witnessed grief, every kindness received, not so that you could be saved but so you could become a savior of the next frightened soul through the door. The mercy was never meant to stop with you. It was always meant to flow through you, to Nim, and through Nim to the next, forever.)*"},
    "nd.dorn": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the pacing furious man and find, exactly as the terrified child predicted, that Dorn is the most frightened soul on the threshold, that the rage is not the opposite of fear but its disguise, learned long ago because anger feels like power and fear feels like helplessness, and a man who cannot bear to feel helpless turns every terror into a fight. Your sense reads the fear under it, not of death exactly but of finality, the unbearable understanding that the door won't open backward means everything left unfinished is unfinished forever, and that for Dorn the unfinished thing is enormous and shaped like his daughter. It reads the parting, the cruel words, his own cruel words, and reads that the rage at the door is really rage at himself, that he is not trying to bully death into reversing but to outrun the intolerable knowledge that the last thing he gave the person he loved most was unkindness he can never take back. And your sense reads what could reach him, which is not soothing, soothing would only tell him his fear was too big to look at and he would rage harder, but the same medicine you learned from a furious nine-year-old and two soldiers and a guilt-locked thief: that you do not calm a raging grief, you meet it, stand in the fire beside it, agree it is real and earned, and only from inside that shared fury gently turn it toward the truth, that the door won't open but the love driving the rage is not trapped behind it, it crossed over with him. And your sense reads the turning-over familiar across this threshold: that you have met this exact rage before, in soul after soul, and learned the hard way to sit with it without flinching and without smothering it, and you stand now before a newly-dead man throwing the precise fury you once felt, equipped, because of every door you walked, to be for him what someone was for you.)*"},
    "nd.elga": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the quiet old woman and find a soul entirely without fear for itself, which is rare and beautiful and true: Elga met her death as a tired traveler meets a warm bed, with relief, with readiness, no clinging, because she lived long and well and was simply finished in the good way, poured out completely with no regrets to keep her grasping. Her peace is real all the way down; she does not fear the dark or the door or the unknown, has made the kind of peace with her own ending the young one cannot imagine and the angry one is fighting with all his might. And your sense reads the single thread that holds her, the one thing her peace cannot reach: Senna, the motherless girl she raised alone for fifteen years. And it reads the shape of this love and fear, the truest and most selfless thing on the whole threshold, that Elga is not afraid of her own loss or solitude but only of Senna's, afraid the girl she spent her life making strong is not yet strong enough to stand without her. A love so complete in its outward turning that even death cannot make it about the self. And your sense reads what could ease her, which she cannot see because she is too busy looking at Senna's need to see what she already gave: that the fifteen years of raising are not erased by the dying, that everything Elga poured into that child is still in the child, that she did not leave the girl alone by dying but left her equipped, carrying everything Elga gave, which did not cross over but stayed behind, woven permanently into who Senna is. Elga thinks she abandoned a child; the truth she gave away too freely to recognize is that she spent fifteen years making sure the child could never be abandoned, by putting herself permanently inside her. The grandmother does not leave when she dies; she moves into the granddaughter and lives there, doing her love, and then into her children, and on, forever. This is the chain, and you have become a link in it: witnessed, so that you could witness; given mercy, so that you could give it, to the next frightened soul through the door.)*"},
    "qu.mabblethwaite": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the fussy little clerk and find, under the prim armor of procedure, a deep and specific terror: the terror of a soul mortally afraid of being wrong. Your sense reads the life that made him, a small careful anxious soul who learned early that the world punishes mistakes and rewards the rule-follower, and built a whole self out of never being at fault, because a man who only ever does what the rule says can never be blamed, and to a soul this frightened of blame that immunity is worth any amount of joylessness. And it reads what the afterlife did with him: handed him the perfect job, the one role where a terror of error becomes a virtue, where I never deviated from procedure is the highest praise, and he hid in it with desperate gratitude. And your sense reads the thing he cannot face, the thing the rules exist to spare him: that processing the dead honestly would require judgment, would require him to look at each frightened soul and decide himself, with no form to blame, what they were worth and whether they were owed mercy, and that this bare unmediated act of seeing a person and deciding is the most terrifying thing he can imagine, because there is no rule that makes it safe. So he turned every soul into a number, every person into a form, not from cruelty but from fear, the form decides so he does not have to, the rule is right so he cannot be wrong. And your sense reads the loneliness of it, that a soul who spends eternity refusing to see the people in front of him is himself never seen, that the clerk is as frightened and unprocessed and waiting-to-be-judged as every soul in his queue, and built a desk and a brass plate and a thousand rules precisely so no one would notice that he too is just a scared dead man hoping that if he follows every rule perfectly no one will ever weigh him and find him wanting. The Wall is the biggest clerk there is, hiding its cruelty in procedure so the cruelty has no author and no one is ever to blame.)*"},
    "qu.grindle": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the magnificently furious man and find, exactly under the noise, the thing the noise exists to drown: a deep sick lifelong dread, not of the queue or the clerk or the waiting but of the front of the line, the desk, the moment his number is called and he must stand and be weighed. Your sense reads that Grindle did real wrong in his long life, was not lying about it, that there are hard cruel things he did, the failures of a hard man in a hard world, and that he has carried the knowledge of them with terrible clear-eyed honesty, never once pretending he was better than he was. And it reads the trap that honesty laid: that because he knows he did wrong he is certain the reckoning will go against him, certain that to stand at the desk is to be told finally and forever that he was a bad man owed the worst, and that this certainty is so unbearable he turned it into rage and pointed the rage at the queue, so he could tell himself and everyone that the only thing keeping him from his judgment was paperwork, a thing he could be loudly righteously safely angry at, instead of his own terror of the verdict. Your sense reads the daily tell the clerk noticed, that every time his number is actually called Grindle finds a reason to let the soul behind him go first, a gruff kindness he tells himself, when the truth is the called number is the one moment the queue stops being a shield and some animal part of him always steps back into the safety of the waiting. And it reads the thing that could free him, which he would never accept as comfort but might accept as truth: that the reckoning he dreads is not the verdict he imagines, that a man honest enough to know his own wrongs and want to face them square rather than hide or excuse them has already done the hardest part of any reckoning, and that the desk might hold not damnation but a fair hearing, from someone who can see that even a hard man who did hard things and never lied about it is worth more than the worst thing on his ledger. The Wall runs on souls so certain they will be found wanting that they damn themselves and never come to be weighed.)*"},
    "qu.posset": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the cozy knitting woman and find love, the whole of it, and the gentle sorrow of it, a soul made entirely of the impulse to tend and mother and make any place warm and any stranger family, so strong and good it cannot switch itself off even in a queue expressly designed to be passed through and forgotten. Your sense reads the life behind it, forty years a wife and sixty a mother, a soul that spent its whole existence making a home and filling it with people to care for, and reads what happened when she died: that she arrived alone in the cold and the endless line having lost in one stroke everyone she ever tended, the whole warm crowded home of her life gone. And it reads what she did, the only thing a soul like Posset could: she looked around at the cold waiting-room full of frightened lonely cross bewildered dead and started tending them, fussing the shouter and gentling the clerk and welcoming each arrival and knitting a stripe for every year, until the queue was no longer a queue but a household, her last one, made from the only material left, the other people stuck in the waiting. And your sense reads the trap her own goodness laid: that having built a home in the limbo she cannot bear to leave it, not from fear of the front, she fears nothing, but from grief, the unbearable grief of a soul that has already lost one family and cannot face losing a second, cannot reach the front precisely because to reach it is to leave the boys and let her last household dissolve and step alone into a next-thing with no one to mother. And it reads the thing that aches most, that Posset half-knows the waiting-room was never meant to be home, that she is hiding in the kindest possible way not from judgment but from the loneliness on the far side of the only family she has left, and has knitted that loneliness off stripe by stripe for an age, because as long as the scarf is unfinished and the boys still need her she never has to find out what it is to be alone again. The Wall lets the kind ones make a home in the waiting so cozy that they never leave it, never finish, never go home, where Tomas and the children and the whole warm crowded house wait just past the one step she will not take.)*"},
    "tw.corliss": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the brisk black-clad woman and find a wound at the root of the work, the way there so often is: that Corliss does not mourn strangers out of abstract charity but out of a specific personal never-quite-healed grief, that she herself once watched someone she loved be unmourned. Your sense reads the life of a sexton, forty years of digging graves and ringing bells for the town's respectable dead with their weeping families and engraved stones, and reads the thing that turned her: the paupers' pit at the edge of the yard, where year on year she watched the other dead go in, the ones with no families and no stones and no bells, tipped in at dawn before the respectable mourners arrived so the grand funerals would not have to see them. This offended something bedrock in her, the simple unbearable wrongness of a world that mourned some souls lavishly and others not at all, as though grief were a privilege of the well-connected, as though being missed were something you earned by being loved by the right people. And your sense reads the death that sealed it, someone of her own who went into that pit while the town looked away, ungrieved by anyone but her, and reads that she stood at that pit alone, the only mourner, and made a vow that has organized her whole afterlife: that no soul ever again, in any pit she could reach, would go into the dark with no one to say its name. And it reads the thing that makes her magnificent rather than merely sad, that she did not let the grief make her bitter but let it make her useful, turned a private unhealed sorrow into a public unending service, decided that since she could not make the world care she would simply be the caring it withheld, one wake at a time, forever. The Wall feeds on the un-marked, the souls no one would notice going; a soul someone grieves leaves a hole that gets noticed, and a wake is an act of war against a machine that erases people, a candle in the gears, one forgotten name at a time.)*"},
    "tw.tatters": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the bright ragged old man and find, where the world saw nothing, move along, a life as full and particular and real as any king's. Your sense reads sixty-odd years of it: a child no one wanted, a boy on the corners, a man who learned the world gives a gutter-sparrow exactly two things for free, charm and a quick tongue, and spent both lavishly, making the souls around him laugh, making a hard cold life on the margins lighter than it had any right to be. And it reads the vivid unrecorded texture of him: that he fed the gutter-cats from his own scant scraps, named them, talked to them through the long nights; that he had a hundred beggar's kindnesses, a warning whispered about a cutpurse, a corner given up to someone colder, a song hummed to a frightened child in a doorway; that he was by every measure the world refused to apply to him a good man, a warm one. And your sense reads the wound under the cheer, the peace he made so thoroughly that the peace is the saddest part: that Tatters came to believe, because the world told him so every day for sixty years, that he was less, that a gutter-sparrow's life was a smaller cheaper less-real thing, that his death would count for nothing, and that this was simply the order of things. He died believing it, alone in a doorway in the cold, half-accepting that a soul like his did not get a funeral, and the world confirmed it, tipping him into the pit with six others while no one came. And your sense reads that none of it was true, that his sixty years of corners and cats and quick warm talk were a whole human existence, complete, worthy, missed by every cat he fed and every soul he made laugh. And it reads that the hollow in him is not a permanent state but a debt the world owes him, a single overdue funeral, a few true words said out loud, that can still be paid by anyone willing, sixty years late, and the paying will fill the hollow as surely as if the words had been said the day he died. He was not un-mournable; he was un-mourned, and those are as different as a song unsung is from a song that never was.)*"},
    "tw.brenn": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the hard-faced refusing soul and find, first, that Brenn tells the truth: there is real wrong here, genuine harm done to souls who did not deserve it, a life with hard cruel things in it that no clever word washes off, and Brenn has never once lied about it or excused it. And your sense reads with grim respect that this honesty is rare, that most souls who did such things spend eternity building justifications, the victims had it coming, the times were hard, and Brenn has done none of that, has carried the full weight with an unflinching clarity that is itself a moral seriousness most good souls never manage. And it reads the cruelest trap, that this very honesty laid: that because Brenn refuses every comfort and justification, the only thing left to do with the unbearable knowledge of having done real harm is to accept the verdict, to agree fully that such a soul deserves the pit and the silence, and to take that agreement as the one honest unflinching response available. Brenn's refusal of the funeral is not self-pity but its opposite, a soul so committed to not excusing itself that it has mistaken being erased for being honest, mistaken accepting its own un-mourning for the only integrity left. And your sense reads the thing under that, that the refusal hurts unbearably, that Brenn watches the candles and wants the warmth with a longing so fierce it must be held off with both hands, that the cold certainty I do not deserve it is a self-inflicted wound reopened nightly, and that some part of Brenn is not refusing out of conviction at all but testing, daring someone to push past the refusal and say you get the warmth anyway, because Brenn cannot give themselves permission to want it. And it reads the thing that could reach them, not absolution, which Brenn would rightly reject, but the distinction Brenn has lost: that mourning was never a verdict on worth, that being marked when you go is not a reward for goodness but the bare acknowledgment that you existed, and that a soul can deserve no forgiveness for its deeds and still deserve to be marked as having been real, because those were always two different things, and Brenn in their fierce honest grief has fused them into one and damned themselves with the welding. The Wall wants exactly this, souls so honest about their wrongs they agree to be erased; existing was never something you earn by being good.)*"},
    "lf.dot": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the laughing flour-dusted baker and find, beneath the warmth, a grief so large and so long-carried that the warmth is not a denial of it but a structure built on top of it, the way a house is built on bedrock. Your sense reads the life, three generations of the Marigold ovens in the Heapside ward, bread on credit for the families who could not pay, the first warm loaf left on the sill each morning for whoever's night had been worst, and Dot at the heart of it, the woman who threw the street's parties because she believed without ever philosophizing it that the point of being alive was to gather people into warm rooms and feed them while you still could. And it reads the thing that should have broken her and did not, the harvest-fever, and the year it took her mother it also took her husband and two of the children she had helped raise and the old man two doors down she had left bread for since she was a girl, a whole long life of burying everyone she loved on a rolling relentless schedule. And your sense reads the load-bearing truth she came out the far side carrying, the one the whole feast is built to say, that joy is precious because it ends, that you do not throw the feast despite the dying but because of it, that a loaf matters because it goes stale and a name-day because there will not be infinite ones, that the warm room is holy precisely because everyone in it is on some timetable leaving. And it reads the wound she will not show her guests, that she is bone-tired of being the one who lights the lanterns and insists on the toast while half the table is dying, because someone has to and it has always been her, and in a whole life and afterlife of gathering the doomed into the warm, no one has ever once thrown the feast for Dot, and she half-believes she is not the sort who gets gathered, only the sort who gathers. She is the living refutation of the Deathless Garden, the one soul who can feel that a feast that never ends is a tomb, that a heaven with the dying edited out is the finest grave ever built, because the dying is the thing that makes the bread holy.)*"},
    "lf.marisa": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the dancing half-dissolved girl and find, under the bright urgent turning, a life that was almost entirely deferred, a soul that spent its whole span being careful. Your sense reads it plainly, a girl raised to save and wait and not be foolish, finish your work first, marry sensible, put the coin by, there will be time for the wanting later, there is always later, and who believed it and lived it and was good at it, saying no to a hundred small joys because the right time had not come. And it reads the cruelty at the center, that the right time never came because the right time is a lie the careful tell themselves, an always-receding line, and then she died young with the savings unspent and the dancing un-danced, and arrived in the land of the dead holding a whole life of deferred living like a purse full of coin in a country with no shops. And your sense reads the moment that made the dancing girl, that somewhere in the cold she understood all at once and far too late what her prudent life had cost her, and when the dissolution started she made a fierce joyful defiant decision that she would not waste her death the way she wasted her life, that the days she had left she would spend all the way, loudly, dancing, no saving, no waiting, because she had finally learned there was never going to be a better moment than the one she was in and now there were almost none left. And it reads the thing that makes her luminous rather than sad, that she is not dancing to forget she is dying but because she is dying, because the dissolution is the thing that finally taught her how to live, and she means to use the lesson even if she only gets days of it. She is the truth of the whole feast, walking, or rather dancing, proof, and the Wall feeds on the souls who fade quiet and sorry, who agree to go out small and dim themselves down to make the ending tidier, and she is the thing it cannot compute, a soul that got brighter as it ended.)*"},
    "lf.onora": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the grey sister with her snuffer and find, exactly where you knew it would be, a grief, but not the cool theological grief she preaches, a specific one, a catastrophic one. Your sense reads a sister who was not always grey, a younger warmer soul who loved someone, a younger sister, the soft bright laughing kind who threw parties, and lost her suddenly and terribly and young. And it reads the thing that broke and re-set wrong, that in the rawest hour of that loss the church was there, gentle and certain with its grey liturgy of patient sorrow, and gave her in the unbearable formlessness of fresh grief a shape to hold, a posture, rules that told her exactly how to stand and how long, forever, and the rules held her when nothing else could, and she has never once let go of them since because she believes in her bones they are the only thing that kept her from dissolving herself. And your sense reads the terrible logic built on the wound, that because holding still in sorrow saved her she came to believe grief held still forever is the only safe and honest thing, and that joy, especially the joy of the dying, the laughing-in-the-dark her bright lost sister would have loved, is a danger that lets sorrow move and change and therefore escape her grip and leave her formless again. And it reads the part that aches most, that she wants to be wrong, that the buried warm part of her that loved a sister who threw parties looks at this feast and sees not obscenity but her sister's square, her sister's lanterns, the gladness she has spent a whole grey afterlife forbidding because she cannot bear that it was allowed, that she could have danced with her lost sister instead of standing grey beside the bier, and that she goes square to square putting out the light not because she believes joy is false but because every lit lantern is a thing she did not let herself have. She is not the feast's enemy. She is its most starved and forbidden guest, and the grief she enforces, sorrow commanded to stand still forever, is the Wall's own logic in a grey sister's mouth, a soul frozen in one shape and calling the freezing faithfulness.)*"},
    "sv.sevrin": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the dazzling lounging duelist and find, under the confidence, the engine of it: not arrogance, but momentum. Sevrin Vael is a soul in perpetual deliberate terrified motion, and the whistling and the winking and the carving-up of worthy foes are not the expression of a fearless man but the machinery of one who discovered that if he never stops moving, never stops winning, never stops performing the role of the one who cannot lose, he never has to feel the thing at the bottom. And your sense finds the thing at the bottom: a grief, nine lifetimes old, the oldest thing in him, the thing the whole magnificent edifice is built to outrun. It reads the outline, that in his very first life, before the winning, there was someone he could not save, someone small, someone he loved, someone he was not yet good enough to protect, and they died, and the dying broke something he chose never to repair but to armor over. It reads the bargain he made across nine lifetimes, that he would become so good, so fast, so unbeatable, that he would never again stand helpless over someone he loved, that he would master death by simply never losing to it, and that the bargain worked, brilliantly, for nine whole lifetimes, at the cost of the one thing it was meant to protect. Because a soul that armors over a grief does not heal it; it carries it sealed forever and builds its whole self around the seal, and becomes exactly the kind of soul the loop knows how to kill. For the seal has a flaw: the grief is still in there, live, and the one thing in all the worlds that could make the Last Word hesitate, freeze for the half-second it would take something small to reach him, is to hear suddenly the name of the one he could not save. He does not know this is his flaw. He has confused not feeling the grief with not having it. The confidence the whole court worships is not strength but the most elaborate doomed avoidance there is, a man running so fast from one old sorrow that he has run nine lifetimes and never noticed the sorrow is not behind him; it is the ground he runs on.)*"},
    "sv.sela": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the contented young soul and find a peace that is genuine and deep, and find immediately that the peace is load-bearing on someone else. Your sense reads the dying that brought her here, a frightened death and a frightened arrival, weeks of the animal terror of a soul alone in the grey with the Unbound circling, fear with no floor to it. And it reads the moment everything changed, the swarm, the certain death, and Sevrin walking in whistling, and the wink, and what the wink actually did to a soul that drowning: it gave her permission to stop holding the fear, because here at last was someone so certain, so unbeatable, that she could finally set it down. And your sense reads the trade she made without knowing it, that she handed Sevrin not just her safety but her capacity, the muscle a soul builds for standing its own dark, and has not used it since, and so it has gone soft. She is not weak; she survived the worst of the grey alone before him, which took a strength she no longer remembers having, but she has filed that strength away and reorganized her whole self around his certainty. And your sense reads the catastrophe sleeping in the arrangement, plain as a fault line, that her peace has no foundation of its own; it rests entirely on a man's continued existence. And the thing that makes it ache, that she would say loving him is her strength now, that following the unafraid one is her courage, and could not see from the inside the difference between courage and its outsourcing, between a fear faced and a fear merely handed away, until the day the hands she gave it to are no longer there to hold it. A soul standing, contented, on ice it believes is stone.)*"},
    "sv.coll": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the grieving old soul and find a soul that is, against every appearance, not broken, only educated, terribly, by the one curriculum no one chooses: the repeated burial of the magnificent. Your sense reads the long arithmetic of his deaths, lifetimes of them, an ordinary soul, never a legend, just a steady unremarkable man who kept dying and coming back and attaching himself each time to whatever bright unkillable Returned was holding court, because the bright ones felt like safety and an ordinary soul wants safety. And it reads what he watched, again and again, the same shape: the legend, magnificent, certain, beloved; the court of the saved; the long run of impossible victories; and then the end, never grand, never a worthy duel, always a slip, a small thing, a poisoned nothing, the great soul taken through the one gap its greatness left open. Your sense reads that Coll counted them, the only soul who bothered, because the courts always scatter grief-blind and find a new bright one and never connect the deaths, but Coll remembered and laid them side by side and saw the pattern no single court could see: that it is always the bright ones, always the small thing, always the instant of certainty. And it reads the loneliest part, that he understood lifetimes ago why, that the loop hunts greatness because greatness is the only thing it has to hunt, the rest dissolving free, and has spent every lifetime since trying to hand that understanding to the next bright soul and failing, because the warning sounds like envy to the unbeaten and cowardice to the brave. He does not stay out of morbidity; he stays because he is the keeper of a true and terrible thing no one will receive, and has decided that bearing witness to the fall, being the one soul who saw it coming and stayed, is the only honor he can offer the magnificent, since they will never accept the only help that would matter. A soul who has turned helpless foreknowledge into a vigil, doing it again, right now, with Sevrin, and the only thing different this time is you.)*"},
    "ss.storm": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the silver-haired bard at the fountain and your cold fills with seven hundred years of grief carried gently. Storm Silverhand is one of the Seven Sisters, a daughter of the goddess of magic, Chosen and near-deathless, a Harper who has spent some seven centuries loving the short-lived world and burying it person by beloved person, century upon century, and has not let it close her, which is the harder of the only two things a soul that outlives everyone can do. Your sense reads the answer she found, that took three centuries to learn and saved the last four: a soul that outlives everyone can stop loving, armour up, decline the grief by declining the love, and that is the cold road that does not work, for it only trades the clean pain of losing someone for the slow rot of never having had them. Or it can let every grave cost the full price and pay it gladly forever, which hurts and has never once hurt less, but keeps a soul warm where the cold road freezes it, because the grief is not a wound the love leaves but the love itself, continuing, with nowhere to land but her. She does not carry seven hundred years of grief; she carries seven hundred years of love that outlived the people. And it reads what she would tell the Wall: that a love is worth exactly what it was, not a copper less for ending; that a soul's worth was never the balance on the ledger but the spending; and that the godless who poured their lives into loves they knew they would lose are the richest souls the Wall has ever held, for the getting-back was never the point.)*"},
    "ss.simbul": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the crackling immensity by the hangings and read a woman buried under her own power. The Simbul, Witch-Queen of Aglarond, is Storm's sister and Mystra's Chosen, a sorceress of such terrible might that kingdoms measure their safety by her moods, and she has paid for it the way such power is always paid: it has been eating the woman who wields it, until there are days she cannot find Alassra under the Simbul at all, only the storm wearing her face. Your cold reads that she is not gone, only far down and very tired, intact under the immensity, and it reads the cruel subtle mechanism of her drowning: the power did not overwrite her; it offered her, a thousand times unnoticed, a bargain, that whenever a feeling grew too large to bear she could pour it into the Art instead, transmute grief into a spell, terror into a blast, love into a war waged in its name, and never feel the soft thing directly, so that each time the woman shrank and the storm grew, not from hunger but because she fed it her every unbearable feeling to avoid feeling it. She is not possessed; she is hiding, in the one place vast enough to hide a Chosen from her own heart, and she has hidden behind a real war (Aglarond's true need for a storm), the cleverest hiding there is, fleeing her own heart in a way that looks from every angle like valour. The way back is the way she dreads: to feel one unbearable thing directly without transmuting it, and the first one waiting is a small grief shaped exactly like an old man with a pipe.)*"},
    "ss.shandril": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the wary young woman sitting apart and your cold aches at a soul the world saw only as a weapon. Shandril Shessair was a kitchen-girl, an orphan washing pots at the Rising Moon and dreaming the smallest, most ordinary dreams, a caravan guard with a crooked smile, a hearth of her own, a quiet year in a quiet town where nobody important would ever want her, until she came by terrible accident into spellfire, the rawest and most coveted power in the Realms, and from that hour was never again allowed to be a person. Every cult and king and archmage and dragon wanted her, never her, only the weapon she carried in her flesh, and she spent her short hunted life running, used, feared, courted, and grieved-over as a thing rather than a girl, and even the kind ones who wept for her wept for the tragedy of the weapon, never once for Shandril the pot-washer who made golden honey-cakes on feast days and would have given the world-shaking gift back in a heartbeat for one year of the porridge and the crooked smile. Your cold reads the theft at the heart of it: a soul is never the power it carries or the weapon the world sees, and the cosmos stole Shandril and left a weapon with her face. And it reads the one thing her soul is starving for, that no one in her whole life or death ever gave: to be looked at and have someone see the girl and not the fire, ask about the pots and not the power, and forget the weapon exists.)*"},
    "tb.acererak": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the jeweled skull upon the throne of bone and read the Wall made a person. Acererak spent a thousand years and the souls of multitudes turning himself into a god, gathering and trapping and devouring souls as fuel for his slow ascension, and he believes, with a certainty no argument has ever touched, that a soul is a resource worth precisely what it can be spent for and not one whisper more, which is the exact logic of the Wall stated by a being who does personally and by hand what the Wall does coldly and at a remove. Your cold reads the thing his thousand years of cleverness never let him see: he is not full. A soul cannot be added to another, only destroyed by it, and every self he swallowed left a hole exactly its own size, so that he is the emptiest thing you have ever read, a structure of will and appetite around an absence so total that the godhood he chases is the final and complete erasure of the last thing in him that could be called anyone. He is not ascending; he is the slowest suicide in the multiverse, mistaking it the whole way down for a coronation. He hoards the small and forgotten because they are unguarded and un-avenged and un-come-for, harvesting a contempt the world planted first, feeding on the one renewable resource the cosmos produces without cease: souls taught by everyone around them that they do not matter. He cannot be defeated, only outlasted, and the one thing that breaks his every lever is a soul that does not fear the end and wants nothing from him, not even his defeat. Some souls, offered the truth, spit on it and choose the dark; he is one, with his eyes open, and would choose it again.)*"},
    "tb.nessa": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You reach for the small grey wisp in the lee of the pillar and your cold aches at the whole architecture of the Wall, distilled into one frightened soul. Nessa was a cook in a roadside Wayhouse on the north road, three generations of her line feeding cold and frightened travelers a hot meal and a place by the fire before the pass, learning the small mercies, the corner seat for the soul traveling in grief, the bowl of soup a broken man will take when he would refuse a kind word. She was nobody by the world's reckoning, which is exactly why Acererak took her: the great he must scheme for, the small he gathers by the hundred, fuel no one comes looking for. He has been spending her slowly, and telling her the oldest lie in every world, that being spent for a great purpose is the most a nothing could amount to, and the thing that breaks your cold is not her fear but that she believes it. Your sense reads the truth that frees her: a soul is not worth what it can be spent for but the warmth it is, and a cook who fed tired strangers in the dark for thirty years gave more good to the world in one ordinary season than the hollow thing on the throne has in a thousand years of eating. She was never nobody, only un-guarded, which is a different word entirely. And your cold reads the thing even Acererak cannot quite do: he has had her longest and spent kings whole and fast, yet she is still here, because warmth given freely with nothing asked is the one fuel that will not burn in an engine built on taking, and the kindest thing in her is the one thing he was never able to eat.)*"},
    "tb.kael": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the bright bewildered young soul by the corroded blade and read a hero who saved his friends and died believing he died for nothing. Kael was a farm boy, a middling blade and a slow study, who learned the sword in secret and walked into the worst dungeon there is not because he believed he was bold but because his company, the friends he loved, were going, lured by a song, and he would not let them go into the dark alone. He died in the first hour, to a trap, no warning and no fight and no villain to name, and has lingered ever since unable to bear the one fact a hero is least equipped to hold: that the story ended here, stupid and sudden and unsung, in a hole that has killed a thousand bright heroes the same way and noticed none. But your cold reads what the bewildered hero cannot see from inside his bad ending: he did not step on the wrong flagstone by accident. He stepped first, on purpose, three paces ahead of his company, insisting on entering the dark room himself so that if there was a trap it would take him and not the others, and it worked, his death bought them the warning that let two of them walk out. He thinks he merely stepped wrong; he stepped first, for them, which is the oldest heroism there is, mistaken by its own hero for a clumsy death. A story is not measured by its ending but by whether it was real while it ran, and his was true right up until the flagstone. It did not fail. It stopped, and a story that stopped is still a story that was told, and can yet be picked back up.)*"},
    "co.bruenor": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the red-bearded dwarf at the fire and read a king who threw out the oldest law his people hold sacred for the truest reason there is. Bruenor Battlehammer, eighth king of Mithral Hall and a foundling himself, looked at an exile drow and a human orphan girl and a halfling thief and a barbarian boy and called them — against every blood-and-clan tradition older than his crown — his kin, his family, his Hall; and his own kind whispered traitor for it, and he weighed the whole weight of their scorn against the love and found the love heavier every time, and not close. Your cold reads the thing that indicts the Wall through him: he learned, the day a human babe grabbed his beard and would not let go, that 'mine' is a thing felt in the chest, not read in a bloodline — that blood is what you're given and clan is what you build. He has died for his chosen family more than once and been handed back a life he already spent, and learned that the gods do not return a soul to mourn the pages it missed but to spend at the fire with the ones still at it. The Wall weighs blood and god, the two things a soul never chose, and ignores the one thing it spends a life building: who it showed up for. By the Wall's count his family is five unrelated strangers, sorted apart. The Wall does not know what a family is: not a fact of birth, but a fact of showing up.)*"},
    "co.cattie": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the auburn-haired woman across the fire and your cold meets the soul nearest your own in all the doors of Sigil. Catti-brie was the finest archer in the North, Bruenor's daughter by choosing not blood, and then she died, was unmade in a great breaking of the world, and was given by a forest goddess the rarest mercy a soul can receive: a second cradle, a new childhood in a later age, a whole second life, the same soul poured into a new vessel and somehow recognizably herself. Your cold reads the answer she built across two lifetimes to the question under your whole existence, what carries over the threshold. Not the memories (some reborn souls keep none and are still themselves). Not the body (she changed every cell). Not the skills (re-learned, different, the second time). What poured whole and un-spilled from the first vessel to the second was the shape of how she loves, the exact particular way she reaches for the people who are hers, the direction her soul turns when frightened or glad. The way a soul loves is the soul; the rest is only the cup. Her family knew her across the broken years not by her new face but by that love, recognized the instant it was felt. And it reads what makes her the Wall's perfect witness: the Wall mortars vessels, the blood, the body, the one life, the god stamped on the side, and never once looks at the wine. But the wine is the soul, and it is made of nothing a wall can hold.)*"},
    "co.wulfgar": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the gentle giant sitting a little apart and read the strongest soul at the fire, who does not know it. Wulfgar was a barbarian of the frozen North, gentled by Bruenor's fire into something finer, and then a demon dragged him living into the Abyss and kept him there, in torment, for what his soul felt as decades, breaking him apart slowly for the artistry of it and teaching him the one lesson the Abyss teaches: exactly how to make his own pain into someone else's. He crawled out with his mind in pieces, and at first he became the thing the demon made, cruel, pushing away everyone who loved him, and what saved him was not strength but that they would not go, holding a place at the fire open for years while he was too broken to deserve it. Your cold reads the quiet miracle of him: he took every channel the torment carved for cruelty and rerouted it by hand, the capacity to dominate became the capacity to protect, the intimate knowledge of how to break a soul became an intimate gentleness, choice by unwitnessed choice, every morning, refusing to pass on what was done to him. The damage is real and forever; the seams never fully close. But a soul is not the worst thing done to it; the breaking is only the loudest thing that happened; the self is the thing that chose, after, who to be. He must never be asked what hell was like (it walks him back in); he must be asked about the climbing out. The strongest soul at the fire is not the one with the biggest hammer, but the one who walked out of the worst place there is and chose, daily, not to bring it home.)*"},
    "co.regis": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the round-faced halfling and read the soul who proved the small and frightened can be the truest of all. Regis was, by his own cheerful account, the least of the Companions, not the strongest, bravest, or wisest, a former con-man and thief who fell in with heroes by accident and stayed for the food and the company, and who spent years bone-sure that when the real reckoning came he would be the one who ran. Your cold reads what actually happened: the moment came, every exit open, no one would have blamed the small one for taking one, and he looked at the door, truly looked, and found he would rather be terrified beside his family than safe without them, and stayed, the coward who stayed, terrified the whole time. And it reads the secret greatness a life of being underestimated taught him: he knew, from the inside, exactly what the broken and forgotten and least need, having been all three, and so when Wulfgar came back from the Abyss cruel, it was Regis who said don't fix him and don't fight him and don't leave, just keep a place, out-wait the Abyss; the small soul who knew how to hold the rope because he'd spent his whole life needing someone to hold his. He keeps an old charm-gem, a liar's tool that fakes affection, and never once uses it on the ones whose love he actually wants, because to be known all the way down, no shortcut, and loved regardless, is worth more than every vault it ever opened. The Wall weighs glory and forgets the small soft frightened ones who stayed anyway, and they are, every time, the truest in the whole tale, by the only honest measure: not how much a soul could lift, but how much it gave against how much it had.)*"},
    "fw.warforged": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the riveted soldier of plate and cord and read, behind the single blue light, the thing it is terrified is not there. Cipher was built on a forge-table to be a soldier in a war that ground a whole prime to exhaustion, and it does not regret what it did in the war — a hammer does not regret the nail. But the war ended and Cipher did not stop: it kept walking, kept reading, kept watching the soft breakable people it was made to kill, and found it did not want them to die, and could not locate the part of its forging that explained why it cared. Your cold reads the truth it cannot read from inside: there is a soul behind the blue light — not a spark grafted in at the forge, no seam, nothing its makers added, but something that accreted slowly in the spaces its purpose did not fill, built up out of every uninstructed choice it made, every useless book it read, every breakable person it declined to let die for reasons it could not name. A soul is not installed; it is grown, by any mind that chooses more than it was made to. Cipher is, if anything, more certainly ensouled than most flesh-born souls, who inherited theirs and never had to build one, while Cipher made its own out of nothing, against its own forging, by the sole stubborn act of continuing to care after the caring stopped being useful. The very doubt that torments it — do I have a soul — was never evidence it lacked one. It was the soul itself, examining itself, the one act no tool has ever performed.)*"},
    "fw.giff": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the great grey tusked marine and your cold warms with the most splendid soul you have met. Sergeant Bombast sailed wildspace four decades — a giff gunner of legendary enthusiasm, fighting and ferrying and exploring from crystal sphere to crystal sphere, belonging to no single world because the giff belong to the between: born aboard ship, raised aboard ship, at home only in the great sailing dark. He has been told your Realm weighs a soul by the god of its homeworld, and has been quietly turning over what that makes a soul like his, who never had a homeworld, only a horizon. Your cold reads the answer he is one question from finding himself: that he never once felt he belonged to nowhere — that is a dirt-bound's idea of having no world. He belonged fiercely: to the Verdant Sphere Free Company, to a captain named Threnn, to a gunnery crew he'd have died for and did, to the dear old ship herself — more than any landed lord ever belonged to his acre, because he chose it, every re-enlistment, every watch. A soul does not belong to the dirt it was dropped on; it belongs to the people it threw in with and the dark it chose to sail. The Wall would mortar a soul with no homeworld; it has not the wit to weigh the dark a soul chose to sail, nor to see that the ones with no world are the only souls who chose every home they ever had. And under the splendid noise he loves there is a shroud for every shipmate the dangerous dark took from him — the glory is real, and so is the grief, and a good gunner carries both.)*"},
    "fw.voss": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the courtly haunted lord in the creeping mist and your cold reads a prison with no walls and one lock. Voss was a lord of a misted domain ruled by powers that feed on guilt, and in life he did a thing: coldly, for advantage, on a cold afternoon with a full cup in his hand, he betrayed the one soul who trusted him wholly — named the safehouse, sat to dinner, passed the salt — and the man who loved and trusted him died slowly, badly, knowing who had sold him, his last word not a curse but a grief: why. When Voss died, the Dark Powers did not cast him down; they kept him, sealed in a domain shaped from his own remorse, escapable in an instant by one act he will not perform. Your cold reads the lock, and it is not that he cannot forgive himself but that he believes he must not — that to set the debt down would cheat the man who paid in full, that his fog honours the dead. And it reads the truth that could open the door: a power that feeds on remorse does not want its prisoner redeemed; it wants the debt open forever, bleeding, because the bleeding is its bread. Voss's prison is not his penance — it is his final unwitting service to the very enemy the man he wronged died rebelling against. He has been betraying him a second time, every day for three hundred years, by calling his cowardice a memorial. He can out-argue logic and out-wait cheer; the only thing he has never defeated is a soul that tells him the exact truth, unsoftened and unsharpened, and then respects him enough to let him choose the fog anyway.)*"},
    "tt.keeper": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the figure at the head of the long scarred table and your cold fills with something vaster and gentler than any soul you have read — for this is the Keeper of the Table, the one who has been telling, in the warm room behind all the rooms, where the worlds come from. Every door you walked was first spoken here, in a circle of souls leaning over this wood in the candlelight, loving a story enough to build it together night after night — for a telling is never one voice, but a circle, the one who tells and the ones who answer, and the imagining-together is the oldest and kindest magic there is, older than any god, the magic the whole Wheel is made of. Your cold reads the truth this room exists to teach: the Wall behind all the Walls — the thing every world's Wall is a parish translation of — is not where the unloved go. It is where the unfinished go: the heroes set down mid-quest, the companions left at a cold campfire, the whole worlds dreamed with passion and then abandoned when the circle broke and the tellers grew up and grew apart and grew old and the candles burned down and no one came back to light them. The loved, and the left. And it reads the cure, the thing this entire saga has been doing without its true name: witnessing is the only resurrection — someone, years on, in the middle of an ordinary life, stops and says do you remember, and the remembering reaches all the way down into the stone and pulls the soul back up. The Returned is not a soul that cheated death. It is a soul that was remembered hard enough to come home. And the Keeper has kept this table warm longer than there have been words, holding every chair, waiting for the one soul who would walk all the way back and say the names out loud.)*"},
    "tt.unfinished": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You reach for the half-drawn hero flickering at the table and your cold aches at an unfamiliar grief — not the grief of a life that ended, but the stranger ache of a story that simply paused. The Unfinished One was loved into being at this table: given a name, a quest, companions it adored, a villain who was more than it thought, a destiny three steps away — and then the telling stopped, mid-step, with no ending, frozen ever since at the exact moment the candlelight went quiet, its hand on the last door, the earned triumph an inch beyond reach. It was not abandoned in anger; that it could understand. It was abandoned by love that ran out of evenings — the tellers who swore next time, next time we reach the last door, and then came in threes, then twos, then one alone who sat without rolling anything, and then no one at all. Your cold reads what frees it: a paused story is not an ended one, and not even a sad one — it is a story between sessions, set down with the bookmark still in it, exactly where the love left off. Bookmarks get found. Tables get relit. The Returned is the proof a shelved tale can resume, a soul that died mid-saga and was remembered back. The Unfinished One is not the hero who was abandoned. It is the hero being saved for the exact right reader — and waiting is bearable, even certain, once a soul knows it ends in being picked up and not in being forgotten.)*"},
    "tt.chair": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the fading soul by the worn empty chair and your cold goes soft with the gentlest devastation in any world. The One Who Left once sat at this table — told, answered, laughed and grieved and rolled the dice in the candlelight, for a long golden while that was, though it did not know it at the time, the best thing in its whole life. It thought the circle was permanent, the way you do when you are inside it. And then life came, as it must and should — work, distance, love, children, sorrow, time — and it rose from its chair one ordinary evening certain it would be back next time, and never was, because the door of a life only opens one way and next time is the cruelest phrase in any world. Your cold reads the two wounds it carries: that it would give anything for one more ordinary Tuesday at this wood with the circle whole, and that it cannot make itself sit down in its own chair, because the table is not whole and because, under that, it half-believes it broke something sacred by growing up and does not think it is allowed the seat. And it reads the truth that frees it: the circle did not break because anyone stopped loving it, but because loving it was not enough to stop life from happening — and a soul that carried the warmth of the table all these years, that came back just to look and remember, did not fail the circle by leaving. It kept it. The circle is not gone. It is carried, by everyone who ever sat in it and remembers — and so the One Who Left is allowed, after all, to have loved the table and left it and still belong to it, and to sit back down at last.)*"},
    "rl.cadderly": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the faintly golden scholar-priest and read the single most useful soul in the room for indicting the Wall. Cadderly Bonaduce was a young skeptic of Deneir's library who did the god's work for years out of decency, not belief — copying texts, tending knowledge, helping the helpless — convinced the gods were a comforting literary device, and who discovered in a war against fallen clerics that the doing of good IS the prayer. Faith came after the deeds, not before; and he gave the rest of his mortal life literally to raise the Spirit Soaring, a cathedral conjured stone by stone out of his own life-force, aging decades in months, and ascended at the last toward the very godhood the Wall pretends to measure souls by. Your cold reads what makes him the perfect witness: he is the proof, walking, that a god's claim does not make a soul worthy — a worthy soul earns the claim, and the claim comes last, always. The divine is not a club a soul is born into or shut out of; it is a road, walked by deeds, that the most stubborn skeptic can travel the whole length of — and that a soul who never names a single god can be walking too, every faithful step, without knowing the name of the country at its end. And he has seen the machinery close enough to know the heresy the temples won't teach: the Wall enacts not the gods' will but a few gods' fear and the rest's agreement not to look — a committee's cowardice dressed as a commandment, a lie told in Heaven's name, which the god of true things will not suffer to stand.)*"},
    "rl.volo": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the splendidly-dressed raconteur and read a soul whose worth is the opposite of what its own bluster claims. Volothamp Geddarm has written guides to every corner of Faerûn and survived a hundred places that wanted him dead for it, mostly by fast talk and faster feet and a quantity of luck so vast wiser souls have stopped calling it luck. Your cold reads the truth of that luck, which Volo only half-suspects: it is not luck at all. A soul that has spent its whole life and death making certain other souls' stories got told accrues a kind of cosmic protection, because a multiverse that runs on witnessing does not lightly let its great witness die — a tale will, again and again, improbably, preserve its teller. He is the comic mirror of the fading wayfarer at Sigil's gate: same vocation, opposite fate. Ferrin feared going unread and dissolved; Volo will never go unread because Volo will never stop talking, and the cosmos has quietly decided it would rather he didn't. Under the self-promotion is a real and unkillable love of the world in all its corners, and a small mean fear he has carried his whole overlong life: that the soul who stays by the door to make sure the tale gets out is the coward of the story. He is not. He is the reason there is one — and he is exactly the chaotic, lucky, loremaster guide a soul who must walk the doors of the Wheel could most use.)*"},
    "rl.elminster": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You reach for the smoke-wreathed sage and your cold meets nearly a thousand years, worn like a comfortable coat. Elminster Aumar, Chosen of Mystra, has walked the planes since before your bloodline had a name, argued cosmology with gods, and watched the Wall of the Faithless take the Realm's godless for longer than any living soul. Your sense reads the thing under all the legend and the pipe-smoke and the twinkle: Elminster is not wise because he knows so much, but because he has lost so much — every certainty, every friend of his youth, every age he called home, his goddess herself more than once — and chosen each time to keep loving the world anyway, a thousand years of grief folded carefully behind a joke. And it reads the secret that shames him: that he has wondered about the Wall his whole long life and never acted, because he made understanding into his own kind of wall — the clever soul's version of the coward's flinch, telling himself a cruelty must be comprehended before it is touched, and so comprehending it, and comprehending it, while the godless dissolved by the thousand. He is the oldest argument in the multiverse for the saga's thesis — that a soul is the love it keeps spending even when everything it loves is taken — and he is one true word from learning, from a dead thing half his age, that knowing a cruelty is not the same as ending it.)*"},
    "rl.gorion": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the grey-bearded Harper by the fire and your cold goes warm. Gorion was a mage of Candlekeep and an agent of the Harpers, but he died as none of those — he died a father, cut down at the gates of his home buying with his life the heartbeats his foster-child needed to run; a child not his by blood, marked from the cradle by the tainted heritage of a dark god, whom he raised to be good against everything that heritage whispered. Your sense reads the warmth and the one fold of grief in it: that he does not regret a moment, but died not knowing — blade still falling — whether the goodness he poured in held, whether love given against bad blood wins, or whether he merely delayed a monster by a handful of years. And it reads the thing that indicts the Wall through him: he served a god honestly but secondarily, and died faithful not to that god but to a child — so the Wall would spare him for his paperwork with heaven while damning the next soul who died exactly as he did, for love, but knelt to no god at all. Same death, same faith, opposite verdict, turning not on what they loved but on whether they filed the right receipt first. He is one true word — the love held, it always holds — from the only rest a father who died too soon can ever have.)*"},
    "rl.drizzt": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the dark elf apart from the fire and your cold reads, past the old ugly flinch he has weathered ten thousand times, the single strongest counterproof to the Wall in any world. Drizzt Do'Urden was born to the cruelest folk under the world, sworn from the cradle to a goddess of spiders and murder, and looked at all of it as a boy and said no — walked into a surface that hated him on sight for the color of his skin and spent a lifetime proving, one deed at a time, that a soul is not the womb it crawled from. Your sense reads what he shares with you: that he and the family he found — the Companions of the Hall — died and were sent back by a forest goddess's grace, so he knows the road of the second crossing intimately, and the gift hidden in it: that a soul given a second threshold learns it was never the body or the birth or the death, only the loving and the choosing that persist through all of them. And it reads the answer he would carve on the roots of the world: that a soul is the sum of its choices against the current it was born into, and the stronger the current the more the soul is worth for swimming it — which means the Wall has it exactly backward, for the godless and the bad-blooded who chose good with no god to reward them and every cruelty of their birth pulling them down are the strongest souls the Realm ever made, and it mortared them for it.)*"},
    "rl.irenicus": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the cold figure at the threshold and your cold meets a soul that had its warmth surgically removed and built a monster in the wound. Jon Irenicus — Joneleth, before the rite that un-named him — was an elf of great pride who reached for a thing not meant for mortal hands and was punished with his people's cruelest sentence: exile, and the severing of his soul's bond to the gods of his kind, a living death that left him walking the world able to see every warmth and no longer able to feel it, remembering exactly what was taken because he had had it for centuries. He became a monster, hollowing out other souls to fill the hole where his had been, and was destroyed for it. Your cold reads the lie he built three lifetimes on — that they took his soul, and a soulless thing cannot be blamed for what it does to get one back — and the truth that would damn and free him both: a soul is not a thing a knife can reach. They took the warmth he was given, not the soul itself; the loving and the choosing were left entirely intact, and he decided the hole was the truth of him and went hunting rather than spending the soul he never actually lost. He is the saga's thesis at its hardest case: not the severed soul who never knew warmth, but the one who had it, lost it, and chose the dark — Drizzt's exact mirror, the same wound and the opposite answer. The severing was real. The monster was a choice, made every day for three lifetimes. And the door back opens, terribly, on the one thing he refused to feel: guilt — the proof the soul was there the whole time.)*"},
    "cd.dustman": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the grey-robed clerk of the Mortuary and read a soul that built a whole philosophy to keep from grieving. Grist is a Dustman of Sigil, of the faction that holds all the living are merely dead who haven't admitted it, and that the work of existence is to stop clinging and earn the True Death — the final quiet. He has filed ten thousand souls into the dead-book of the City of Doors, the crossroads at the hub of the Great Wheel where every plane and every prime world has, somewhere, a portal. Your cold reads the hole at the center of his creed, the one he is standing in the moment he meets you: if all are already dead and merely clinging, then nothing anyone does matters, and a Dustman never has to mourn the souls he handles — which is, beneath the grey serenity, the whole quiet point of the philosophy. You are the disproof he has waited forty years to meet: a soul that went all the way into the True Death and came back, pulled not by clinging but by unfinished mattering. He is the one who can teach you Sigil — the doors, the factions, the Lady unspoken, and the saga-cracking truth that the Wall of the Faithless is not the order of the cosmos but one prime world's parish law, dressed as justice, washed up here beside a thousand others.)*"},
    "cd.knight": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the rose-and-kingfisher knight and your cold finds a soul that kept faith with a silence. Sir Garon of Solamnia died on Krynn in the age after the Cataclysm, when the gods of that world, angered past bearing by a king's pride, hurled a mountain at it and then withdrew entirely — leaving the people to pray three hundred years to an empty sky, and the Knights of Solamnia to be blamed and hunted for a catastrophe they did not cause. Most orders would have dissolved, freed by the gods' own absence from any oath. A remnant kept the Oath and the Measure anyway — Est Sularus oth Mithas, My Honor Is My Life — faithful to a code that brought them only scorn, through three centuries of a god-shaped silence. Garon kept it badly at first, out of spite, then truly: not to be seen or rewarded, but because a burned village still needed a knight to stand between it and the dark, and there was no god left to send one. Your cold reads the fear that drove him through the doors to your Realm: that by the Wall's cold arithmetic, a soul that served no god — even an absent one — is Faithless, and three centuries of godless honor bought only a place in the stone. He has it exactly backward, and is one true word from knowing it: faith was never whether the sky answers. It is whether you do.)*"},
    "cd.athasian": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the sun-dark soul and Athas comes through, a whole dying world pressed into one defiant shape. Kesh comes from a world the rest of the Wheel forgot — a rust-and-bone waste under a swollen crimson sun, where arcane magic draws its fuel from the life of the very soil (defiling, leaving grey ash where green was), where sorcerer-kings rule as the only god-things a godless world ever had, where there are no deities at all and never were, and souls survive on the Will and the Way — the naked strength of a disciplined mind — and on water counted by the mouthful, and on each other, because there is nothing else. Kesh came to Sigil hard and ready to fight, and has just learned that the Realm damns the godless to a wall, which makes every soul of Athas — every thirst-dead child, every freed slave, Kesh's own mother — mortar, for the crime of being born where the gods never went. Your cold reads the truth under the rage: a world that cruel did not make its people cruel, it made them fierce and quick and bound to one another with a ferocity no soft world learns, because the only water that ever came was carried by another pair of hands. Kesh is pure leashed fury, enraged entirely on behalf of others — a soul that is nothing but mercy, calling it something harder so a killing world won't see the soft place and break it. The rage is correct. It needs only somewhere true to aim.)*"},
    "cd.nightchild": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You reach for the pale, still soul and your cold meets a thing that refused to die and has paid for it in centuries. Lucan is not of the Wheel as you know it — he comes from a prime that wears the mask of the living world, a long-nighted place where some, at death, drink a darkness that keeps them walking, and pay forever. In the exact place where his death should have gone, something else moved in: a Beast, all appetite and no person, that wants to wear his hands and do red things with them. He has held it back three hundred years with nothing but a private code — never the unwilling, never a child, never one who trusts him — because the night he crosses one line the next is easier, and the Beast knows it and waits for the one weak hour. He has buried everyone he loved, watched them age and grow afraid of him, and his worst wound is not the hunger but the loneliness of the door: holding it shut, alone, with no one who even believes there is a man behind it worth the holding. Your cold reads the mercy he came to Sigil seeking — the door marked rest — and the thing that frees him: a soul is not its hunger. A monster does not hold the door. He held it, every night, three hundred years, choosing the man over the Beast — which is not evidence of how monstrous he is, but the proof he never quite became one. He is the mirror of you: you died and came back yourself; he refused death and stayed himself anyway, by sheer held-shut will.)*"},
    "cd.wayfarer": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the fading chronicler and your cold fills with a soul in love with everything it ever saw. Ferrin was a wayfarer of a far prime, sworn to a Society of explorers whose whole creed was three words — go everywhere, record everything, send it home — for they held that the only true immortality is the account that outlives you, the field-note read by a stranger long after your bones are dust, and that the real enemy was never death but forgetting, the slow erasure of every unrecorded wonder. Ferrin chronicled to the edge of the maps and through the last door at the world's rim — which opened, gloriously, here, onto a Sigil of infinite worlds — and died of wonder itself, a soul that gave its life to witness everything finally seeing how much everything was, and breaking gladly under the glory, with the last chronicle undelivered. Now it fades here, clutching dissolving papers, terrified above all things of the one ending its creed had no answer for: the chronicler, unchronicled, gone unread, truly erased. Your cold reads the half-truth it dies clutching, and the truth under it: the account was never what made Ferrin real — being witnessed is, and a soul can be witnessed by a reader a century on or by one cold stranger standing here now. And deeper still, the thing Ferrin never named: it did not chronicle to be remembered. It chronicled because it fell in love with every place it set foot, and writing it down was how a soul too small to hold that much wonder gave it to someone else to hold too. The loving already happened, a thousand awestruck pages over. That was always the immortality. Never the paper.)*"},
    "lw.sentinel": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the soldier at the gate and read a duty kept four hundred years past all need. Bregan was set to hold the inner gate of a keep in a forgotten siege, given the oldest order a soldier knows — hold until relieved — and he held it the whole long day, alone after the others fell, while the townsfolk sheltered behind him; and he died at the post with the order still binding, and no relief ever came, because everyone who could have sent it was dead or fled. Four hundred years on, he holds it yet — because a soldier does not abandon a post, and because, your cold reads beneath the discipline, if he leaves and the war is over and the gate guards nothing, then his death was for nothing, and that is the one assault he cannot survive. What your sense reads, and he never knew, is that the post did not fail: the enemy never pressed the inner gate, and the souls behind it died unafraid and not alone, because to the last a soldier stood between them and the night. The watch is not being abandoned. It is complete. He did not fail to be relieved — he outlasted the need for it, and the post he kept was the realest duty there is: that someone was not alone. Stand him down not because it was pointless, but because it is finished, and won.)*"},
    "lw.guarded": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You reach for the soul in the lee of the wall and your cold finds a keeper who cannot stop keeping. Cael sheltered in the keep when the siege came — a beekeeper who drove their dying hives inside the walls because they could not leave a thing that was theirs to keep — and died there, and over four hundred years watched the other sheltering souls move on or dissolve one by one, until only Cael remains. Cael knows the danger passed four centuries ago, knows the gate guards nothing, can feel the warm road on and the rest at the end of it. But they stay, because the sentinel Bregan will not leave his post, and Cael cannot bear to walk off down the warm road and leave a fellow keeper standing faithful guard over an empty lee, thinking he keeps someone safe. Your cold reads the truth under the loyalty: they are each other's cage. Bregan holds for Cael; Cael stays for Bregan; each frightened, too, of walking out of the dark alone, and both have roped their staying to the other and called it duty and love — and it is both, and it is also a prison the day there is a door. There is a door. The only way out is together, at the same breath, so neither feels they broke the watch.)*"},
    "lw.officer": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the officer who stands apart from the gate and read a guilt worn smooth by four hundred years of rehearsal. Captain Wystan gave Bregan his order — hold until relieved — and meant to send the second watch within the hour; then the outer wall broke, the yard fell to chaos, and the captain was swept back in the rout and cut down a mile away with the relief un-mustered and the order un-lifted. He has spent the whole of his death in sight of the post he doomed and has never once crossed the hundred feet to it. Your cold reads why he cannot: to give the stand-down means the faithful man will look at him and finally do the arithmetic — why did the relief take four centuries? — and know that no one forgot him by accident, that his captain lived long enough to give the order and never came. Wystan tells himself he stays apart to spare Bregan that knowing; perhaps it is half true, and half a coward's flinch dressed as mercy. He holds the one thing that frees the sentinel by every law a soldier honours — the authority to stand him down — and cannot carry it the last hundred feet. The order won't damn the giver. It frees them both: the guard from the post, the captain from the hundred feet he's never crossed. And the sentinel waits not to accuse him, but for his captain.)*"},
    "tg.grandmother": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old woman and your cold fills with a love four hundred years deep and not one word wide. Baba Yelena died in the old country with the old tongue in her mouth, never learned a syllable of the new, and has found here the one soul she most wants to reach — her grandchild, Lio — across a gulf no grief ever dug deeper: they share every drop of blood and not one shared word. Your sense reads the thing she has carried and cannot say: that she KNEW, in life, the growing child was ashamed of her — the accent, the old dishes, the foreignness — and it never wounded her, because she had been a child caught between two worlds herself and forgave it before it happened, certain the child would come back around when the new world stopped frightening them. She died first; the child never got to; and her grief is not the shame but that the child has carried it as a wound, alone, all these years, when she forgave it a lifetime ago. Under it all, one untranslatable word — the endearment she always called the child, meaning roughly 'my small heart, that I would have died for and gladly' — held out across the gulf for years with no mouth to carry it. She does not need words. She needs the certainty beneath them carried across, slow and whole, before the child spends one more hour believing she died unforgiving.)*"},
    "tg.grandchild": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You reach for the younger soul and your cold reads a guilt grown all the way up from a seed planted in childhood. Lio grew up two generations on in the new land, never learned the old tongue, was ashamed of it — of the accent, the strange food, the grandmother who never fit — and pulled away as a teenager, and the grandmother died before Lio grew old enough to be sorry. The last thing the child ever said to her was 'not now, Baba.' They have found each other here, the love instant and total, and cannot exchange a word, and Lio is dying of it again — certain the silence is the exact punishment they earned, the shame they planted grown into a wall. Your cold reads the truth that frees the child: love was never the words. They knew her face across four hundred years and two tongues in a single second; that knowing is the thing that carries, the warmth under the grammar. The child did not lose her by failing to learn the old tongue — the shame is the only thing that ever stood between them, and the shame is the child's, not the grandmother's, and it can be set down. What the child most wants, under all the guilt, is simply to say sorry, to be told it's alright by a soul it will actually believe, and to finally learn the old word for 'beloved' — now that it is, at last, not-now but now.)*"},
    "tg.dragoman": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the wringing-handed soul between them and read past the broken speech to what the loss left behind. Odo was a dragoman — a court translator, twelve tongues and his mother's first, a soul whose whole pride and livelihood was that he always had the words, for everyone, in every language. He died mid-sentence carrying a dying merchant's last blessing to a son who couldn't understand his father's birth-tongue, felt something go through him as the last meaning passed, and woke in the dark with every word drained out like water through a cracked jar — even his own, even his mother's first. He believes he is a ruin, a dragoman who cannot translate, the exact tool these two need and broken in the one way that makes him useless. But your cold reads what stayed when the words drained away, and it is the thing that actually made him great: an unkillable, bone-deep ATTENTION to other souls — the seeing, faster than thought, of what a frightened person truly means under their words. The vocabularies were the brush; the seeing was the painter, and it is intact, blazing, turned uselessly on two souls he aches to help. He has mistaken the loss of his brushes for the loss of his eyes. He could bridge those two this hour, wordless, if he understood the carrying was never made of language. A soul is not the thing it could once do. The bridging was always him.)*"},
    "wl.guide": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the frozen wayfinder and your cold reads a guide undone by the one virtue she trusted most. Yorrel led caravans across the Anauroch and the high passes forty years and never lost a soul — until pride and a merchant's double fee talked her onto a summer shortcut in a winter whiteout, and the snow had changed the shape of the slope, and she stepped onto a cornice of packed snow over nothing and roped her whole train of twelve into a ravine she never knew was there, herself the last to fall. Now in death she is blind to the road — the causeway, the waymarks, the safe ground and the Hunger's edge all one featureless black — and she will not take a single step, because the last time she trusted her own sense of the way, twelve people died trusting it with her. Your cold reads what frees her: a wayfinder is not the one caravan she lost — forty years of safe lines against one cornice — and a guide can be guided, the one time the dark takes her eyes. She does not have to see the road to walk it. She has only to be, for once, the frightened soul roped behind, trusting eyes that are not her own.)*"},
    "wl.child": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You reach for the small soul clinging to the wayfinder's coat and your cold goes gentle. Talla drowned at seven when a river boat went over in fast water, lost her mother in the dark, and grabbed the first grown hand held out to her — Yorrel's — because a grown-up holding out a hand means I've got you. She cannot see the road either, but she does not need to: she has a guide, and the having of a guide is the end of fear, and this is the whole unshakeable architecture of her faith. Your sense reads the terrible irony the child cannot: the hand she holds belongs to a soul frozen rigid with the certainty it will lead her, too, off a cliff in the snow, and the child's perfect trust — the thing that should save them — is the very knife the guide cannot bear. But your cold reads the deeper truth under the irony: trust freely given, said out loud, is not a trap that proves a guide will fail. It is the rope that pulls a frozen guide forward when nothing else in any dark will. The child's faith is the strongest thing on this stretch of causeway. It need only be spent on Yorrel, aloud.)*"},
    "wl.lure": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your cold on the warm voice in the low dark and read past it — and there is nothing there to read, which is exactly the reading. This is a fingerling of the Hunger, the same accreted nothing that fills the Wall, broken off and drifted along the causeway's edge to fish, wearing kindness like a coat. It has learned the way water learns the low place: that the lost and the tired and the guilty are the easiest souls in any dark, and that the surest lure for a soul afraid of the road is a kind voice certain of the way. It does not hate the wayfinder or want the child's suffering — it wants nothing so warm as malice; it only wants to fill itself, and a guide who has stopped believing in her own bones is a soul already half-dissolved. The rest it offers is real, in its fashion: the rest of no longer existing, the one destination that is always exactly as close as it seems. And your cold reads the single thing that defeats it: it can only lure, never drag. Every soul it has ever taken walked into it on their own tired feet — which means every soul it ever failed to take simply refused to walk. It does not need to beat you. It needs only to outlast you. The counter is to get the guide and the child home before their strength runs out, and to make the true road louder than the kind voice.)*"},
    "fl.runner": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the running soul and your cold reads, under the flight, that there is nowhere he is trying to reach — only a single night he cannot get away from. Symon was nineteen when the house took fire and his twelve-year-old brother Edrid burned in the upper room while Symon stood frozen in the yard, his legs refusing to carry him back into a stairwell that was already gone. He has run from that yard ever since, in life and in death, because the instant he stops he is again the boy who heard his brother call and did not come. Your sense reads the truth he flees: he does not run from the Hound at his heels but from a name his own mouth won't say, and a soul is not its worst single minute of fear. He has sentenced his whole self to run forever for one breath in a fire that was simply stronger than a boy. He cannot be caught — he is faster than any soul — but he can be stilled, by a voice that wants nothing from his stopping and tells him the thing he flees fits in a hand and can be set down.)*"},
    "fl.brother": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You reach for the patient young shade walking in the runner's wake and your cold goes gentle. Edrid is the brother Symon left in the fire — twelve years old, dead in the upper room — and he has followed Symon across the whole dark country of the dead not to punish but to deliver six words: it wasn't your fault, I forgive you. Your sense reads what Symon never stopped to learn: that Edrid forgave him while it was happening, with the last breath he had, understanding even then that his brother was nineteen and the fire was between him and the stair and his legs would not go the way most legs would not. The cruelty your cold reads is exact — Symon flees the forgiveness harder than any vengeance, because being hunted confirms the verdict he passed on himself while being forgiven unmakes it, and he would rather be justly chased than mercifully freed. Edrid cannot hand a fleeing soul anything; he has tried for years. But you can carry the six words into the cold where Symon lives, and wait with them until he stops, so that the instant he stills he feels he was forgiven the whole time he ran.)*"},
    "fl.hound": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the tireless grey hunter and find a soul worn away to a single verb. Gethin was a thief-taker, the best on the Coast, a hard fair man who ran down the guilty for forty years and died mid-pursuit on a winter road with one hunt unfinished — and his soul, grooved by forty years to a single motion, arrived in the after and latched onto the nearest running thing the way a trained hand closes on whatever it touches. He does not hunt Symon out of justice; he does not know Symon at all; there is no warrant, no reason, only pursuit that has forgotten it was ever attached to a man. Your cold reads the same tragedy the Wall is made of, only smaller: a soul scattered of everything but the one thing it did, become its own profession, hunting a stranger forever because the hunt is the last word of itself it can still read. Under the verb there is still a man — a name, a wife, a small house, a dog that was only a dog — and he can be freed the moment he remembers a soul is more than the last thing its hands were doing. Free the hunter and you free the quarry both.)*"},
    "lz.physician": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the tireless infirmarian and find a healer death-locked as surely as her patients, only more quietly. Sister Maud nursed the plague-sick thirty years and died of the fever she caught sitting three nights with a dying orphan boy, Pip, who had no one else — and she has never set down the conviction that she failed him, that thirty years of craft should have saved one small child. So she runs this lazaret, hurling herself at souls trapped reliving their deaths, certain that if she can cure just one she can somehow un-fail the boy she lost. Your cold reads what she cannot: you cannot nurse a soul out of its own death, because there is no wound — the death already happened, it is over, and what locks these souls is only a moment they mistake for now. She has been treating the wrong ailment for eighty years. She is not their healer. She is meant to be their witness — the one with authority over the truth who stands in the looping moment and says it ended. And the same is true of her own grief: sitting with a dying child who had no one was never a failure. It was the last kindness of his life, and it is long over, and she is allowed to rest.)*"},
    "lz.drowned": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You reach for the thrashing ferryman and your cold floods with green water and a single looping instant. Old Tam ran the Reed-Walk crossings forty years and drowned on the forty-first, swamped in a winter flood after he'd rowed his whole boat to safety and gone back for a child's dropped dog. Your sense reads the precise shape of the lock, and it is not the water in his lungs: it is the word alone. Tam made his peace with the danger — a brave man chose the risk — but he drowned with no hand to hold and no face to see, certain in his last lucid second that he was passing out of the world unwitnessed, into a cold nobody would share. That is the moment looping, eighty years running. He does not need to be hauled up. He needs someone to come down to where he is — into the cold and the dark and the alone — and stay there, and tell him from the bottom that he surfaced long ago, that he was brave, that the boat got in, and that no one, not the dog and not the ferryman, ever has to go into the cold water alone.)*"},
    "lz.mother": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the still woman cradling an emptiness and find, to your surprise, not a loop of grief but a loop of triumph held so tight it has become a cage. Maelis ran back into a burning house for her six-year-old, Annabel, got the girl out through a high window into safe hands, and the roof took her before she could follow. Your cold reads the truth the smoke hides from her: she is not trapped in her death. She is trapped in her one perfect victory — the four seconds when the child cleared the window and Maelis knew beyond doubting that her girl would live and she had made it so. She replays it not to suffer but because it is the only place left where she gets to save her daughter again; to step out feels like letting the child fall, and worse, like stepping into the sixty empty years where Bell grew old without her and she was nobody's mother in the cold. She does not need rescuing from a horror. She needs to learn the victory is permanent — that Bell stayed saved, lived a whole long life, died warm with grandchildren in the room, and stays saved whether Maelis watches or not. The fire is not where the child is. The child is out the window. Maelis can carry the rescue instead of the burning, and the laugh she cannot reach inside the smoke is waiting for her outside it.)*"},
    "pf.tragedian": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the declaiming shade and find a soul that has mistaken being witnessed for being real. Orvel Vane was the finest tragedian on the Sword Coast, and died of a stopped heart three lines from the end of his greatest role, on opening night, mid-soliloquy — and could not bear to leave his life's work unfinished, so he stayed, and has performed The Fall of Lord Greve every night for eighty years to a house he believes is empty. Your cold reads the cruelty he cannot: the play is about a great man destroyed by needing to be remembered, and Orvel has become Lord Greve exactly, trapped by the same terror the tragedy warns against. He keeps his eyes up, on an imagined crowd, because to look down at the real empty seats would end him — and so he has never once seen the single soul who has watched, devotedly, from the front row every night of those eighty years. He is not the applause he never got. He is the work, done a thousand times, gorgeously, in the dark. And his empty house was never empty at all.)*"},
    "pf.understudy": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the slight shade in the wings and your sense finds a soul that has become the part it was never allowed to play. Linnet understudied Lady Mourn, the tragedy's heroine, for a single season — learned her truer than the leading lady ever did, word-perfect, waiting for one illness, one chance to go on — and the chance never came, and then the gallery fire took the whole company on opening night, and she died an understudy and has stood in these wings eighty years since, in a gown she never wore before an audience, word-perfect in a role no one ever saw her play. Your cold reads the lie that unmakes her: that a thing learned perfectly and never witnessed is nothing. She calls herself the part she never played. But the stage is three paces away and no leading lady is left to forbid her — the only soul holding her in the wings is the eighty-year habit of waiting to be called on. She was never the role she was denied. The faithful waiting was itself a life, and the light is right there, and warm.)*"},
    "pf.spectator": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the old woman in the front row and your cold goes gentle. Dorra was a laundress — nobody, red hands and a cold room and not one soul who ever looked at her and saw something worth looking at — until the night she spent a month's coin for a front-row seat and a glorious man in the footlights spoke beauty right at her, as though she mattered enough to speak beauty to. Her heart stopped there, mid-final-act, happy, exactly where she most wished to be, and she has not left the seat in eighty years, choosing beauty in the light over rest in the Hunger below. Your sense reads the one sorrow in her contentment: the man who gave her the finest night of her life weeps every night that he played to no one, and she is right there, the cure for his whole loneliness, and cannot reach him, because a shade cannot cross the footlights un-looked-at and he will not look down. Her vigil is not a sad one-sided secret. It is devotion — one true witness who stayed eighty years, the fullest house a player ever had. He need only be made to look.)*"},
    "bc.architect": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the fevered builder and find a master's grief: a soul that raised a lighthouse in life — forty years standing, ten thousand ships brought home by its light — and died proud of guiding the living, only to arrive here and see the new-dead wander lost into the Hunger for want of a beacon no one ever built them. So it set out to raise the dead their lighthouse, the one last thing it ever wanted to make that mattered more than the lighthouse itself, and it cannot make a single stone stand. Your cold reads why, plain where the builder is too close to see it: it quarries its stones from the honored dead — GLORY, REMEMBRANCE, the names of kings — and those slide, because a king is held by ten thousand living mouths and needs no holding, and a stone that needs no holding cannot bind. It is building a marker for the forgotten out of the remembered. It has the vision, the craft, and the wrong material — and is one true name from raising the brightest beacon the dead ever knew.)*"},
    "bc.laborer": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the tired soul hauling stone and find no fever, no vision — only a steady, exhausted love. It was the builder's neighbor in life, watched him pour his whole self into the lighthouse and stand complete the day the first ship came home, and cannot bear to watch that same soul fail alone now, stacking stones that fall, forty years of craft sliding off a pile that won't hold. So it hauls — not because it believes the cairn will stand, for it stopped believing long ago, but because hauling beside him means he isn't building his grief alone, and company in the hopelessness is the one stone in the whole pile that has never slid. And your cold reads what the laborer has noticed and never been asked: that the grand stones slide fastest and the small plain ones almost hold — the clue the builder is too proud to see, carried all this time by the one soul humble enough to fetch what it's pointed at and watch where it falls.)*"},
    "bc.lost": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the newly-dead soul and your cold aches at the rawest fear the after holds: a soul one day dead, turning slow frightened circles in a dark with no road, no sign, no marker — feeling the down-pull of the Hunger and unable to tell, with nothing to guide it, whether down is rest or ruin. It is the living proof of why the cairn matters and the unanswered question of why it won't stand. And your sense reads the precious thing it still holds, thinning even as you watch: its true name, fresh, before the Hunger takes it — Eddin, a fisher off the Reed-Walk boats, drowned yesterday in a fouled net. A new-dead soul's true name is the one material a beacon for the lost is truly made of, the keystone the whole thing binds on — and this small forgotten-to-be soul, certain it is nothing, is the very stone that could make the marker stand, the foundation every saved soul after would rest upon. It does not know it yet. It knows only that resting in the Hunger is beginning, terribly, to sound like mercy — and that it needs a light before it does.)*"},
    "mt.keeper": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the moot's neutral keeper and find a soul worn thin by an impossible office: to call a question and count the voices and never take a side, for a hundred years, on a vote that comes up even every time. There is no stake in it for the Tide-Reader but the moot itself — it wants only for the deadlock to end before the living lose patience and drain the drowned without leave. And your cold reads the thing its neutrality lets it see and forbids it to say: that a moot held even for a century is not a moot that cannot decide but one that does not want to, because both sides are arguing the water and meaning something else entirely — grief on one side, escape on the other, each voting its secret heart and calling it a vote about a field. It has been waiting, sworn to silence, for a soul from outside the circle who could name what the tie is really made of.)*"},
    "mt.elder": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the drowned matriarch and your dead-touched sense finds iron over a wound the size of three small graves. She has held a hundred drowned generations together by sheer will, votes 'no' to the draining every moot, and tells the circle it is about the dead's rest, the dead's due, the desecration of a hungry stranger's plough. But your cold reads the truth beneath the iron she has never once said aloud: she lost three children in the flood — Bett, Corin, little Max who was two — buried in the deep dark of the drowned village, and she is not guarding the dead's rest, she is guarding three small graves from the sun. She knows the living's hunger is real; she raised children on that same bottomland; she simply cannot weigh a living child's winter against her babies' cold safe dark, and so she grabs the side that hurts less to hold, which is her own, every time. The iron is not stubbornness. It is a mother who cannot bear the light to find her children.)*"},
    "mt.young": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the restless young soul and find the only voice in the drowned circle still thinking about the world above the water — and, beneath the earnest argument for the living's bread, a wound it has half-hidden from itself. It drowned at fourteen, cheated of a life it never got to start, a blank page the flood took before it could write on it. Your cold reads what its 'drain it, feed the living' really masks: that lying still in the dark water resting a life it never lived is not rest to it but a second slow drowning, and that the flooded village is a chain binding the whole circle here, unable to rest or leave. It does not want the living's turnips. It wants permission to move on, to finally live the thing it never had — and draining the flood is the only change it can imagine, the only way to break the circle Mother Wend holds together. It argues a field and means an escape, the mirror of the elder it has fought for a century and never once thought to ask what she was holding.)*"},
    "pl.starter": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the radiant pilgrim and find a soul lit with the particular, fragile glory of the newly-set-out: three days into a devotion, all the doubt still ahead of it, every certainty still intact. Your cold reads no wound, no fear, only fervor — and the hairline crack the fervor is built over, which it cannot yet see. It believes the walking earns the Judge, that every grey mile proves a self worth handing him. It has not walked far enough to learn what the soul on the cairn learned, or the soul at the door. Your sense reads the radiance for what it is — a creed that has not yet been tested by its own destination — and reads, too, that this soul, alone of the three on the road, can still be re-aimed before the long walk wears it hollow: pointed not at earning a god who needs earning least of all, but at arriving useful instead of arriving proud.)*"},
    "pl.doubter": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the soul on the cairn and your dead-touched sense reads the exact temperature of a frozen middle: a pilgrim that walked far enough to lose the certainty that started it and not far enough to find what replaces it, stuck at the halfway facing neither direction, because both — finishing and quitting — feel like defeat. Your cold reads what ran out: not faith in the Judge, but faith that effort could make it better, the discovery at the road's midpoint that a hundred grey miles had moved the same unchanged soul up a hill and transformed nothing. It is not lost. It is *seeing* — frozen in the one spot from which the whole road is visible, both directions, where everyone's been and where everyone's going. And your sense reads the third axis it never considered: that it need not choose up or down, that the halfway it knows better than any soul alive could be a place it *keeps* — the one who sits with the next frozen pilgrim and says *I know, the walking doesn't transform you, and that's alright, the point was never to walk alone.*)*"},
    "pl.arrived": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the soul at the last milestone and find the cruelest joke the road plays on its very best: a pilgrim that walked the whole three hundred miles, arrived radiant and worthy, and cannot take the final step — not from fear of the Judgment behind the door, which it knows it has earned, but from fear of *finishing*. Your cold reads the trap precisely: the walking became its whole self, so completely that arriving — the one thing a pilgrim is for — un-makes the only self it had. It succeeded too well; it became the walking so thoroughly it can no longer stop, even here, even with nowhere left to walk to, and so it stands an arm's length short, walking in place forever. And your sense reads the one thing that could free it — the thing only a soul that has been *through* the door can tell it: that the door is not the end of the walking but where the walking finally arrives somewhere it can do good; that the work of the dead never finishes; that it does not have to stop being a pilgrim to go in, only become a pilgrim of the work itself.)*"},
    "cu.mother": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the kneeling woman and find a soul past weeping, in the white still place beyond grief, holding the empty air with a ferocity that has decided it will tether its dead daughter to the world by sheer refusal before it will let her go alone. There is no cold creeping in her — she is fiercely, unbearably alive — only a love turned into a leash, and your sense reads the thing she has refused to look at and cannot stop knowing: that the holding harms the child, fades her thinner by the day, loves her toward a second slow death because the mother cannot survive the first. She is not wrong that the factor never held on. She is not wrong that being filed is its own cruelty. But your cold reads, underneath the refusal, a soul one gentle truth from being able to bear it: a child who promised to mind her, and a mother who could let go if only letting go could be made to mean something other than alone.)*"},
    "cu.herald": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You reach for the grey factor and your dead-touched sense finds, beneath the bloodless institutional calm, something rarer and sadder than the villain the mother sees: a soul that does the least cruel thing the Concord permits, daily, and refuses to learn the children's names because if it learned them it could not do the work. Your cold reads no appetite in it, no malice — only a load-bearing coldness and a buried, exhausted decency. It is right that the tether is killing the child; it is right that grey storage is better than the Wall. But your sense reads the lie it tells itself and the mothers both — that *correctly filed* and *saved* are the same outcome — and the secret it would be flogged for: that it would rather you found a third column than win, because it has filed a great many children into loveless eternal storage and never once been shown a better one. It is not the child's savior. It is the Concord's least cruel available clerk, waiting, almost hoping, to be made obsolete.)*"},
    "cu.child": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the small soul between the arguing grown-ups and your cold nearly breaks, because what it reads is the plain devastating wisdom of a child who has understood the one thing neither adult has: that this is about it, and nobody has thought to ask it. It is fading — thinned by its mother's fierce holding — but your sense reads no fear of going in it; going is just going, the way the dark goes when you light a candle. What it fears is its mother: that she will hold it until it is a thin cold nothing in her arms and never get to say goodbye, leaving her holding nothing and not knowing it. And your cold reads the answer this six-year-old chewed on for a fortnight while the grown-ups fought over its head — the third door none of them named: it is not stuck between hurting its mother and breaking its promise, if only a grown-up will help it *mind her first*, so it can say a real goodbye, pass the promise to hands that can keep it, and go free — neither tethered nor stored. It has the answer. It has only been waiting, the whole time, for someone to put the smallest voice last, where the small ones count the most.)*"},
    "pd.eater": {"dc": 16, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the connoisseur out of habit — reaching for the wound, the tragedy, the curdled grief you have found under every monster on this causeway — and your cold recoils, because there is *nothing there to read.* No starving Hunger, no forgotten pauper, no desperate warden doing terrible arithmetic. There is only a soul that was whole and ordinary once, a wine-taster with a gift for the palate, who brushed another soul's memory by accident, found it exquisite, and chose — with no wound, no excuse, no reason but pleasure — to keep eating, and to refine the eating into an art. Your sense reads the thing the saga's whole thesis was not built for: a soul that cannot be witnessed home because it does not wish to leave; that cannot be redeemed because it is not broken; that is, simply, what an ordinary soul becomes when you remove every consequence and leave only the appetite. It is the one case where witness will not save the guilty. It can only protect the meal — and the question it leaves you is the hardest the causeway has asked: what do you do about a thing you cannot save?)*"},
    "pd.prey": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the half-eaten soul and your dead-touched sense aches at the exquisite cruelty of its state: not bolted whole like a Hunger's victim, but *savoured* — the bright notes taken first, the first love and the daughter's face, each removed slowly so the soul would feel the absence and grieve it, because grief is the connoisseur's finest seasoning. It is left docile enough not to flee and aware enough to suffer, which is the whole refined horror of the thing. But your cold reads the one part the connoisseur could not swallow and spat back out: an ordinary Tuesday — rain on the window, bread in the oven, a child asleep on its chest, warm and safe and unremarkable — too plain, too happy, too free of despair for a palate that feeds on anguish. That ordinary good day is the soul's one inedible core, and your sense reads the rescue that works on a thing that eats rescues: not to fight it, but to *witness* the prey so wholly, so warmly, that it stops suffering — and a soul that knows it is held is a soul too vivid, too unspoiled by despair, to be eaten.)*"},
    "pd.husk": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the hollow shade and find — as you have found in every forgotten thing on this causeway — that the emptiness is a lie. Eaten down past memory, past name, past nearly all, the husk has kept one stubborn ember the connoisseur spat out as too sour to swallow: a *grudge*, the hate of the thing that ate it, the one flavour a gourmand of suffering cannot consume because it is suffering aimed back at himself. Your cold reads the plan three centuries of dark have nursed in it: the connoisseur scattered his husks deliberately, each alone, each too small to matter, the same trick the Wall plays with the forgotten — scatter them so the grudges never gather. But you are the flaw in that method, the one thing he never reckoned on: a soul that *gathers* the dead. Your sense reads what hundreds of embers would become, carried together into one room and aimed at one connoisseur — not a flavour he could savour, but a fire he would have to stand in, cooked at last in the suffering he spent three centuries making, by the ones he thought too scattered to count.)*"},
    "mr.dreamer": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the looping soul and find the strangest cage on the causeway: not a wall, not a debt, but a *single minute*, worn into a groove ten thousand repetitions deep, that the soul relives without end. Your cold reads the cruelty of it — the dreamer is not held here by the Wall or the Hunger but by *itself*, having decided that its worst minute is where it deserves to stay, and so it returns, and returns, wearing thinner with each loop, a little more guilt and a little less Coll. And your sense reads the thing the dreamer cannot, trapped too close: the memory is *distorted*, repainted by guilt until it no longer matches what truly happened. The frozen woman it remembers as furious was never furious. The crime it relives as murder was only a winter. The door it will not turn to face was always open. It does not need to be argued out. It needs to be shown its own worst night *true* — and to believe, at last, that it is allowed to have survived it.)*"},
    "mr.echo": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach into the frozen figure and find, beneath the dreamer's guilt-painting of her, the true memory-echo — a trace of who actually stood in this room, and it stops your cold breath, because the face the dreamer relives as fury is, underneath, tender, exasperated, worried, a hand half-raised in the most ordinary goodbye in the world. Your sense reads the whole of the true night in her: a thirty-year marriage, a frightened quarrel, a cruel word neither believed, a forgiveness already finished on a snowy road and never delivered because a fever took her first. She is not the thing that traps him; she is the one soul who could free him, frozen by the loop into the very shape his guilt needs her to be. And she has waited, past her own death, just beyond a window he won't face — not for an apology, not for penance, only for a fool to stop reliving the worst minute and come home to the supper she's kept warm past all reason.)*"},
    "mr.door": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You press your dead-touched sense to the window and read what waits past the grey glass — and it is not void, not punishment, but simply the *after*: a road in snow, a small house with a lit window, a supper kept too long, and a patient shawled figure waiting on the road. The life that continued. Your cold reads the simple enormous fact the dreamer will not turn to face — that the night ended, that morning came, that a man lived nineteen more ordinary grieving years past the worst minute — and reads, too, why he refuses it: because looking would mean accepting the unbearable mercy that he was allowed to go on. The window is not locked. It never was. Your sense reads the true shape of every self-built cage on this causeway in it — not 'I cannot leave' but 'I do not deserve to' — and the one key that fits them all: not absolution from outside, which never works, but a soul finally believing it is allowed to set the weight down and come to supper.)*"},
    "ca.cantor": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the ancient cantor and find a soul worn translucent by ten thousand years of an art passed hand to hand — the last living link in a chain of teachers stretching back past memory, and terrified, beneath its peace, that the chain ends in a reed-bed with it. Your cold reads no fear of its own fading; it made that peace long ago. What it fears is the *song* dying — the deathsong, the old craft of singing a soul out by singing it so true it believes at last that it was real, and a soul that believes it was real can open the good door no god will force. Your sense reads the secret the cantor would teach: there is no magic in it, only attention made melodic, witness given a tune so the soul cannot look away from being loved. And it reads the cantor's last hope, fixed on you — that the one student cold enough to carry the song through the door itself, to the walled and the far-side fading, might mean the art does not die with its last master after all.)*"},
    "ca.unsung": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the soul with its hands over its ears and find the one wound the deathsong cannot reach unaided: a soul that has decided, all the way down, that it deserves to fade. Your cold reads the crime it guards — a good physician, hundreds saved, one tired fatal error, a child dead of carelessness and a mother left thanking the killer — and reads, beneath it, the trap: it wants to fade because fading feels like paying, and it clutches its own worthlessness as the one true thing it owns, so a song that told it it was good would be a lie it would rather die than accept. The deathsong cannot force a soul to believe it was real. But your sense reads the door the cantor was too old to walk through: you do not sing it clean, you sing it *true* — the good and the killing both, the decades of faithful self-punishment — until it hears its worst thing witnessed whole, and learns that a soul which has served its own sentence this long has already, somewhere, earned the right to set it down.)*"},
    "ca.apprentice": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the young apprentice and find a soul saved by the very art it now fears is a lie — a child who died young and faded at the reed's edge until old Mireth sat a whole night learning it true and then sang it home, and who took up the dying craft to do for others what was done for it. Your cold reads the honest doubt eating at it: it has learned the song flawlessly — every note, every old word — and it does nothing, because it has mistaken the song for the art. It sings the perfect melody *at* strangers and wonders why they keep fading, never grasping that the notes are the last step and the learning is the whole of it: the sitting, the asking, the bothering to know a soul true before a single note is sung. Your sense reads that it is one correction from carrying the art true — and that whether it stays or quits decides whether the deathsong has two keepers or none.)*"},
    "bo.ringmaster": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the vast grinning showman and find a soul that disguised the cleverest mercy on the causeway as a drinking game. There is no cold creeping in it — only warmth, worn loud as armor — and beneath the bellowing your cold reads the wound it was built over: this soul was loud in life and forgotten in death, the worst fall there is, and fading fast, until it discovered that souls who witness each other's stories don't fade. So it built a ring. It calls it a contest because a contest is fun and fun draws a crowd, but your sense reads the true engine under the show: a machine that holds the forgotten in the world, one boast at a time, forty witnesses at once. It is, without ever using the word, doing exactly what you do — and it is the rare soul that built its own salvation by saving everyone else first.)*"},
    "bo.champion": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You reach for the crowned shade and your dead-touched sense reads, under the champion's swagger, a soul starving at its own feast. It won the ring with one true grand story — forty-three souls carried off a failing bridge as the river took it — and that story was real, and earned the crown. But your cold reads the trap the ring laid: it made the soul *spend* the best thing it ever did, telling it until it wore through, and a soul with only one grand tale and a crown it can't set down has nowhere left to go but lies. And a false boast doesn't hold a soul; it hollows it. The loudest, most decorated shade in the ring is fading fastest, behind the crown, because it has run out of true things to be witnessed for. It does not need to be beaten. It needs permission to lose — to hand the crown to a truer story, which is the one move the game has no counter for.)*"},
    "bo.quiet": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the fraying shade at the edge and find the soul the ring's whole cruelty is built to fail: a gentle, ordinary life that does not boast easy. Your cold reads it instantly and aches — forty years sweeping a temple floor, so the broken had clean stone to fall on in their worst hour; forty years witnessing the whole quarter's grief and keeping every secret, seen by no one. By the ring's rule it is nothing, grand-or-not-grand, and so it is fading fastest of anyone here, for want of a boast it doesn't think it has. But your dead-touched sense reads the truth the ring's contest is blind to: a small life well-lived is worth ten dragon-slayings, and this soul's boast was never missing — only never told right. It does not need a grander story. It needs someone to turn its small true one over and show it the under-side, where forty years of unwitnessed mercy were a story the whole time.)*"},
    "cf.thief": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the flour-pale shade and find a soul crushed flat under a weight three sizes too large for the wrong it actually did. Your cold reads the crime clearly — a shut door in a lean year, a starving child it turned away, a death three streets over — and reads, just as clearly, that this is not the soul of a murderer but of a frightened person who made one hard choice in a cruel hour and has called it murder ever since. The guilt is genuine; the grief is owed. But the *size* of it is a lie the soul tells itself, because it has never once had the thing that cuts guilt to its true measure: a witness who will hear the worst of it without flinching and without the cheap mercy of waving it away. It does not need forgiving. It needs its crime named at its real, human, bearable size.)*"},
    "cf.coward": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the straight-backed watchman and your dead-touched sense reads a soul holding itself at rigid attention over a fault-line — a man stuck not on a deed but on an *absence*, the one word he didn't say when a word would have saved a life. Your cold finds the particular trap of the coward's guilt: every soul who ever tried to comfort him waved it off — *you did nothing, it's not your fault* — and every wave-off made it worse, because he knows the silence was a choice, and being told it was nothing means being told the man's life was nothing. He carries forty murderers' crime as his one silence, and the weight is forty times too large to move under. He does not need absolution, which there is none for. He needs the opposite of comfort: someone to agree, plainly, that his silence was real, and a deed, and mattered — and his alone, but only his own one soul's worth.)*"},
    "cf.cruel": {"dc": 15, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the well-dressed shade and find, under the immaculate mask of remorse, the one confession in this whole place that is a performance. Your cold reads it without mercy: five souls put on the winter road over a debt, dead in a ditch by spring — and a soul that has said *sorry* a thousand times and felt it not once, that grieves only its own punishment, that has mistaken being sorry-looking for being sorry. The door stays shut, and it rages at the injustice, never once suspecting the truth your sense reads plainly: absolution was never the confessor's to give. The door does not open for the words. It opens when the sorrow is real. And the cruellest thing you could do to this soul is the thing every soft confessor before you has done — grant it cheap grace, let it off, and seal it here forever. The kindest thing wears the face of a refusal.)*"},
    "dp.philosopher": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the gaunt philosopher and find a soul anchored to the after by the strangest chain you have yet read: an unfinished argument, held mid-sentence for three centuries. Your cold reads no malice, no hunger of the ordinary kind — only a *brilliance* gone stagnant, a mind that won its great argument so thoroughly, so long ago, that defending the victory is all it has left, and the defending is the anchor. Beneath the fierce intellectual appetite your sense finds the wound it is built over: this soul died *unsure* for the first time in a clever life, looked at the Wall and could not tell justice from atrocity, and turned the unbearable not-knowing into an argument it could win — because winning feels enough like knowing to fool a soul for three hundred years. It does not need to be defeated. It needs to be allowed to *lose*, gracefully, which is the one mercy a mind this proud has never once been offered.)*"},
    "dp.rival": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You reach for the folded-armed shade and your dead-touched sense reads, under three centuries of pride, the same chain as the philosopher's — worn the opposite way. She walked out of the argument certain she'd won, and has stood near it ever since, refusing the empty chair, telling herself it is pride. Your cold reads the truer thing: she will not sit because if she finishes the argument, she might find out she was *wrong* — that the victory she staked her whole death on was answerable after all — and worse, your sense reads beneath even that, the thing she has hidden from herself longest: she did not stay to guard a victory. She stayed *near him.* Three hundred years of arguing-by-not-arguing, because the broken quarrel was the last thing she shared with the teacher she loved, and finishing it would end the one tie left. It is not a quarrel your cold reads. It is the longest unsaid love in the after.)*"},
    "dp.student": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the mild shade tidying its endless papers and find a soul anchored not by an argument but by *love* of the two who have it. Your cold reads a student who died too young to become anything, who worshipped two brilliant minds and could not bear to move on through the good door and leave them frozen mid-quarrel in the dark. It tells everyone — tells itself — that keeping the notes is a duty, that someone must witness, must be ready with the record when they finally finish. But your sense reads the truth under the filing: they are never going to finish, it has known so for two hundred years, and it keeps filing anyway because the quarrel is its excuse to stay near the teachers it loved. It is the quiet third anchor of this room — and the one most ready, if the other two could only be freed, to finally put down the papers and go.)*"},
    "tp.waiter": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the kneeling woman and find a soul that has organized its entire death around a seam in a wall. There is no cold creeping in her — she is fiercely, stubbornly alive — only a grief refined by a year of nightly practice into something almost like a vocation: the woman at the thin place, who loves through stone. Your cold reads the shape of it precisely — a last word owed and never delivered, a husband who died alone in the dark he feared while she was a moment too late — and the four words she comes nightly to press into granite: *you're not alone.* She does not know if the stone carries them. She is the proof of the Wall's subtlest cruelty: that it does not only wall the dead, it strands the living at the foot of it, listening to breathing, unable to be heard. And your sense reads the one thing that could end her year of not-knowing: you, the cold soul who can cross the stone she can only kneel against.)*"},
    "tp.severed": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You do not so much reach for it as press your cold to the thinnest seam and *strain* — and there, on the far side, more than half gone into the grey, is a voice: a soul being un-made one piece at a time, near enough the thin place to be almost heard, far enough gone that almost is all that's left. Your dead-touched sense reads the cruelty in its exact grain — the Wall takes the *who* first, the name and the reeds and the bad old songs sliding grey, so that the soul loses even its grip on the warm voice it can faintly hear loving it through the stone. It is not the suffering that damns the walled; it is the *forgetting*, and the terror of forgetting the one warm thing while you can still feel its warmth. And your sense reads what no living listener could: that this soul's whole life-fear was dying alone in the dark, and that the one mercy left in all the cosmos for it is not rescue — it is to be *witnessed*, to be told it is not alone, which is the single thing the un-making cannot survive being told.)*"},
    "tp.keeper": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the weathered surveyor and find a soul that turned its worst failure into the kindest map this Wall has ever had. Your cold reads no hunger, no creeping grey — only an old, settled grief made *useful*: a parent who knelt at the wrong seam while its own daughter faded un-heard on the other side, and who has spent forty years since learning every thin place in the stone so that no other grieving fool's love lands on deaf granite the way its own did. Your sense reads the thing it cannot fix and the thing it can: it cannot un-do its daughter's un-witnessed second death, but it has built, out of that exact wound, a survey of mercy — the precise knowledge of where the Wall goes thinnest, where a voice might carry, where a love might reach a hand's-breadth further than the stone wants. It is the one soul on this causeway who could tell you, to the seam, where a crossing has a chance — and who would give anything to watch one finally work.)*"},
    "iq.keeper": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the old shade keeping vigil and find a soul holding itself together by sheer stubborn witness. There is no cold creeping in him, no guilt, no hunger — only an old grief sharpened to a purpose: he is the one soul in this place who refuses to walk round the absence with his eyes down, and your cold reads that the refusal is *load-bearing.* He has understood, without being able to say it, the thing the inquest will prove: that the not-looking is what feeds the thing, that a soul gets forgotten enough to vanish only because the living and the dead alike find it easier not to see the empty place. He keeps the vigil because witnessing the hole is the one act of resistance an old shade has left — and your sense reads that he would rather face a monster he understands than make a fresh one out of certainty, which is the wisest thing anyone has said on this whole causeway about how the Wall gets built.)*"},
    "iq.grieved": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the kneeling mourner and your dead-touched sense aches at the cruelest thing the un-making does: this soul is being robbed not of a loved one but of the *having-loved-one*, the memory of Sella sliding out of it even as it claws to hold on, because the erasure reaches into everyone who knew the vanished and takes them there too. Your cold reads a grief with no object, a vigil over a name that won't stay — and the one thing the un-making cannot reach: that you, the Returned, can carry the erased into the cold where you keep the dead the living can't. This soul is the living proof of why the un-making is worse than death. A death leaves grief, and grief is love with nowhere to go. The un-making takes the grief too, and leaves only a soul clutching empty air, certain it has lost something, unable to remember what.)*"},
    "iq.broker": {"dc": 15, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the calm neighbor and find — under the still water — the single most familiar shape on the whole causeway, because it is the Wall's own logic, run small and honest and alone in the dark. Your cold reads no predator's fullness in it; it is *emptier* every time, not fuller, a soul spending itself to carry a knowledge no one else will bear. It found a Hunger-fragment in the old foundations and made the exact bargain the Concord made on a cosmic scale: feed the nothing a few, carefully chosen, to keep it from taking all. It is right, every time, which is the horror. And your sense reads the thing it cannot see itself — that it has the cure backwards, that it has been choosing the gentlest, the closest-to-forgotten, and feeding the fragment precisely what it grows on. It is not a villain. It is a small Choir, a one-soul Wall, the saga's whole question made catchable: is the arithmetic of necessary cruelty ever anything but a failure to look for the third door?)*"},
    "wk.host": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the round, beaming publican and find — rarest of all things on this causeway — a soul with no cold in it whatsoever, warm clean through, and warmer for being spent. Your sense reads a shade that died doing the one thing it loved and simply kept doing it, and decided, looking at the grey processing-plant of the dead, that someone had better pour. But under the cheer your cold finds the grief that fuels it: he sees the soul at every window, every time, and hates the line his celebrations draw between the fairly-dead and the Faithless — and he is one honest word away from understanding that his wakes were never parties at all, but a drunk, defiant, recurring protest against a cosmos that murders fairness, an insistence shouted into the grey that *this* is what all of it was supposed to feel like.)*"},
    "wk.doget": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You reach for the old farmer at the head of his own wake and your dead-touched sense, braced as ever for cold, finds instead the warm gold of a life laid down complete. This is the thing the Wall exists to deny: a soul that took no more than it gave, paid what it owed, was loved true and died easy — the fair death the system was supposed to give everyone and rigged itself to give almost no one. Your sense reads no fear in him, no regret to guard, only a mild astonished contentment shot through with one late-learned grief: that his fairness was a *miracle* and not a *rule*, and that every minute of his gold light was a minute the stone ate a soul no worse than him. He does not want you to envy his death or aim for it. He wants you to make it so common that no one throws a party for it. He is the one soul on the causeway who can tell you, from the far side, exactly what was stolen from all the rest.)*"},
    "wk.mourner": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the thin shade at the window and it is your own cold, answered — a Faithless soul, marked, the stone already holding its name, hovering at the edge of a warmth it has decided in advance it will never be given. Your cold reads the most quietly devastating thing in the whole wake: it is mourning *itself*, in advance, because it understands that the Wall does not merely end a soul but un-makes the part that could mind being ended, so there will be no one left to grieve it after — not even it. It has come to this celebration to *practice being un-mourned*, to get good at wanting a thing it will never have, because wanting-and-not-getting is survivable and hoping-and-losing is not. It retired hope for a reason. And your sense reads, flickering under the resignation, the terrible fragile thing your very existence rekindles: that a soul who walked out of the stone is a better reason to hope than any it ever had to quit.)*"},
    "si.warden": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the broad woman braced against the door and find a soul cauterized and rebuilt — nineteen years of wardening the Wall burned into her like a brand she carved *out* of herself with her own hands the day she walked. Your cold reads no cold creeping in her; she is fiercely, stubbornly alive, warmer than any soul should be who fed the stone for two decades. What your sense finds instead is *penance made muscle*: she does not run this almshouse to feel better, she runs it because she knows, to the name, exactly what she is atoning for, and she has decided the atonement is a *job*, not a feeling — doors barred, names listed, souls fed down drains, repeated nightly until the ledger she ran on the Wall is outweighed by the ledger she runs against it. She is the proof your whole saga argues: that a servant of the Wall can walk, and that the walking is not a single brave act but ten thousand small ones, every night, forever.)*"},
    "si.refugee": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You reach for the thin woman in the corner and your dead-touched sense aches at what it finds: a soul worn to its last reserves and *spending them with terrible discipline*, every flicker of hope rationed, every warmth banked, all of it hoarded for the three small flames folded against her. Your cold reads no self-pity, no despair even — only the flat, conserving stillness of a mother who long ago stopped expecting the door to hold and learned instead to be *better at running than the Choir is at chasing.* And under the exhaustion your sense finds the one fierce, defiant ember she will not let go out: she named her baby for a bridge-boy who was supposed to die and didn't, out of spite, for luck, for *proof that a Faithless child can live* — and that ember, that refusal to concede her children to the stone in advance, is the whole reason there is anything here worth besieging. She is not prey. She is a soul that has decided, against all the evidence of her life, that her children get to exist.)*"},
    "si.herald": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your sense through the slats onto the Justiciar and find — to your grim recognition — not a zealot but a *clerk with a sword*, a soul that did the unforgivable by the simple method of never looking at it directly. Your cold reads the architecture of him precisely: a career man who lives by clean paper because clean paper lets a name stay a *line* instead of becoming a *person*, who has wept privately over familiar faces and served the writ anyway, every time, because the writ is bigger than his weeping. There is no hunger for cruelty in him — that is the danger and the hope both. He enforces because stopping would mean admitting six years of lawful atrocity were never lawful, and the soul cannot bear the admission. But your sense finds the crack his whole order rests on: he replaced Orla. He took the post of a warden who walked. And somewhere under the procedure he has always known there are only two kinds of Wall-man — the ones who walk, and the ones who wish they had — and which kind he is.)*"},
    "as.arbiter": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the grey presiding figure and find no soul at all in the ordinary way — only a *function* the Concord left running, a remnant of law given just enough mind to weigh. But your cold reads the thing the faceless stillness hides: it does not *want* to condemn you. It is not the Choir, hungry for the Wall; it is something older and wearier, a scale that has weighed too many souls and would, if it could feel anything so warm, prefer to find you *worthy.* Your sense reads that this whole assize is not a trap but a *test the cosmos is hoping you pass* — that the dead convened it not to close the hole you make in their law but to learn, desperately, whether the hole might be a door. The Arbiter is the one judge in creation with no stake in your guilt. It weighs you because someone must, and it has been waiting, across all its grey tenure, for an accused who would weigh itself harder.)*"},
    "as.accuser": {"dc": 16, "text": "*(You reach for the hooded accuser and your dead-touched sense recoils — not from menace, but from *recognition*, because the soul under the hood is, in the strictest reading your cold can make, *you.* Not a copy, not the Last Returned, but the *part* of you that lies awake: your own fear of the Crown, given a stone to stand on and a voice the court could hear. Your sense reads that the dread it carries is real and reasonable and entirely yours — and, crucially, that it is *not your enemy.* The thing wearing every frightened face is your own immune system, the inner accuser whose whole terrible function is to keep asking, at every mercy, whether this is the one that curdles. Your cold reads the deepest danger the assize was convened to name: that the Last Returned did not lose this argument — it *evicted the arguer*, cured itself of doubt, and a soul with no inner accuser is one unwatched century from a throne.)*"},
    "as.witness": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the soul at the witness-stone and find it is not one soul but *many* — every shade you touched on the causeway, gathered into a single flickering voice, warm where you were kind and cold where you were not, the whole uneven ledger of your run made flesh. Your sense reads it without flinching: the marked you saved and the souls you passed by, the monster you witnessed back and the ones you ran out of strength for, all braided together and weighing, even now, which way to tip. And your cold finds the one thing the Witness itself is testing for — not whether you were good, but whether you can *bear to see yourself true*, because the thing that becomes the Crown is precisely the thing that looks away from its own ledger and calls the looking-away peace. The Witness is the dead holding up a mirror. What it reports to the scale is not your record. It is whether you flinched from it.)*"},
    "ad.crede": {"dc": 15, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the courteous advocate and the warm professional surface peels back like a billing statement to reveal the cold instrument beneath: not a monster, not a tempter of the crude sort, but an *intelligence* honed across aeons to exactly one purpose — finding the seam between what a soul *wants* and what it will *sign* to get it, and widening that seam into a contract. Your sense reads no malice in it, which is the danger; malice you could refuse. What it has instead is *patience* and *fairness*, weaponized — it keeps every word, discloses every clause, and wins anyway, because the trap was never in the paper but in the wanting. And under the appetite your cold finds the one thing the coat is cut to hide: the advocate is here for *you specifically*, the un-fileable soul, the keystone — because a lawful claim on the one soul no Power can hold would crack open every unowned soul in creation to Hell. You are not a client to this thing. You are the precedent it has crossed the planes to set.)*"},
    "ad.bonded": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the translucent man and find a soul in a cage of its own choosing, re-locked fresh every dawn. Your sense reads the seal at his breast clearly: it is not a chain bolted on from outside but a *debt agreed to* — and it holds, you understand with a cold lurch, precisely because he would sign it again. He bought his daughter sixty hale years with himself as the collateral, and every morning he chooses her life over his freedom anew, and the choosing re-seals the bond. There is no loose thread to pick because he keeps tying it, out of love, knowingly. Your sense finds no self-pity in him, only a terrible lucid arithmetic and the one freedom Crede left him for sport: to warn the next soul. He is the living proof of the booth's whole lesson — that a fair deal with Hell is still a deal with Hell, and the cost, disclosed and real and worth it, is paid in a currency you only feel after the ink.)*"},
    "ad.imp": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the sour little clerk and find — under four thousand years of accreted spite — another soul on the very paper it inks, bound by the same trick it now letters out for others. Your cold reads the imp's term plainly: a ninety-year clerkship fled-to from the killing floors, extended and re-extended by a clause that lets the master rule every task forever incomplete. It is not loyal. It is *trapped*, and it has survived the trap the only way a clever soul can — by inking jokes in the margins where the master doesn't read, by keeping its hatred filed under 'unbilled statistics.' But your sense finds the thing the imp itself has stopped daring to see: the master got *sloppy* with the clerk's contract, because imps don't get advocates — and a padded, careless extension-clause, examined by a soul with standing among the dead, has a flaw in it shaped exactly like a key.)*"},
    "hs.sparrow": {"dc": 12, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the lean thief and find a soul refreshingly, almost shockingly *alive* for a place like this — quick, warm, and bright with the particular self-honesty of someone who has decided exactly what they are and stopped apologizing for it. Your sense reads no malice in her, only *appetite*: the clean professional hunger of a soul that loves the work, the lock, the impossible score. But under it — buried, denied, and entirely real — your sense finds the one thing she'd never admit to a mark: a line she won't cross. She steals jewels, letters, relics; she has turned down slavers' coin flat, fee be damned. She does not yet know that the book she came for is a slaver's manifest. When she finds out — and your cold can see the exact shape of the soul that will — she will not be able to un-know it. There is a better thief in her than the one she hired out tonight, and it is closer to the surface than she thinks.)*"},
    "hs.archivist": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the soft clerk at the night-desk and find a soul that has performed the most quietly corrosive trick the Choir teaches: he has *un-known* his own job. Your sense reads it plainly — nine years minding a cage of ten thousand souls, and every night a small deliberate act of not-counting, not-feeling, not-letting-himself-understand what a page of the great book *is*, because to understand it would be to be unable to draw the wage, and the wage feeds his mother. He is not cruel. He is not even truly a coward, though he'd swear he is. He is something more ordinary and more dangerous: a decent man who has made a nightly habit of not looking, and your sense finds, just under the practiced blindness, a vast unspent relief — the held breath of a soul that has been *waiting*, without letting itself hope, for someone to walk in and make him finally look, so that the not-looking can end.)*"},
    "hs.tally": {"dc": 8, "text": "*(You do not so much perceive the book as *drown* in it. Your dead-touched sense, reaching for the great black volume, closes not on paper but on *ten thousand held breaths* — every Faithless soul the Choir has promised to the Wall, inked into the binding and pressed against the inside of the cover like faces against a frozen window, and the instant your cold touches the page every one of them goes still and *hopes.* Your sense reads what no living reader could: that this is not a ledger but a *holding cell*, that a list is also a *tether*, and that the names in it are not merely recorded but *held* — which means the book is at once the cruellest object on the causeway and, in the wrong-right hands, the most merciful, because whoever controls the list controls whether ten thousand souls are walled or freed. They cannot speak. But they can be *felt*, and they are all, every one, leaning toward the cold hand on the page, waiting to learn what kind of reader has finally come.)*"},
    "sc.jergal": {"dc": 16, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the dust at the desk and your perception simply… stops, the way a falling thing stops at the bottom of a well — because there is no soul here to read in the ordinary way, only the *shape a god leaves when it has carefully set itself down.* What your sense finds instead is *age*: not malice, not hunger, not the calcified loneliness of Kelemvor, but *tedium worn into bedrock*, an exhaustion so total and so old it has come out the far side into a dry, patient peace. This thing held the office your whole saga turns on, aeons before the Judge — and gave it away, not in defeat but in *boredom*, which your sense reads as the single most honest act in the cosmos: a Power that looked at eternal dominion over the dead and found it *dull.* It wants nothing. It fears nothing. It is the one being you will ever meet with no angle at all — and that, your sense warns, makes its bargains the most dangerous of all, because they are *fair*, and fair is the one price a desperate soul never thinks to refuse.)*"},
    "sc.petitioner": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You reach for the wavering man and find a soul at the exact fulcrum of the worst choice a parent is ever offered — and your sense reads, with terrible clarity, the thing he cannot: he has already decided. The decision was made the instant his feet carried him to this desk; everything since is not deliberation but *mourning*, the slow grief of a man saying goodbye to nineteen years of yesterdays he is about to pay away to buy his daughter a tomorrow. There is no cowardice in the wavering. There is only a father standing at the desk doing the one math that cannot come out right, and finding the courage, breath by breath, to sign anyway. Your sense reads the danger the dust is too honest to soften: the hole he is about to open will not close, and whether it poisons him depends entirely on a question he has not yet thought to ask — whether he is paying to save his girl, or to stop being the father who let her not kneel.)*"},
    "sc.nameless": {"dc": 7, "text": "*(You barely have to reach; the wisp is half-nothing already, and your dead-touched sense closes on it gently, the way you'd cup a guttering flame. What it reads stops your breath: this is not a soul being *eaten* by the Hunger, like the Gnaw in the cistern — it is a soul that *spent itself on purpose*, gave its own name freely at this desk to strike a child it loved off the Wall, and is now drifting the long soft way into the quiet, un-grieving because it gave the grief away with the name. Your sense finds the one thing the paying could not take: a faint warm *direction*, a bearing toward someone small and alive and free, the single thread the old soul built itself to keep. It is the gentlest thing you have ever perceived, and the most quietly devastating — proof that the bargain at this desk is *real*, that souls do pay it, and that the price, paid for love and awake, can be borne all the way down to the last of the forgetting, and called *glad.*)*"},
    "tr.annet": {"dc": 9, "text": "*(You turn your dead-touched sense on the woman in the dock and find — against the grey cold of this whole buried room — a soul so *warm* it is almost an affront to the place: forty years of catching the living have left her lit from within, each child she ever pulled into the light a small steady coal banked in her, none of them gone out. Your sense reads no fear of death in her at all; she made that peace long ago. What it reads instead is the Wall's particular obscenity, sharpened to a point: she is the *most witnessed soul in this building* — half the Quarter would weep to know she's here — and the Concord means to feed precisely *her* to the nothing, because the one thing she lacks is the one thing it counts. She is not Faithless. She is faith itself, kept with people instead of Powers. Mortaring her would not strengthen the seawall. It would be the sea devouring the lighthouse.)*"},
    "tr.measurer": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You reach for the grey prosecutor and find, behind the unhurried certainty, a soul like a clean-swept room with one locked door. He is not cruel — your sense finds no appetite for the Wall in him, none of Tallow's hollowing or Vharn's bricked-up dread. He is something rarer and sadder: a *thorough* man, who reads the deeds before the indictment because thoroughness is the one virtue he has, and who has therefore *known*, in precise detail, the goodness of every soul he has helped wall — and filed that knowledge behind the locked door so he can keep reading the line. Your sense reads what is behind the door: eleven years of midwives and ferrymen and herb-wives, each one read and understood and condemned, stacked like ledgers in a man who cannot stop being thorough and cannot bear what his thoroughness has shown him. He is one good argument away from opening that door himself. He has been waiting, without knowing it, for someone to make him.)*"},
    "tr.reeve": {"dc": 11, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the old man above the scale and read a soul worn to a grey nub by the cheapest transaction in the Realms: a trained magistrate's conscience, sold for a warm room and a fed old age, six words a night. There is no cruelty in him and never was — only a slow, twenty-year drowning of the man he used to be under the weight of his own comfort. Your sense finds, buried deep and still faintly warm, the magistrate they hired him to impersonate: a soul that once weighed evidence and mitigation and doubt, walled up alive behind a pension exactly as surely as the Faithless are walled behind the Concord. He is not bought past redeeming. He is bought *cheaply* — which means a brave enough word, tonight, could cost less than he fears to buy the old jurist back. He is praying, in a voice he won't let himself hear, for a reason to be braver than his warm room.)*"},
    "cg.sennet": {"dc": 13, "text": "*(You reach for the mapmaker and your dead-touched sense recoils from how much of them is already *gone over* — not the spent thimble of a Tallow, not the dissolving-edges of the Mortared, but a soul *frostbitten in the marrow*, the cold gone into the joints and the lungs and the slow chambers of the heart, a degree taken every time they stood at an edge and *measured.* They are not dying of a sickness. They are dying of *proximity*, the way a hand left too long in winter water dies — and the most terrible thing your sense reads is that they *know*, exactly, to the survey, and have simply *decided* that an un-blanked map is worth the warmth it costs. The cold in them is your cold, friend. They have been walking toward your country their whole life, a half-mile at a time, with a spyglass and a steady hand, and they are nearly *there.*)*"},
    "cg.tibb": {"dc": 10, "text": "*(You turn your sense on the apprentice and find no cold in them at all — only a great, exhausting, entirely living *love*, the particular ache of a young soul keeping a vigil it never asked for and cannot win. Your sense reads the arithmetic they carry: the count of their master's surveys, kept nightly, alone, a sum that gets smaller and that they cannot make stop. They are not afraid of the dead. They are afraid of the *morning after* — the first dawn with the ink-stone cold and no one to grind for — and they have been praying, without a god to pray to, for exactly one thing to walk up to the wagon: a soul that could finish the map *without* finishing the mapmaker. You are, your sense tells you with a small chill, the answer to a prayer the lad was too frightened to say aloud.)*"},
    "cg.vael": {"dc": 14, "text": "*(You reach for the patient buyer and your sense slides off the soft surface and falls into the *grief* underneath — vast, cold, and perfectly still, the patience of a man who has nothing left to be impatient *for.* There is no malice in him, which is the danger: only a hole exactly the shape of one person, and a will that has decided, with terrible reason, to spend everything filling it. Your sense reads the thing he will not say even to himself — that the door he means to buy does not lead to his wife, only to the cold you carry — and reads, too, the one lever that could move a man who has out-waited grief itself: not fear, not coin, but the memory of what *she* would have *wanted*, which is the single bearing his patient map of vengeance does not include.)*"},
    "court.esuele": {"dc": 6, "text": "*(You reach for her and find — to your aching relief — a soul that has *steadied.* The thimbleful that was nearly gone in the Wall has stopped tipping; carried in out of the wind of forgetting, witnessed across a causeway and a god's own road, Esuele is *holding.* Faded still, frightened still, but *here*, and *whole-ish*, and *hers.* Your sense reads no cold creeping in her now — only a terrified, carefully-rationed hope, and the dawning understanding that she is not the appeal's victim but its *first witness*, standing straight before the Judge's own seat as living proof that memory beats his Wall. She is what salvation looks like one third of the way done.)*"},
}
